<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Terrorist 1stLd-Writethru   05-22 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Terrorist, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0809,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Says Bomb Maker Eyed in Pan AM Flight 103 Case Is Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `A spokesman...' with two grafs to UPDATE with
officials quoted as confirming report. Pick up 5th pvs, ``He has...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magazine reported Monday that a
bomb maker for a Palestinian group suspected in the Pan Am Flight
103 bombing was freed 15 days after his arrest in West Germany
because he works for the country's intelligence service.
   Stern magazine said Marwan Khreesat, 44, was arrested in October
after raids in Neuss and in Frankfurt, but was allowed to go free
the following month and returned to Jordan, where he was born.
   ``Five weeks later, a radio bomb of the type that Khreesat had
built in Neuss blew up in the Pan Am jet over Lockerbie,'' the
Hamburg-based publication said.
   The New York Times, in Tuesday's editions, quoted unidentified
U.S. officials in Washington as confirming the report.
   But a spokesman for the intelligence agency,
Bundesnachrichtendienst, or BND, denied the report, saying of
Khreesat:
   ``He has never been an agent for BND and he is not one now.''
   The spokesman declined to discuss other aspects of the report.
He spoke on the condition of not being identified.
   A spokesman for the chief federal prosecutor's office said
Khreesat was released because investigators could not find enough
evidence to hold him.
   Khreesat is believed to be the bomb maker for the Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, or PFLP-GC, Stern
said.
   British, U.S., and West German news reports have mentioned the
Syrian-based group as a prime suspect in the bombing of New
York-bound Pan Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21. All
259 people on board and 11 on the ground were killed.
   Stern said its report was based on information provided by two
high-ranking security officials it did not identify.
   It said Khreesat was among 16 suspected Palestinian terrorists
arrested in West Germany in October. Police seized large quantities
of weapons and explosives in the raids, including a bomb-rigged
radio cassette recorder.
   A similar device is believed by British investigators to have
caused the Pan Am explosion.
   Stern said Khreesat was responsible for making ``radio bombs for
attacks on planes'' for PFLP-GC.
   West German officials say they have no evidence linking PFLP-GC
members arrested in West Germany to the Pan Am bombing.
   Only two of the 16 arrested in October remain in custody.
   Stern said its report is to appear in Wednesday's editions of
the magazine. The publication released the report in advance to
other news media on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
