<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 0029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-22 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO GRANDE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fearless fowl named Judy refused to be
cooped up following a record-setting flight at the 18th annual
International Chicken Flying Contest.
   Judy flew 542 feet, 9 inches Saturday to win the contest at the
Bob Evans Farm in southeast Ohio. Her flight shattered the
10-year-old mark of 302 feet, 8 inches and won $1,100 for her
owner, John Salyers.
   But Salyers was unable to bring Judy to the trophy stand to
share in the award ceremony. During her flight, Judy swept over the
flying course, an adjacent field, and so far into the nearby woods
that Salyers was unable to find her.
   ``I lose one or two every year that way,'' said Salyers, who has
entered chickens in the meet for nine years. ``Two years ago, I had
the longest flier here and I never did find that chicken.''
   The rest of the 228 contestants were not as anxious to flout the
law of gravity.
   The average chicken entered the mail-box launching chute,
flapped its wings hysterically and settled on the ground a few feet
away.
   Salyers said he had no secret for training flying chickens.
   ``I don't mistreat them,'' he said. ``They're pretty wild. I
just go out and say, `Shoo!' That scares them, I guess, and they
take off. But there's no training a chicken so you'll know which
one will fly and which won't.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW STRAITSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal revenuers have taken the
moonshine out of the New Straitsville Moonshine Festival.
   The New Straitsville Betterment Association had a temporary
permit from the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to
make moonshine whiskey for the last seven festivals, but that has
been lifted.
   ``The bureau says they can't legally give us a permit to make
moonshine when they're trying to stop it,'' said Kenny Burgess Jr.,
secretary of the association.
   The 19th annual festival runs Wednesday through Monday in New
Straitsville, a south-central Ohio community which for years called
itself the moonshine capital of the world.
   Of the 47 stills smashed by federal revenuers in the 1930s in
Perry County, 32 were in or around New Straitsville, Burgess said.
   Festival organizer Betty St. Clair said she needed permission
from the bureau just to make the mash, a concoction of cracked
corn, sugar, yeast and water that is run through the still.
   ``I think it's silly. There are no free samples,'' she said of
the decision to halt the moonshine.
   Ms. St. Clair remembers being asked by a policeman where she was
from during a trip to the 1934 World's Fair in Chicago.
   ```New Straitsville?' he said. `Oh, you're from down there where
they make that good moonshine,''' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
