<DOCNO> AP890522-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 0035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ClassroomTV     05-22 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Classroom TV,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Classroom TV: It Isn't Just The Commercials</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Tennessee-based Whittle Communications
started beaming a news program with commercials into six high
schools last winter, educators were outraged.
   This spring, when Ted Turner and the Discovery Channel each
promised schools commercial-free cable news and documentary
programming, many of those same people applauded.
   Those reactions left the impression that the presence or absence
of Snickers or blue jeans ads was the only concern school officials
have about classroom TV programmming.
   But there are other issues.
   One is time, ``a school's most precious commodity,'' said Ernest
L. Boyer, president of the Carnegie Endowment for the Advancement
of Teaching.
   Hardly a week passes that some study doesn't demand that public
schools raise test scores and teach more math, or science, or art,
or values, or safe sex _ all of this, presumably, to be shoehorned
into the same 180-day school year.
   The 12-minute-a-day Channel One news show that Whittle offers is
the equivalent of six classroom days a year, one of which would be
commercials alone.
   Manya Ungar, president of the National PTA, and others say that
because classroom time is so precious, educators should be sure
that TV programs support, rather than supplant, the curriculum.
   ``If there are ways to provide this technology when, where and
how the teacher feels it best enhances instruction, discussion and
comprehension, then it is to be applauded,'' Ungar said. ``If it
doesn't, it's a detriment.''
   Few educators outright oppose classroom TV. Nearly two-thirds of
all school districts now have some link to cable programming,
according to a National School Boards Association survey.
   But television has inherent shortcomings as an educational
technology, many still believe, especially compared to
microcomputers.
   ``Television is not the preferred technology in most
instances,'' said Scott Thomson, executive director of the National
Association of Secondary School Principals. ``It has a cost
advantage over film.
   ``But microcomputers are far more powerful educationally than
television because they are individualized and they are interactive.
   ``Unfortunately,'' he continued, ``the public thinks we are
against technology when we say we're not that impressed with
television. But in many ways it is outdated. Research shows it is
not that effective.''
   At least some of these problems can be overcome.
   Kentucky won praise this school year when it financed the
nation's first statewide educational satellite system. Public TV
station KET's ``Star Channels'' features hardware that allows
students all over the state to communicate with a televised teacher
at the touch of a button.
   The announcement last week of ``Assignment: Discovery,'' to
debut Sept. 18, followed Turner's announcement that his Cable News
Network will begin running a 15-minute current events show called
``CNN Newsroom'' on Aug. 14.
   The Discovery Channel's proposed classroom TV offering is
getting favorable early notices.
   Teachers would be free to tape Discovery programs and use them
when and however they see fit.
   Discovery Channel's forte is documentaries, and school officials
said they were excited at the prospect of supplementing lessons
with clips that would bring history alive in the classroom as no
textbook could.
   ``In a social studies class, I can imagine a teacher saying, `I
want you to watch John F. Kennedy give his `Ich Bein Ein Berliner'
speech,'' said Gary Marx, a spokesman for the American Association
of School Administrators.
   The group has blasted Whittle's commercial Channel One, but has
praised Discovery Channel.
   But the debate over classroom commercials masks another
fundamental issue: the decadeslong failure of government and
educational systems to harness technology to enhance student
achievement.
   In effect, commercial broadcasters like Whittle are being blamed
for stepping into that void and wanting to make a profit. And the
school officials pointing accusing fingers at Christopher Whittle
for his commercials are the very ones who have largely escaped
blame for doing little about the technology void that private
entrepreneurs now seek to fill.
   ``I think it's a scandal that we're so far into these
technologies and yet they remain so unconnected with schools,''
said Boyer. ``Education is still standing in the wings, lamenting
its abuses.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Mitgang has covered education for the AP
since 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
