<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 0106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Proxmire Bjt   05-22 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Proxmire, Bjt,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Proxmire Still Moving Fast After Senate Career</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The platform of the Washington subway station
is crowded and former Sen. William Proxmire is striding so rapidly
through the cavernous space that he could almost be said to be
running.
   Flashing lights and a far-away rumble signal the approach of a
train.
   Proxmire is out of position. He moves from a rapid walk to a
dash, darting inside a car just before the doors close with an
automated whoosh.
   It's not an isolated event. It's a routine.
   ``I pace up and down carrying a heavy brief case,'' the
73-year-old Wisconsin Democrat says. ``I do a sprint right at the
very end.''
   Proxmire was once the country's most celebrated long-distance
amateur runner.
   For decades he ran flat out _ ``I never jogged'' _ the five
miles between his home in Cleveland park in Northwest Washington
and his Senate office on Capitol Hill.
   ``I can't do that anymore,'' he says. ``I've got a bum knee.''
   So he exercises, rides his stationary bike, and strides the
length of lengthy subway platforms.
   ``One great heart specialist says the secret is that you've got
to keep moving, got to keep moving,'' the former senator says.
   On this particular day, like most days, Proxmire goes to work in
a tiny cubicle attached to the Robert M. LaFollette Sr,
Congressional Reading Room in the Library of Congress.
   The room has a special significance for him.
   He held LaFollette's seat in the United States Senate for 31
years, ever since he won a special election to replace the late
Sen. Joseph R. McCarthy in 1957.
   The cubicle is equipped with a chair, bookshelves, a telephone
and typewriter. It is not equipped with a view. A computer terminal
is expected soon.
   Not much room, not much equipment, for a man who until last
December commanded a large office suite in the Dirksen Senate
Office Building and a personal and committee staff of dozens.
   ``When you're in the Congress you really get support,'' Proxmire
says. ``I loved the Senate, but I don't very much miss it.''
   ``What I do miss is the clerical staff, the secretarial support,
the schedulers, the researchers.''
   In retirement, Proxmire is pretty much of a one-man band, with
an occasional boost now and then from former staff members. He does
his own typing.
   And he is gingerly returning to what he calls ``my first love,
journalism.''
   An early job, in 1949, was as a reporter with the Capitol Times
in Madison, Wis. He was fired after a series of run-ins with
management.
   But now he's back.
   Proxmire is launching a twice-a-week newspaper column under the
auspices of United Features Syndicate. He says that one of the 40
or 50 subscribers signed up so far is The Capitol Times.
   Proxmire launched his column last week with a news conference at
the National Press Club in which he resurrected his Golden Fleece
Award, perhaps the most successful political public relations
device of its era.
   The Fleece will be a monthly feature of the Proxmire column,
carrying on a tradition that, beginning in March 1975, continued
for 165 consecutive months with citations for what Proxmire
considered examples of conspicuous government waste, and an
occasional award of merit for a positive action that saved money or
spent it well.
   ``Just because I'm out of the Senate doesn't mean we have to
abandon a device that does something to cut down spending in this
time of fearful budget deficits,'' Proxmire says.
   Proxmire also is planning a book.
   Subject: debt, government debt, business debt, household debt.
   Proxmire, former chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, has
been predicting a sharp recession for years: ``I think when the
recession comes it's likely to be a real killer, a depression _ and
that is because our debt is so enormous.''
   He has been working up to the book by using debt as the theme of
dozens of speeches around the country.
   At the press club news conference, Proxmire was asked if he, as
a former Banking Committee chairman, had ever considered giving
himself a Golden Fleece for failing to spot and stop the pattern of
abuses that grew into the multibillion-dollar savings and loan
scandal.
   There were so many mistakes by so many people ``that you'd have
to have a barrel of fleeces, including one for the chairman of the
Senate Banking Committee,'' he replied.
   ``I'll let other people give me a fleece, rather than commit
suicide,'' Proxmire said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence L. Knutson covers Congress for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
