<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     05-22 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Remains In Very Critical Condition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Marcos Exile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family and friends of Ferdinand Marcos were
heartened by news that the former Philippines president was alert
and responding to medication, an aide said.
   Marcos continued to rally on Sunday, said a spokesman for St.
Francis Medical Center, stressing that his condition remained very
critical.
   Marcos, 71, was undergoing kidney dialysis, had a respirator to
help him breathe and was hooked up to a monitoring system, said
Eugene Tiwanak, the hospital's assistant adminstrator.
   Arturo Aruiza, a top aide who has been with Marcos much of the
time since a surgical procedure was performed Thursday to prepare
him for dialysis, said Marcos has shown the will to live.
   ``The will to fight, the determination, he has that,'' Aruiza
said.
   Marcos is able to mouth words to his doctors and family, and
responds with a smile when his wife, Imelda, and children, Irene
Araneta and Ferdinand Jr., hold his hand and speak to him, Aruiza
said.
   Marcos was alert and conscious and seemed to be responding to
medication to fight a bacterial infection, Tiwanak said. But he
added:
   ``I didn't say he improved. I said his condition is such that he
appears to be rallying, but I'm cautioning always that it's very
episodic and can drop _ just as I'm standing here, it can get
worse.''
   Marcos still has a fever, but not as high as a few days ago,
Tiwanak said.
   Aruiza said cautious optimism had replaced some of the despair
that prevailed Thursday.
   ``Even the hospital wanted to know our arrangements for the body
then,'' Aruiza said. ``They said their morgue could only keep a
body for a certain number of days. It was very morbid.''
   Marcos and his wife have lived in exile in Hawaii since fleeing
the Philippines in February 1986 after a civilian revolution swept
Corazon Aquino to power.
</TEXT>
