<FIRST>r a PM-Bush'sSister     05-22 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush's Sister,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Bush's Sister Suffers Minor Mishap on the Way Graduation
Ceremony</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's sister injured three police
officers in a minor car accident en route to hear her brother speak
at Boston University's commencement.
   The officers had been directing Nancy Bush Ellis to a parking
area Sunday morning near the campus where 30,000 graduates and
their families were gathering to hear Bush and French President
Francois Mitterrand deliver the keynote addresses.
   Mrs. Ellis stopped to talk to the officers after she encountered
a roadblock. She put the car in reverse and the car suddenly
lurched backward and struck the officers, police said.
   ``One officer was hit in the knee with the car's fender, another
was hit by the door as it flung open, and a third was swept back
about 10 feet by the door itself,'' said Linda Orlando, a police
spokeswoman.
   Mrs. Ellis' Audi sedan then bashed into a police truck stationed
at the roadblock, Orlando said.
   Two of the officers sustained minor cuts and bruises and the one
who was swept back 10 feet sustained minor head and neck injuries,
Orlando said. All three men were treated at a hospital and released.
   Investigating officers reported there was no apparent negligence
on the part of Mrs. Ellis and no charges were filed, Orlando said.
   ``All's well that ends well, so to speak,'' she said.
   Mrs. Ellis did not answer a message left on the telephone
answering machine at her suburban Boston home.
</TEXT>
