<FIRST>r a PM-BushCommencement     05-22 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Commencement,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush-Mitterrand A Mixed Blessing for BU Graduates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They may have been just yards from two world
leaders, but many graduating seniors were less than awestruck
during Boston University's 116th commencement.
   The presence of President Bush and France's President Francois
Mitterrand at Sunday's graduation caused a mixed reaction among the
roughly 5,400 graduates.
   ``We had to throw away the champagne bottles,'' said graduating
senior Dave Wheeler, 21, who received a degree in political
science. ``But I guess it is worth the trade-off if it means having
the president here.''
   Mary Hansel, 22, a graduating senior from Rochester, N.Y., said
some in her class thought Bush and Mitterrand would overshadow them.
   ``Some of the people fear it takes away from us,'' Hansel said.
``But mostly it is exciting. Most people can't believe we are
here.''
   But if some students were ambivalent about the extraordinary
pomp and circumstance surrounding their graduation, many of the
more than 30,000 alumni, friends and relatives in the packed
audience were thrilled.
   Some, like Saul Holtzman, 72, a member of the class of 1939,
came from Albuquerque, N.M., for the ceremony.
   ``It's great _ really exciting,'' said Holtzman, sitting with
other members of the 50th reunion class on Nickerson Field, which
was festooned with French flags. ``It's a lot different from 50
years ago. (Republican presidential candidate) Alf Landon was our
speaker then.''
   Adel Anbar, 23, a graduating senior, said his parents traveled
from the small Persian Gulf nation of Qatar when they heard that
Bush and Mitterrand were the featured speakers.
   ``It was a good reason for my parents to come,'' said Anbar.
   Bush and Mitterrand, and their wives, Barbara Bush and Danielle
Mitterrand, were welcomed with applause and cheers.
   The heartiest and most surprising reception was reserved for
Democratic Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, who has been under siege since
his failed presidential campaign for the state's fiscal crisis.
   Some of the students wore peace symbols on their gowns and the
words, ``Bush Knew'' on their mortar boards. A few held up protest
signs when Bush began his address.
   ``I'm wearing this because Bush knew about the Contras but went
ahead and made Oliver North the scapegoat,'' said Claire Connelly,
22, a graduating senior from south Boston. ``It's an imperialist
presidency and Bush shouldn't be here.''
   Another group of demonstrators handed out leaflets outside the
stadium, protesting Bush administration policies.
   But most of the students, a number of them holding tiny French
and U.S. flags, said they were pleased with the commencement. They
often interrupted Mitterrand's speech, cheering the French
president's exhortations for a better environment when he said,
``The earth is our planet, let us save it.''
   Wheeler, who will be attending law school, said most students
were glad Bush attended the graduation.
   ``We're all pretty bourgeois,'' he said.
</TEXT>
