<FIRST>r a PM-High-RiseDemolition     05-22 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Rise Demolition,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Building Not Budging Despite Demolition Attempts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folks in these parts don't have to go
all the way to Pisa to see the Leaning Tower after a stubborn
high-rise refused to collapse despite two demolition blasts.
   ``We've got one building leaning and one building leaning
against it,'' Police Maj. John Power said Sunday. ``It's a
hazardous condition and I don't know what could happen.''
   A cloud of smoke rose from the bottom of the 10-story building
about 8:30 a.m., but the structure remained standing. Patrolman
John Egan said demolition crews were unsure why the implosion
failed to work.
   The demolition experts, who had used 500 pounds of dynamite in
the first implosion, fetched 36 pounds of more explosives for the
second try. This time, part of the building tipped slightly and
leaned against another tower, but the structure remained standing.
   Power said a few families living nearby would have to find
somewhere else to stay until the building was brought down.
Residents without a place to go would be accommodated, officials
said.
   Stephen O'Rourke, head of the city's housing authority, said it
could take two weeks for the wrecking crews to dismantle the
listing building.
   The Providence Housing Authority had planned to tear down the
complex and build smaller buildings for housing. City officials
felt that tearing down the deteriorating towers would be cheaper
than renovation.
   The tower and two others are the subject of a federal suit filed
by Project BASIC, a housing advocacy group, against the housing
authority. U.S. District Judge Raymond Pettine allowed the tower to
be demolished after architects ruled that the building, when being
prepared for demolition, was made unsafe.
</TEXT>
