<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-22 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Hits 19-Month High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massive dollar buying, spurred partly by unrest in
China, pushed the U.S. currency to a 19-month high today, while
stock prices gained moderately.
   The dollar's closing of 140.45 yen, up 1.68 yen from Friday's
close of 138.77 yen, marked the first time the dollar had closed
above 140 yen since Oct. 28, 1987.
   The dollar opened at 139.37 and ranged between 139.35 yen and
140.65 yen in heavy trading. With only a slight pause last Friday,
it has climbed 6.01 yen since May 11.
   Dealers said dollar buying also was encouraged by the dollar's
continued rise despite intervention by the Bank of Japan. The
central bank sold an estimated $2 billion.
   ``The unrest in Beijing was the direct motivation for the dollar
buying,'' said a dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Dealers also mentioned political uncertainty in Japan, where the
ruling party has been unable so far to find a successor for Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, who is resigning over an
influence-peddling scandal.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 144.65-point gainer on Friday, added another
65.90 points, or 0.19 percent, closing at 34,067.86.
   Securities dealers said many investors were waiting on the
sidelines to watch developments in exchange rates and in the
domestic political situation.
   Trade volume in the first section was estimated at 550 million
shares.
   ``Until the market environment clears, we can hardly predict the
market direction right now,'' said a dealer at a major brokerage,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Dealers attributed the slight gain in the Nikkei index to rises
in overseas stock markets last week.
   ``The market itself is ready for another rally, and we just have
to wait for the environment to calm down,'' the dealer said.
</TEXT>
