<FIRST>r a PM-China-USReax     05-22 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-US Reax,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Students in U.S. Start ``Newslift,'' Denounce Peng</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters in San Francisco started a ``newslift'' and East
Coast demonstrators said they no longer recognized China's
government as Chinese college students in the United States
expressed support for the uprising in their homeland.
   ``If the present government is still in power when we return, we
may suffer,'' said Liang Yongsheng, 38, a musicology student from
Beijing studying at Stanford University. ``There'll be a heavy
shadow hanging over all of us. But we can't worry about that. It's
too important for us to stand up and speak out now.''
   Rallies also were held this weekend in New York, Philadelphia,
Washington, D.C., Houston, Chicago and Lawrence, Kan.
   Students in the San Francisco Bay area have started using
telephones and facsimile machines to send information to
pro-democracy demonstrators in the Chinese capital. The effort,
dubbed an emergency ``newslift,'' began after Chinese government
officials declared a news blackout late Friday.
   ``People there know far less about what's going on than we do,''
said Yu Tau, president of the Chinese Students and Scholars
Friendship Association at the University of California at Berkeley.
   The support from Chinese college students in the United States
came as hundreds of thousands of students and supporters occupied
Beijing's Tianamen Square for a third day today. An ultimatum
issued by Premier Li Peng passed without any sign of a military
crackdown.
   In New York on Sunday, about 300 Chinese students delivered an
open telegram to the Chinese consulate pledging support for
protesters in Beijing and ``our complete disobedience to such a
hostile government.''
   ``Lots of the students are crying ... I feel like crying, too,''
said Dong Lu, a graduate student at Hunter College. ``I feel so sad
and so angry.''
   Three of the protesters met with Consul General Tang Uyu-Boo and
delivered an open telegram on behalf of 10,000 Chinese students on
the East Coast, Dong said.
   ``We no longer recognize the Chinese government led by Li Peng
as a legal administration in China, and we pledge our complete
disobedience to such a hostile government toward the whole Chinese
nation,'' the telegram said.
   A woman who answered the telephone at the Chinese consulate said
officials had no comment.
   Students in Beijing have led the largest uprising in the 40-year
history of the People's Republic of China. The United States is
host to about 40,000 students from that nation.
   In Montana, a leading Chinese dissident said Li will be forced
to resign by senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   Liu Binyan, a former high-ranking official at the People's
Daily, said several Chinese provinces and eight government
ministries, including the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, are refusing
to support Li Peng's government.
   Liu, an outspoken critic of corruption in government, was ousted
from the Chinese Communist Party in 1987, but is still vice
chairman of the Chinese Writers' Association. Liu said he remains
in close telephone contact with top-ranking officials in the
current government.
   He was at the University of Montana in Missoula to speak at a
human rights conference today.
</TEXT>
