<DOCNO> AP890522-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 0529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RadnerRemembered     05-22 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radner Remembered,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Classmates, Professors Remember Gilda Radner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Radner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gilda Radner's classmates and teachers remember
how she made them laugh long before her zany characters on
``Saturday Night Live'' made the nation laugh.
   While the show business world paid homage to Radner, 42, who
died Saturday in Los Angeles after a three-year battle against
ovarian cancer, the comedian was recalled by those who knew her in
her native Michigan.
   ``Her sense of humor was constant and engaging,'' said Richard
Burgwin, a retired University of Michigan drama professor. ``When
she was a student in Ann Arbor, we sort of got a free `Saturday
Night Live' every day because of that bubbling attitude toward
life, and it was original.''
   Radner ``was a wonderful fountain of wit and joy,'' Burgwin said
in a telephone interview from his home in Bradenton, Fla.
   Betty Irwin remembered the time in high school when Radner acted
like her ``Saturday Night Live'' co-star, Chevy Chase.
   ``There was a play once, `The Mouse That Roared,''' said Irwin,
a classmate of Radner's at the Liggett School in Grosse Pointe.
``She was upstairs in the dressing room trying to get dressed. Lee
Jenkins was the queen (on stage). Gilda lost her balance and
literally rolled down the stairs and onto the stage.
   ``She began ad-libbing right away,'' Irwin said. ``The teacher
behind the stage was just having a fit because she couldn't follow
the script. It was really cute.''
   Born in Detroit, Radner attended the all-girls Liggett School
and graduated in 1964.
   In her freshman year, Radner performed with her school choir
with the Detroit Symphony Orchestra at Ford Auditorium. In her
junior year, she transferred to Detroit Mumford High School and
worked as a volunteer at Sinai Hospital.
   ``Actually I was going to teach retarded kids. I used to work
with the emotionally disturbed in Detroit,'' she told the New York
Daily News in 1977.
   She returned to Liggett for her senior year, then enrolled at
the University of Michigan as a drama student. She left without
obtaining a degree.
   ``I think she was bored, quite frankly,'' Burgwin said. ``There
are performers who need and want training, and there are others who
are themselves, and ready to go.
   ``I think Gilda made the right judgment. What we had to give was
not what she needed.''
</TEXT>
