<HEAD>200,000 Rally in Yerevan, Call for Ouster of Armenian Leadership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200,000 people rallied in the Armenian
capital of Yerevan and called for the ouster of the southern
republic's top three leaders, a local activist said today.
   Sunday's demonstration also called for a resolution of the
longstanding conflict over Nagorno-Karabakh, a largely Armenian
enclave in the neighboring republic of Azerbaijan, Rafael Popoyan
said in a telephone interview.
   More than 90 people were killed last year in ethnic clashes over
Nagorno-Karabakh, which many Armenians want annexed to their
republic.
   The demonstrators called for the replacement of Armenia's
Communist Party chief and the republic's president and premier.
   The crowd decided to halt a 4-day-old general strike at schools
and many businesses in anticipation of Thursday's inaugural session
of the country's new Congress of People's Deputies, Popoyan said.
   He said Armenia's deputies to the body would meet today or
Tuesday to discuss plans for asking the congress to take on the
problem of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   If the congress fails to respond, the strike may be renewed,
Popoyan said.
