<FIRST>r a PM-YellowstoneTourism     05-22 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone Tourism,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Curiosity Over Fires Fuels Yellowstone Tourism Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ANGELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Curiosity is luring
tourists to America's oldest national park a year after fire
scarred roughly half of its 2.2 million acres.
   ``I haven't been here since I was a kid,'' said John Gurrad, of
Albuquerque, N.M. ``If the fires hadn't happened, I wouldn't have
come here.''
   Robert Barbee, superintendent of the 117-year-old park, said
Saturday that predictions that curiosity would attract visitors
appeared to be coming true.
   ``There was great concern early on because reservations were
down,'' he said. ``But that has reversed itself. In April, our
reservations were 29 percent above last April. I am convinced we
are going to have an excellent season.''
   Officials for TW Recreational Services, the park's chief
concessionaire, report bookings at the Old Faithful Inn, the only
lodging open during the park's early spring season, were running 5
percent ahead of projections.
   Sharon Roe, front office manager, said all 327 rooms have been
booked since May 14.
   Some areas that were burned are erupting in the reds, yellows
and oranges of wildflowers, although many areas remain blackened
from the fires.
   ``I didn't think it would be as bad as what I read,'' said Larry
Long, a park visitor. ``And I don't think it is. I think it will
get better over time.''
   On Saturday, NBC anchorman Tom Brokaw, speaking at a conference
of the Greater Yellowstone Coalition, defended news coverage of the
fires. He said the impression the park was destroyed was reached
largely by the news audience itself.
   ``Too many people think of a national park as a city park,
except larger,'' he said. ``The same popular perception applies to
fires. They think of flames only as a destructive force. When there
are fires in a national park, to most people, that is not good
news.''
   Visitors on Saturday said they did not believe the fires took
anything away from the park's basic beauty.
   ``I think a lot of it here is still really pretty,'' Gurrad
said. ``But there are going to be some pretty ugly spots, too.
There are some spots that are really dead.''
</TEXT>
