<HEAD>Two People Killed as Planes Collide over N.H.-Vt. Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADFORD, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two small planes collided along the New
Hampshire-Vermont border, and one aircraft plunged into a river,
killing both people aboard, officials said. The other plane landed
safely on a highway.
   The two occupants of the second plane were listed in fair
condition at a Hanover, N.H., hospital after the accident Sunday
afternoon.
   ``There was this crunch,'' said Vernon Clark of Lebanon, N.H.,
who was playing golf. ``And the young fellow playing with me looked
up at the noise and said, `My God, those two planes just collided.'
I looked up and saw one of the planes veer away to the river and go
into a spin. It seemed to take a long time to come down.''
   State Police and witnesses said the windshield of the plane that
landed safely on Interstate 91 had been shattered by what appeared
to be a piece from the other plane's tail. That plane went down in
the Waits River.
