<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0496,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Legislators Protest Chinese Crackdown on Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th pvs, ``The Taiwan...'' to ADD number of seats in legislature.
Pickup 5th pvs, ``The Nationalists...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty lawmakers from the governing
Nationalist Party demanded today a halt to all private contacts
with China to protest the communist government's hard line against
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   ``We should suspend our policy of opening up toward the mainland
until the Chinese communists lift martial law and end any military
crackdown,'' the legislators said in a statement to the government.
   On Saturday, Chinese Premier Li Peng imposed martial law in
Beijing and ordered troops to end massive protests that have spread
through China the past month. His hard-line policy has encountered
resistance, and reports from Beijing on Monday said military
leaders have opposed it.
   The Taiwan lawmakers said the Nationalist government should
offer to open direct trade and shipping links between the rival
nations if China cancels the crackdown order and acknowledges the
protests are ``patriotic and democratic.'' The legislature, which
is dominated by the Nationalist Party, has 297 seats.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan in 1949 when they lost a
civil war on the mainland, continue to claim they are the
legitimate government of all China. They are technically still at
war with the Chinese communists, and they have refused to have any
direct contacts with the mainland government.
   But in the past two years, they have pursued a flexible policy
that has allowed Taiwanese and Chinese to exchange visits and trade
through third countries.
   Government spokesman Shaw Yu-ming said on Sunday that Taiwan
would continue to pursue its flexible policy but would reassess it
if the situation on the mainland deteriorates and threatens to
endanger Taiwan residents.
   Legislator Huang Chu-wen, who initiated the statement signed by
60 lawmakers, said a successful military crackdown could set back
democracy on the mainland by 20 years and ``we would miss a good
opportunity to reunite (China) peacefully.''
   The Nationalists ended 38 years of martial law in 1987. They say
China and Taiwan, considered a Chinese province by both the
Nationalists and communists, should be reunited under a democratic
system.
   The legislators said they will submit their statement to the
lawmaking Legislative Yuan for discussion Tuesday and then relay it
to the government Cabinet.
   Also Monday, Hu Chin-heng, 35, a clerk at the Ministry of
Communications, began a three-day hunger strike in Taipei to
protest what he described as ``Taiwanese indifference'' to the
democracy movement in China.
   Hu, a native Taiwanese, staged his strike at a park dedicated to
the late President Chiang Kai-shek, who led the defeated
Nationalists to Taiwan from the mainland. Chiang died in 1975.
   Students and faculty at some universities have signed petitions
supporting the democracy movement in China, but there have been no
major public rallies.
</TEXT>
