<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0482 05-22 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0482,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>250 Moslem Fundamentalists Detained In Gaza Strip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with soldiers shot at, army comment,
six women injured. Pickup 5th pvs, ``In clashes...'' Minor editing to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops in the occupied Gaza Strip
detained more than 250 Moslem fundamentalists and seized a cache of
automatic weapons in the biggest arrest raid since the Palestinian
uprising began, the army announced.
   In the occupied West Bank today, unidentified gunmen fired three
shots at police in the center of Bethlehem, police and army
officials said. One shot hit a police car, but no one was injured.
   Israel radio said soldiers at a hitch-hiking post in the Negev
desert reported gunmen in a passing car shot at them today. They
were not hit.
   The shootings and discovery of the weapons cache came amid
mounting concern over Palestinian threats to step up violence and
end a policy of not using guns in the 17-month-old uprising.
   Col. Renaan Gissin, the deputy army spokesman, said there
recently has been an increase in Palestinians' use of firearms.
   ``We see it as a grave development,'' he said in an interview.
   Elsewhere today, soldiers shot and wounded two Palestinians in a
clash in the Gaza Strip refugee camp of Dir El Balah. And six women
were hurt by metal pellets fired by soldiers in the West Bank town
of Tulkarem, Arab reports said.
   In clashes on Sunday, soldiers shot and killed two Palestinians
and wounded at least 25, according to hospital reports. The deaths
raised to 496 the number of Palestinians killed since the uprising
against Israeli rule of the occupied lands began in December 1987.
Twenty-two Israelis have been slain.
   Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, head of the army's central command,
said the arrest operation in the Gaza Strip was a ``decisive blow''
to Hamas, an organization of Moslem fundamentalists.
   ``In the long term ... there will be a reduction of violence in
the area,'' Mordechai said in comments broadcast on Israel radio.
   Hamas, which means ``zeal'' in Arabic, takes a harder line than
the Palestine Liberation Organization in seeking an Islamic nation
that would exclude the existence of a Jewish state. Many of its
leaders oppose peace negotiations with Israel.
   An army announcement said security forces confiscated 18
weapons, including pistols, U.S.-made M-16 and Soviet Kalashnikov
automatic rifles, Israeli Uzi submachine guns and Swedish Karl
Gustav rifles.
   The statement said Hamas members fired at an Israeli car and an
Israeli man digging a well in Gaza in March 1988. The group also
was blamed for throwing an explosive device at Israeli soldiers.
   According to the army, Hamas planned anti-Israeli
demonstrations, firebombed shops of storekeepers who violated
strike orders by the uprising leadership and killed Arabs suspected
of collaborating with Israel or those who were involved in drugs
and prostitution.
   About 45 suspected collaborators have been killed in the
uprising.
   Mordechai said that among those detained was Sheikh Ahmed
Yassin, the spiritual leader of Hamas who was accused of ordering
beatings and shootings of suspected collaborators.
   Yassin, who is paralyzed and confined to a wheelchair, had been
sentenced to 12 years in jail in 1984 after being convicted of
having knowledge of concealed weapons. He was released in a
prisoner exchange in 1985.
   The raids against Hamas were conducted during a six-day curfew
in the Gaza Strip that confined some 700,000 people to their homes.
   The army lifted the curfew on Sunday but few Gazans went to
their jobs in Israel because of a strike ordered by leaders of the
uprising.
   There was increased concern that Palestinians had escalated
their rebellion.
   A leaflet published this week by pro-PLO activists called on
Palestinians to kill an Israeli soldier or settler for every
Palestinian killed by Israeli soldiers.
   Last week, three Palestinians fired on Israeli troops in a West
Bank village, killing one soldier and wounding seven before they
were killed. It was the first gun battle of the uprising.
   Mohammed Abbas, the chief of a radical PLO faction, also called
for the use of firearms by Palestinians in an interview published
in the Kuwaiti daily Al Watan on Sunday.
   The United States has accused Abbas, also known as Abul Abbas,
of involvement in the 1985 hijacking of the Italian cruise ship
Achille Lauro in which an American, Leon Klinghoffer of New York,
was killed.
</TEXT>
