<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins Today In Former Congressman's Perjury Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `The trial ...' to CORRECT year to 1990 sted
1992.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy-five potential jurors began filling out
questionnaires today for the trial of Pat Swindall, a two-term
Republican congressman who lost his seat while under the cloud of a
perjury indictment.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Freeman has said he wants to try to
seat a jury before ruling on Swindall's request to move the trial
out of town.
   A judge aborted Swindall's first trial six months ago after
Swindall campaign mailings proclaiming his innocence arrived at the
homes of at least two jurors.
   Freeman set aside the entire day to complete the questionnaires
and allow lawyers to study the answers. Questioning of prospective
jurors was set for Tuesday.
   Swindall, who acted as his own attorney last fall, is
represented this time by Richard Hendrix, a former federal
prosecutor.
   Swindall was indicted Oct. 17 on 10 counts of lying to a federal
grand jury. Each charge carries 10 months to five years in prison.
   The trial could determine his political future. The 38-year-old
conservative has said he would like to run against Democratic Sen.
Sam Nunn in 1990.
   Swindall is accused of lying to a grand jury in 1988 when he
said he did not remember being told that an $850,000 home mortgage
loan he was seeking might be coming from illegal drug proceeds.
   Swindall negotiated the loan with a money broker who turned out
to be an undercover federal agent, and the prosecution has a
recording of the agent telling Swindall he had a ``gut feeling''
drugs were involved.
   In October, Swindall, running for re-election and hoping to
clear his name, waived his right to file pre-trial motions and got
an immediate trial.
   But Judge Robert Vining aborted the trial.
   Swindall lost his seat in Atlanta's eastern suburbs to Democrat
Ben Jones on Nov. 8.
</TEXT>
