<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Benefits     05-22 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Benefits,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Study Social Security Regulation in Colorado Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to study a
federal regulation aimed at saving the government time and money
when it mistakenly overpays some Social Security recipients.
   The court said it will study a ruling in a Colorado case that
struck down the regulation.
   The regulation applies to two Social Security programs: old age,
survivors and disability insurance benefits and supplemental
security income.
   Adopted by the Department of Health and Human Services, the rule
covers instances in which the government at different times
overpays and underpays benefit recipients.
   The rule allows officials to balance the overpayments against
underpayments, arriving at a net amount that is either owed the
government or the recipient.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, based in Denver, ruled
last August that the regulation is illegal because it may operate
to deprive needy recipients of the chance to keep overpayments.
   The appeals court ruling applies to recipients in Colorado,
Kansas, New Mexico, Oklahoma, Utah and Wyoming. Federal appeals
courts elsewhere have handed down conflicting rulings.
   The 10th Circuit court said federal law requires that the
government abandon recovery of overpayments when a recipient is
blameless or if returning the extra benefits would cause the
recipient serious hardship.
   The appeals court rejected government arguments that allowing
recipients to keep the extra money is an unfair windfall.
   ``An overpaid beneficiary who does not have to repay excess
benefits is not receiving a windfall but rather is benefitting from
Congress' express provision that recovery (by the government) must
be waived in appropriate situations,'' the appeals court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, Justice Department laywers said
the appeals court misunderstood the way the disputed regulation
works. They said the rule would not deprive needy people of the
opportunity eventually to keep the extra money.
   The government said the regulation would spare the government
from paying out millions of extra dollars automatically and then
going through an elaborate procedure to recover some of the money.
   Government lawyers said that from 1981 to 1986 an average of 4.7
million people each year received too much or too little due to
errors in the retirement and survivor's insurance program alone.
   The case is Sullivan vs. Everhart, 88-1323.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Gacy     05-22 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Gacy,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gacy Loses Supreme Court Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mass murderer John Wayne Gacy, convicted and
sentenced to death in 1980 for killing 33 boys and young men, lost
a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The justices rejected arguments that Illinois' death penalty law
wrongly gives county prosecutors ``complete and unguided discretion
to determine whether to seek the death penalty in murder cases.''
   Gacy's appeal also had contended that he was denied a fair trial
because the presiding judge limited the testimony of an expert
psychiatric witness for the defense.
   Both arguments were rejected by the Illinois Supreme Court last
Sept. 29.
   The high court's action came without comment other than a
dissenting statement by Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood
Marshall, who oppose capital punishment under all circumstances.
   No one in U.S. history has been convicted of killing more people
than Gacy.
   Police found 29 of Gacy's victims in the crawl space beneath his
Norwood Park Township home in Chicago. Four more had been in nearby
rivers.
   Prosecutors said the murders were committed over a three-year
period beginning in 1975.
   Gacy said he strangled all but one of the 33 by wrapping rope
around their necks and twisting it with a stick. He sexually
assaulted some of the victims before killing them.
   A Chicago native, Gacy lived in Springfield, Ill., and in Iowa
before returning to Chicago in the early 1970s to start a
successful remodeling business. He often hired teen-age boys.
   Gacy, who received death sentences for 12 of the murders and
life terms for each of the remaining 21, now resides at Menard
Correctional Center in Chester, Ill.
   A January execution date was postponed, and no new date has been
set. The last execution in Illinois occurred in 1962.
   Gacy's name surfaced briefly in the 1988 presidential campaign
when a pamphlet distributed by Illinois Republicans contended that
Gacy would have been eligible for weekend passes had he committed
his crimes in Massachusetts under Gov. Michael Dukakis'
administration.
   Dukakis labeled the pamphlet ``garbage,'' and Gacy later wrote
to state Republican officials to complain about what he called the
``sleazy'' tactic.
   The case is Gacy vs. Illinois, 88-6828.
</TEXT>
