<FIRST>r a PM-CondorChick     05-22 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Condor Chick,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Year's Third Condor Hatching Ups Species Count to 31</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildlife officials believe the endangered
California condor is on the rebound after the hatching of a fourth
bird bred in captivity.
   Kaduku, whose Konkow Indian name means ``very strong being, both
physically and spiritually,'' became the 31st known condor when it
popped out of its shell Sunday at the San Diego Wild Animal Park
without much help from keepers.
   The chick weighed in at 5.8 ounces. Its aqua-colored egg was
laid on Easter.
   ``This is the first time in two decades that there have been
more than 30 of the birds,'' said park spokesman Tom Hanscom. ``We
expect a lot more hatches next year.''
   All known California condors, which are North America's largest
land birds with wingspans up to 9{ feet, have been captured in
hopes of rebuilding their numbers to the point where the species
can be reintroduced in the wild.
   Seventeen of the birds are at the Wild Animal Park; the 14
others are at the Los Angeles Zoo.
   Molloko, the first captive-bred condor, which hatched last year,
remains in good health, as do all three chicks produced this year,
Hanscom said.
   Another egg is expected to hatch in about two weeks. Next year's
mating season, more of the condors will have reached sexual
maturity.
   Handlers feed the chicks using lifelike condor puppets to keep
the birds from becoming attached to humans.
   The number of the black carrion-eaters dwindled dangerously low
because of shooting and pesticide poisoning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
