<FIRST>r a PM-ParachuteDeath     05-22 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Parachute Death,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Making First Jump Dies When Chute Doesn't Open</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST MORICHES, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man making his first sky dive died
after he jumped in the wrong position and his parachute failed to
open, an instructor says.
   Jack Reilly, 28, of Bellmore was fatally injured Saturday at
Spadero Airport. He and 18 others had just completed a sky-diving
class.
   Ray Maynard, president of Skydive of Long Island Inc., said
Reilly jumped out of a plane at about 3,000 feet. Jumpers are
attached to a ``static line'' that automatically pulls the chute
from its pack, he said.
   Reilly jumped in the wrong position, causing the parachute to
not fully open, then waited too long to pull his reserve chute,
which opened about 300 feet from the ground, Maynard said.
   Maynard said each student is given 5{ hours of lessons; 2{ hours
of classroom time and three hours practicing jumps from a mock
airplane.
   ``When the instructors feel that a student is not confident they
will not let him jump, but Reilly seemed confident and (we) felt he
was very good,'' Maynard said.
   He said his company has been at the airport for seven years and
that it was the first fatality.
</TEXT>
