<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Green     05-22 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Green,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Limits Federal Judges' Power to Exclude Evidence in Pennsylvania
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today limited federal
judges' power to exclude potentially prejudicial evidence from
civil trials, ruling against a young Pennsylvania man who lost his
arm in a car wash accident.
   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, said Paul Green's product-liability
lawsuit was not denied a fair trial when lawyers representing the
sued manufacturer were allowed to tell jurors about Green's
criminal record.
   Writing for the court, Justice John Paul Stevens said federal
rules of evidence require judges ``to permit impeachment of a civil
witness with evidence of prior felony convictions regardless of
ensuant unfair prejudice to the witness or the party offering the
testimony.''
   Federal judges may exclude evidence only when it is a criminal
defendant who might be harmed by it, Stevens said in interpreting a
particular rule of evidence.
   Green was 19 when he lost his arm in a June 23, 1984, accident
at the Lemoyne Minit Car Wash near Harrisburg, Pa. At the time,
Green was on work-release employment from the county prison.
   He had reached into a towel-drying machine that his suit alleged
was defective. The machine tore Green's right arm completely off at
the shoulder.
   He sued the drying machine's manufacturer, Bock Laundry Machine
Co.
   At trial, Bock's lawyers were allowed to tell jurors through
cross-examining Green that he had been convicted of several
felonies, including burglary and statutory rape.
   Green's lawsuit was tried in federal court because Bock is not
based in Pennsylvania, but in Toledo, Ohio.
   A jury ruled for Bock, and a federal appeals court upheld the
manufacturer's trial victory. The appeals court said the trial
judge had no discretion to exclude such evidence in a civil, or
non-criminal, trial.
   Today, the Supreme Court agreed. ``No error occurred when the
jury in this product-liability suit learned through impeaching
cross-examination that plantiff Green was a convicted felon,''
Stevens wrote.
   Justices Harry A. Blackmun, William J. Brennan and Thurgood
Marshall dissented.
   They said the federal rule of evidence in question should allow
trial judges ``to consider the risk of prejudice faced by any
party, not just a criminal defendant.''
   Writing for the three, Blackmun said: ``This case should have
been decided on the basis of whether the Bock Laundry Machine Co.
designed and sold a dangerously defective machine without providing
adequate warnings.
   ``The fact that Paul Green was a convicted felon ... has little,
if anything, to do with the issues. We cannot know precisely why
the jury refused to compensate him for the sad and excruciating
loss of his arm, but there is a very real possibility that it was
influenced improperly by his criminal record. I believe that this
is not a result Congress conceivably could have intended.''
   The case is Green vs. Bock Laundry Machine Co., 87-1816.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0065 </DOCNO>
