<FIRST>r a PM-MassacreMemories     05-22 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Massacre Memories,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Plans to Sell Wild Matewan Image</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MATEWAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This community deep in the rugged
Appalachian coal fields wants to use its bloody past to bring in
tourists.
   ``We can do the same kind of thing that Tombstone's (Ariz.)
done,'' said Mayor Johnny Fullen, whose town this weekend marked
the anniversary of a fatal 1920 shootout between miners' union
sympathizers and coal company guards.
   This town near where West Virginia, Kentucky and Virginia meet
also was in the middle in the late 1800s when the Hatfields and the
McCoys began their feud.
   Tombstone is known for the gunfight at the OK Corral, won by
Marshal Wyatt Earp and his brothers.
   ``What happened here in history wasn't pretty,'' said Robert
McCoy, a former mayor and member of the Matewan Development
Center's board of directors. ``But it was important nationally.
Frankly, I'm perplexed as to why this part of history has been
neglected by the state.''
   On Friday, the town of 800 marked the massacre with a talk by
Lon Savage, author of ``Thunder in the Mountains,'' issued a
walking tour brochure and met with state, federal and community
officials to find ways to preserve the town's past.
   This summer, two historians from West Virginia University will
spend 10 weeks in Matewan taping 50 oral histories, and Marshall
University's Center for Regional Progress will conduct a survey of
the town's tourism potential.
   Local officials also are thinking of opening the town's first
motel.
   ``West Virginians should be proud of their history,'' the mayor
said.
   The body count for the 1920 shootout has not been definitively
settled, but estimates place the toll at two miners, seven
detectives and the mayor, all killed in a hail of gunfire along the
railroad tracks behind a hardware store.
   Nineteen people were indicted, none convicted. A key figure,
Police Chief Sid ``Two-Gun'' Hatfield, a descendant of clan leader
Anderson ``Devil Anse'' Hatfield, was gunned down outside the
courthouse where he was to stand trial.
   Until recently, ``everyone was sort of secretive'' about the
Matewan Massacre, which was the subject of the 1987 movie
``Matewan,'' Fullen said.
   ``I guess the people involved were still here,'' he said.
</TEXT>
