<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica McClure gave a thumbs-up to a TV
movie about her 58-hour ordeal in a well, but the toddler's father
says he came off too scruffy.
   ``I should have played myself,'' Chip McClure said after
watching the ABC movie ``Everybody's Baby: The Rescue of Jessica
McClure'' on Sunday night.
   McClure said he knew he didn't always look his best during his
daughter's rescue in October 1987 from an abandoned backyard well
in which she had become wedged. ``But I didn't look that scruffy,''
he said of actor Will Oldham.
   ``I did a better job at the press conference in Hollywood. And
he could have shaved the sideburns and the beard and I would have
been a lot happier,'' McClure said.
   Roxanne Zal played his wife, Cissy, and Laura and Jennifer
Loesch played Jessica, now 3 years old.
   The subject of the film gave it a ``thumbs up,'' McClure told
the Dallas Morning News.
   ``She's real interested in it,'' he said. ``She knows it's her
they're talking about. I told her this was going to be a scary
movie and if she didn't like it, we could turn it off.
   ``But she's not scared at all,'' her father said. ``She says,
`That's you, mommy, and is that you, daddy?'''
   McClure said he was hopeful that 19 months of media attention
would end with the showing of the TV movie.
   Robert O'Donnell, one of two rescuers who pulled Jessica from
the hole, said the actor who played him, Whip Hubley, ``is a little
bit stockier than myself. He'd never have fit in the shaft.''
   Other residents portrayed in the movie were happier with it.
   ``It's kind of weird to see yourself on TV but how many times
does something like this happen to you? Now we can just sit back
and enjoy it,'' said police Sgt. Andy Glasscock, the first rescuer
on the scene.
   Glasscock watched the movie with other rescuers, their families
and friends. Some couldn't help shouting out advice to characters
in the movie.
   ``Cissy, look in the hole!'' one viewer shouted as Jessica's
movie mother looked around the yard for her missing daughter.
