<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Brainwashing 1stLd-Writethru a0518 05-22 0982</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Brainwashing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Shield Moon's Unification Church From Being Sued</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 2, The court also, and 22-36, In the Gacy, with
other cases.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to shield the
Rev. Sun Myung Moon's Unification Church from being sued by two
former members who say they were duped into joining it.
   The court also turned down an appeal by mass murderer John Wayne
Gacy, convicted and sentenced to death in 1980 for killing 33 boys
and young men.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that religious
freedom protects the church against allegations of ``brainwashing''
and fraudulent recruiting.
   David Molko and Tracy Leal told similar stories in court papers
of how they became ``Moonies'' in California and how
``deprogramming'' led them to quit.
   Molko was 27 when he graduated from Temple University law school
in 1978 and decided to visit San Francisco.
   Soon after arriving there in 1979, he was approached by two men
at a bus stop who told him they belonged to an international
community of socially conscious people.
   Molko went to dinner with them, and later joined a group that
went to a farm outside the city. He said that in the ensuing days
he and others at the retreat were kept to a tight schedule of
lectures, group discussions and calisthenics.
   He said he had no time to himself and, at least at the outset,
even was accompanied to the bathroom by a group member.
   Molko said he asked group members several times whether the
organization was a religious one and was told it was not. It was
not until the 12th day _ after the group arrived at another retreat
called ``Camp K'' _ that he was told the group was part of the
Unification Church, he said.
   Molko said he was confused and angry but decided to stay on when
members convinced him that deception had been necessary because of
the church's negative reputation.
   Ms. Leal was a 19-year-old college student when a recruiter
approached her at a San Francisco bus station in 1979.
   She said she was not told the group was part of the Unification
Church until her 22nd day at the retreat.
   Ms. Leal and Molko remained church members for several months
before they were abducted by ``deprogrammers'' who had been hired
by their parents.
   They are suing the church for punitive damages for the emotional
distress they say they suffered. Molko also is seeking the return
of $6,000 he donated to the church.
   The California Supreme Court, voting 6-1 last October, overruled
two lower courts and reinstated the suits. It ordered jury trials.
   ``Molko and Leal ... contend that by the time the church
disclosed its true identity, the church's agents had rendered them
incapable of deciding not to join,'' the state court said. ``They
contend, in other words, that the church deceived them into a
setting in which they could be `brainwashed'.''
   The state court said the former members are entitled to their
day in court to prove their charges, even though no physical force
was involved in the alleged brainwashing.
   The state court rejected arguments that forcing the church to
defend itself against fraud allegations interferes with its right
to practice its religion freely.
   ``At most, it potentially closes one questionable avenue for
bringing new members into the church,'' the state court said.
   The National Council of Churches, other religious organizations
and a group consisting primarily of college professors urged the
justices to overrule the state court.
   They said the state court ruling ``has had, and will continue to
have, a serious chilling effect on religious proselytizing and
conversion in California and elsewhere.''
   In the Gacy case, the justices rejected arguments that Illinois'
death penalty law wrongly gives county prosecutors ``complete and
unguided discretion to determine whether to seek the death penalty
in murder cases.''
   Gacy's appeal also had contended that he was denied a fair trial
because the presiding judge limited the testimony of an expert
psychiatric witness for the defense.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Limited federal judges' power to exclude potentially
prejudicial evidence from civil trials, ruling against a young
Pennsylvania man who lost his arm in a car wash accident.
   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, said Paul Green's product-liability
lawsuit was not denied a fair trial when lawyers representing the
sued manufacturer were allowed to tell jurors about Green's
criminal record.
   _ Agreed to study a federal regulation aimed at saving the
government time and money when it mistakenly overpays some Social
Security recipients.
   The court said it will study a ruling in a Colorado case that
struck down the regulation.
   _ Refused to shield Chicago from being sued for monetary damages
in state court for allegedly allowing excessive noise and air
pollution at O'Hare International Airport.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that court
allow such lawsuits.
   _ Rejected an appeal by a former Chicago councilman convicted of
fraud for illegally conspiring to buy and sell tax-delinquent
properties.
   The court, over one dissenting vote, refused to use the case of
Thomas E. Keane to set guidelines on when some people may challenge
their fraud convictions after completing prison terms for those
convictions.
   _ Ruled that a lawsuit stemming from the terrorist hijacking of
the cruise ship Achille Lauro in 1985 may be tried in a federal
court in New York City.
   Voting 9-0, the justices rejected an appeal by the ship owners
aimed at transferring the suit to a court in Naples, Italy.
   _ Made deadlines for the filing of civil rights lawsuits by some
prison inmates more flexible.
   The court unanimously ruled in a case from Michigan that states
may give prisoners extra leeway on when they file such federal
suits.
   The Unification Church case is Holy Spirit Association vs.
Molko, 88-1600.
</TEXT>
