<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-AchilleLauro 1stLd-Writethru a0524 05-22 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Achille Lauro, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Achille Lauro Lawsuit May Be Tried in New York City Federal
Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts graf 6, Mrs. Klinghoffer, with Klinghoffer claim settled.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today that a lawsuit
stemming from the terrorist hijacking of the cruise ship Achille
Lauro in 1985 may be tried in a federal court in New York City.
   Voting 9-0, the justices rejected an appeal by the ship owners
aimed at transferring the suit to a court in Naples, Italy.
   Palestine Liberation Organization terrorists seized control of
the ship in October 1985 while it was cruising in the Mediterranean
Sea.
   Leon Klinghoffer, 69, of New York, was killed by the hijackers
and thrown overboard. Klinghoffer, who was Jewish, had been
paralyzed on his right side by a stroke several years earlier and
was in a wheelchair.
   A number of American passengers, including Klinghoffer's wife,
Marilyn, sued Lauro Lines in federal court in New York City.
   Mrs. Klinghoffer died in 1986 and the couple's daughters, Ilsa
and Lisa, settled privately with Lauro Lines. But the claims by
others in the suit still are pending.
   The Italian ship-owning company said American courts lack
authority over the suit because of a provision on the passenger
tickets that said any such claims must be filed in an Italian court.
   A federal judge in New York City said the lengthy and intricate
instructions on the ticket, in small print, did not give the
passengers reasonable notice they were barred from suing in this
country.
   The Supreme Court today said, whatever the merits of that issue,
the lawsuit first must go to trial in the United States.
   Justice William J. Brennan, writing for the court, said if Lauro
Lines loses the suit it will have an opportunity then to appeal on
grounds that American courts lacked jurisdiction.
   Lauro Lines does not have the right now to appeal on that issue,
Brennan said.
   The case is Lauro Lines vs. Chasser, 88-23.
</TEXT>
