<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-US     05-22 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-US,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Black U.S. Ambassador To South Africa Ends Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Edward
Perkins, ending his tour of duty in South Africa today, said he
remains encouraged by the determination of the black majority to be
free despite goverment suppression.
   ``I think that probably is the most encouraging because it tells
me that it's pretty difficult to stifle the desire of people to be
free,'' Perkins told an airport news conference as he concluded 2{
years as the first black U.S. ambassador to South Africa.
   Perkins, 60, said the most disappointing events of his tenure
were the continuation of the government's state of emergency to
control anti-apartheid protests, the banning of 17 activist groups
and the large numbers of people who are arrested and held without
charge under the government's emergency powers.
   Perkins was a strong critic of such developments during his
tenure. Although the embassy repeatedly condemned restrictions on
the press, Perkins gave no on-the-record interviews during his
tenure until last week, when he talked to two South African
newspapers.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   State-of-emergency regulations in effect since 1986 restrict
reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of
detainees, some forms of protest, and a broad range of statements
the government considers subversive. Enforcement of the regulations
has not been comprehensive.
   Perkins said, ``South Africa is moving through a transition to a
different kind of country, to one where the majority population
will have a decisive say in how they are governed, to a South
Africa in which the majority will participate in and benefit from
the wealth of its economy.''
   Perkins has been appointed director-general of the Foreign
Service, which is subject to Senate confirmation.
</TEXT>
