<DOCNO> AP890522-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-MarcosExile 1stLd-Writethru a0436 05-22 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos Exile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Stance on Marcos Belies Claims Of Stability</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Aquino comments today, adviser
saying government might consider Marcos burial. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino's response
to Ferdinand Marcos' latest health crisis belies her claims of a
stable government and shows the nervousness with which she still
views her ousted predecessor.
   Mrs. Aquino said today her government is not strong enough to
risk the return of Marcos and that even his funeral could cause
trouble.
   She refused on Friday to allow the ailing, 71-year-old deposed
president to return from Hawaiian exile and die in his homeland.
She also refused to allow him to be buried here.
   But her national security adviser and a senator closely
identified with the administration indicated today the government
might allow a Marcos burial if his followers guarantee there would
be no bid to undermine the government.
   Mrs. Aquino's caution is well-founded, considering Marcos
supporters led some of the six coup attempts wthat rocked her first
two years in power.
   But since a bloody August 1987 attempt, the government has
boasted continually of its stability, pointing to two years of
economic growth rates above 5 percent and numerous surveys showing
Mrs. Aquino's popularity.
   Government and military spokesmen claim communist rebels are
losing strength and Marcos' following has been reduced to a few
thousand fanatics.
   ``Marcos is no longer viewed by many Filipinos as a threat to
the Aquino government,'' wrote Aquino critic Ninez Cacho-Olivares
in the Filipino publication BusinessWorld. ``Few believe that he or
his wife is capable of making a political comeback.''
   Few challenge Mrs. Aquino's decision to prevent Marcos coming
back alive.
   But in a society that tends to forget its leaders' past
indiscretions, preventing a former president from being buried in
his homeland has struck many as short-sighted and vindictive.
   ``One would hate to think too that Mrs. Aquino would be so
stubbornly uncharitable as to turn down a dying man's last request
even if, as she probably believes, the man was the single biggest
cause of her widowhood,'' said the newspaper Malaya, which strongly
opposed Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino's husband, Benigno Aquino Jr., was slain at Manila
airport in 1983 moments after returning from the United States to
challenge Marcos.
   After a Cabinet meeting to discuss the affair today, Mrs. Aquino
told reporters she feared Marcos' followers would exploit the death
of the man who ruled longer than any Philippine president much as
her own supporters used her husband's murder for political gain.
   ``Let's say a person has been ill for 20 years and now, after
three years, he is slowly recovering,'' Mrs. Aquino said. ``Just
because he is growing stronger does not mean you are going to
expose him to infection.''
   Commentator Luis Beltran wrote in The Manila Standard: ``It is a
no-win situation for President Aquino and her government. If she
keeps to her frequent statements that her government is stable and
beyond the reach of coups d'etat, she has no choice but to allow
Marcos and his family to come home.''
   National Security Adviser Rafael Ileto told reporters today
there was a chance the government might reconsider a Marcos burial.
   ``I don't think that issue of forever refusing him is valid,''
Ileto said. ``It could change.''
   Sen. Aquilino Pimentel said the government might allow a burial
in Marcos' Ilocos Norte home province if the family pledged ``that
they will not use his remains as political capital, like parading
him around Manila.''
   Marcos evokes deep and often contradictory emotions in an Asian
society that respects authority but harbors bitter memories of
eight years of martial rule.
   On Friday, amid reports Marcos might die at any time, news
organizations were flooded with calls from bankers, officials and
ordinary Filipinos asking if he was dead.
   Government officials have said privately the administration
could face the specter of counter-demonstrations by both
anti-Marcos leftists and pro-Marcos rightists if his body were
returned.
   That would encourage opposition from the left and right and
discourage foreign investors.
   Already, questions have been raised about the stability of the
Aquino administration in the wake of the April 21 assassination
here of U.S. Army Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe by communist rebels.
   As a sign of uncertainty, share prices dropped 18 points Friday
because of the rumor Marcos already had died. Business sources said
banks were quietly buying up dollars for fear Marcos' death would
trigger unrest and depress the Philippine peso.
   Selling stocks and buying dollars was a ``normal response'' to a
looming political crisis, one analyst said on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Reid has been Associated Press chief of
bureau in Manila since 1986.
</TEXT>
