<FIRST>u a PM-AbortionConsent     05-22 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Consent,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida's High Court Refuses to Enforce Abortion-Consent Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's Supreme Court today said
minors are free to get abortions without an adult's consent, at
least until next month.
   That is when the court will hear arguments challenging the
constitutionality of a 1988 Florida law requiring single girls
under 18 to get permission from parents, a guardian or judge before
getting abortions.
   The case involving a 15-year-old girl had gone all the way to
the U.S. Supreme Court, which refused to order enforcement of the
law last week.
   The law had previously been struck down as unconstitutional by a
state appeals court. The state Attorney General's office had asked
the state Supreme Court to allow the law to be enforced until the
justices take up the matter.
   But today the Supreme Court refused, without comment. However,
the court agreed to speed up a hearing on the law, from September
to June 27.
   With today's ruling, ``it is our opinion that the law is
unenforceable statewide,'' said Assistant Deputy Attorney General
Mitch Franks.
   The U.S. Supreme Court had refused without comment Thursday to
reinstate Florida's abortion consent law.
   Some experts said at the time that the justices had cleared the
way for all Florida minors to get abortions without permission, but
the attorney general's office said that the ruling might apply to
only one of Florida's five appellate districts.
   After the U.S. Supreme Court ruling, the girl's attorney, Jerri
Blair, refused to say whether her client, who was 12 weeks pregnant
and is identified only as T.W., had obtained an abortion.
</TEXT>
