<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HughesBiography     05-22 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hughes Biography,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoax Autobiography Sells For $5,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only known manuscript copy of Clifford
Irving's phony Howard Hughes autobiography sold at auction for
$5,000.
   The manuscript was sold Sunday along with other Hughes
memorabilia, including an album containing several unpublished
photographs of the reclusive billionaire on his record-setting,
round-the-world airplane flight.
   The buyer of the manuscript would not give his name.
   Irving in the early 1970s duped a publisher out of $650,000 by
claiming he had compiled an autobiography of Hughes based on 100
secret meetings.
   The meetings never took place, and Irving served 17 months in
jail for the fraud. He appeared on the cover of Time magazine as
Con Man of the Year.
   The 989-page manuscript includes the forged signature of Hughes
and other notations, once authenticated by leading handwriting
experts.
   A New York court had ordered all copies of the manuscript
destroyed except Irving's, the one purchased Sunday. Irving asked
Ray Simpson, owner of Simpson's Antiques, to auction the document.
   A London collector bid $6,500 for the album ``A Picture and Word
Story of Houston's Celebration in Honor of Howard Hughes,'' dated
July 30, 1938.
   In all, 26 Hughes-related items sold for $17,000, Simpson said.
</TEXT>
