<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Cholera     05-22 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Cholera,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 100 New Cases Daily of Cholera in Luanda</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors in the Angolan capital of Luanda
are reporting more than 100 new cases of cholera daily in an
epidemic that has claimed dozens of lives, a newspaper reported
Monday.
   Angolan health officials have not released a death toll for the
epidemic but foreign doctors in Luanda are reporting between 100
and 150 new cases every day, according to the state-owned
Portuguese daily Diario de Noticias.
   The paper said dozens have died in the past two weeks from the
disease, an acute intestinal infection.
   Angolan health authorities have launched a media campaign
advising Luanda's 1.2 million people to boil water before drinking,
wash their hands before preparing food and avoid eating seafood,
raw fruit and vegetables, the paper said.
   Officials said the cholera that often surges in May's hot and
humid rainy season was spreading rapidly due to poor water
supplies, drainage and general pollution in the city.
