<DOCNO> AP890522-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Notebook     05-22 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Notebook,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Today's China, it's the Motorcycle Gang of 400</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cruising for democracy has come to China.
   The one-month old movement for more personal freedom and clean
government has involved hundreds of thousands of students, workers
and journalists. Now they've been joined by bikers.
   A pack of motorcycle riders has been roaring up and down central
Beijing's main streets the past week in support of students fasting
in central Tiananmen Square for democracy.
   The Beijing branch of the ``Wild Bunch'' kicked into gear with
about 75 motorcyclists and grew to nearly 400 by Saturday, when
students in the square were expecting the army would try to force
them out.
   Many of the people who brought gauze and surgical masks Saturday
night as a precaution against tear gas wound up covering up for
protection from the plumes of exhaust from the cycles.
   Several cyclists rode with their fashionably dressed girlfriends
perched on the back. They waved Chinese national flags and banners
with anti-corruption slogans as they sped by. At least one swilled
beer as he careened around the square.
   The cyclists seemed to have the most fun late at night, roaring
down the avenue in front of Zhongnanhai, the compound where the
country's leaders work and live, honking horns and revving motors
to make sure their presence was known.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Students protesting for democracy have shown a fondness for
bureaucracy and the trappings of power, two things they supposedly
are fighting.
   For much of the past week, one could barely walk through the
student-occupied Tiananmen Square for more than a minute without
being told the territory that lay ahead was out of bounds.
   ``You can't go in there,'' was a familiar refrain from countless
students armed with nothing more than an air of self-importance.
   Student leaders issued passes to some reporters that supposedly
allowed access around the square. But even they were met with the
response: ``I'm sorry, but those passes are temporarily
ineffective.''
   Meanwhile, other students waved flags, blew whistles, displayed
impressive hand signals and constantly barked orders in trying to
direct the chaotic traffic in central Beijing created by the
Tiananmen protest. Despite their best efforts, however, traffic
remained impossible.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers deployed in the outskirts have spent much of the past
few days meeting the citizens of Beijing, who have swarmed around
the military convoys to prevent them from taking action against
protesting students.
   The people and the military generally appear to get along.
   The people have offered the soldiers popsicles and squash to
eat, newspapers to read and lectures on democracy to mull over.
   The troops, in return, have chatted with the masses and
entertained them with an occassional song.
   One revolutionary blast from the past sung by troops to hearty
applause was ``Learn from Comrade Lei Feng.'' The song is a tribute
to a perhaps mythical soldier offered for emulation years ago as a
keen student of Mao Tse-tung's works. Comrade Lei, so the story
goes, died when he was beaned by a falling telephone pole.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
