<FIRST>r a AM-FrogJump     05-22 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frog Jump,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Frog Jumping Contest Draws 7,000</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGELS CAMP, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 21 years of entering frogs in
the annual Calaveras County Fair and Jumping Frog Jubilee, Tom
Beatty won with a leaper whose name is rich in literary meaning _
Heavy Metal.
   The heavy favorite in Mark Twain's tall tale about jumping frogs
lost because it had been loaded with buckshot.
   Heavy Metal, the last of 76 entrants in the 61st annual contest
Sunday, jumped 19 feet 9} inches to win the prize as a crowd of
7,000 cheered, said fair spokeswoman Jewel Lucken.
   This former gold rush town hosts the jubilee to honor Twain's
1865 short story ``The Celebrated Jumping Frog of Calaveras
County.'' In the story, gamblers loaded up the ace jumper so
heavily the frog couldn't get off the ground.
   On Sunday, each frog got three jumps from the center of a
circle, and the distances were totaled. Handlers were allowed to
scream, dance or do anything but touch their frogs to get them to
jump.
   Beatty traveled from Bend, Ore., to enter his jumper. Gary
Johnson of Angels Camp didn't have to go far to enter Moon Shine,
which placed second at 19 feet, 4 inches.
</TEXT>
