<DOCNO> AP890522-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Editor     05-22 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Editor,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shanghai Party Leader Says Firing Editor Was Rash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party leader of Shanghai has
acknowledged he was too rash in firing a popular, daring newspaper
editor whose dismissal angered journalists nationwide.
   The China Women's News said Jiang Zemin ``welcomed everyone's
criticism,'' but also denied reports that he was criticized by the
national party's Central Committee.
   Jiang did not say if he was willing to reinstate Qin Benli,
editor in chief of the weekly World Economic Herald.
   China Women's News carried Jiang's comments in its Friday
edition, which was not delivered until Monday.
   Mass protests in Beijing against the government's hard-line
attitude toward student demonstrators have disrupted delivery of
mail and newspapers. Some newspapers also have missed editions
since Premier Li Peng declared martial law Saturday.
   Shanghai authorities fired Qin after he refused to alter the
paper's April 24 edition and accused him of repeated ``violations
of discipline.''
   The edition contained calls for a reassessment of party chief Hu
Yaobang, whose death April 15 triggered student protests that led
to the mass marches. Hu was ousted in 1987 for failing to crack
down on earlier student protests.
   After dismissing Qin, Shanghai authorities set up a special
committee to ``rectify'' and supervise the paper. However, its
lower-level editors and reporters have continued to express
defiance and try to publish controversial articles, and officials
have halted and revised two editions since.
   Qin's dismissal prompted journalists in Beijing and Shanghai to
join the student protests. More than 1,000 Beijing reporters signed
a petition demanding a dialogue on censorship, and thousands
marched last week in Beijing and Shanghai.
   It is the first time journalists for the tightly controlled
official media, many of whom are party members, have rebelled
openly and in such large numbers.
   They said they were embarrassed that many Chinese had to get
news on events in their own country from foreign short-wave radio
broadcasts such as the Voice of America and the BBC.
   Li Datong, an editor at the China Youth News who organized the
Beijing reporters' petition, said he thought it was possible Qin
could be reinstated if enough people kept pressuring Shanghai
officials.
   Chinese sources said last week that Jiang offered to reinstate
Qin if he wrote a self-criticism of his actions and the Herald
agreed not to attack Jiang or the Shanghai city government. The
paper refused.
</TEXT>
