<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Palestinians Bjt   05-22 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Palestinians, Bjt,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expulsion of Workers May Cause Problems for Families, Employers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's decision to expel thousands of
Palestinian workers could cause financial hardship for their
families in the occupied lands and harm the businesses that
employed them.
   About 50,000 workers from the Gaza Strip were ordered home last
week. Many hold low-paying jobs in construction, textiles,
restaurants, street cleaning and garbage collection.
   Israeli officials say workers from Gaza will be allowed to
return only with special permits and the system probably will be
applied later to the 60,000 workers from the West Bank.
   Government officials said the purpose was to punish Palestinians
for the 17-month-old uprising against Israeli rule.
   Criiticism came from within the government and from liberal
legislators.
   Shimon Peres, finance minister and deputy prime minister, told
Israel radio expelling workers would cause economic problems for
Palestinians that would inflame the uprising.
   ``We are pushing them into a corner from which there will be
more bitterness and resistance,'' he said.
   Worried businessmen say their industries will suffer unless
replacements are found quickly and have appealed for permission to
hire workers abroad.
   Palestinians expressed concern that delays in issuing the new
permits might cost them their jobs. Fawaz Abu Sitteh, an economist
from Gaza City, described the action as ``the ugliest means of
collective punishment.''
   Annual per capita income in Gaza is equivalent to less than $750
and people have little in savings, he said.
   ``They depend on daily work,'' the economist said. ``They cannot
finance themselves if they don't work.''
   The 110,000 Palestinians who work in Israel are breadwinners for
many of the 1.7 million who live in the territories, bringing home
an estimated $700 million a year. They will find few jobs at home
because little industrial development has taken place during 22
years of Israeli occupation.
   A study in 1988 by the West Bank Data Base Project accused
Israel of ``a deliberate and consistent policy aimed at keeping the
territories as a dumping ground for Israeli industrial products and
as a pool of cheap labor.''
   Those who run industries dependent on unskilled Palestinian
workers say they will have trouble finding replacements because
Israelis do not want the jobs.
   Dov Pollak, managing director of Polgat Textiles, said his
company had employed about 130 Gazans and was hard-pressed to find
substitutes.
   Aharon Sapir, director of the construction industry's
Contractors Association, described the loss of Arab workers as
``catastrophic'' and said ``the immediate solution is to bring
foreign workers'' to replace them.
   So far, the government has opposed importing workers because
112,000 Israelis are unemployed.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin made clear the new policies are
intended to punish the Palestinians.
   ``We started two or three months ago to look for measures that
will make it clear to the Palestinians in Gaza, later on in the
West Bank, that the right to leave the territories is a
privilege,'' he said in an interview.
   Rabin said there must be ``a certain balance between their
freedom to work in Israel and their participation in violence and
terror.'' He has the support of many Israelis angered by the
government's inability to crush the uprising.
   One place feelings are especially strong is Ashkelon, a coastal
city north of Gaza. The body of a soldier the government said was
killed by Palestinians was found near Ashkelon. A missing soldier
believed kidnapped by Palestinians, is from the city.
   ``We shouldn't let them work here anymore. Thy kill our
children,'' said Shmuel Attias, 57, who has overseen Palestinian
sanitation crews in Ashkelon for two decades.
   Yossi Sarid, a parliament member from the left-wing Citizens
Rights Movement, described the government action as ``stupid,
unjust, ineffective and immoral.''
   He accused Rabin of playing into the hands of radical Israelis
who want to expel all Palestinians.
   ``By sending back the inhabitants of the Gaza Strip in a way
which reminds me of South African methods, I believe he gives
legitimacy to all the transferists everywhere,'' Sarid said.
</TEXT>
