<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Baltics     05-22 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baltics,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Accuses Baltic Fronts of Going Overboard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popular movements in the Baltic republics are
going too far in demanding greater independence and backing
programs that amount to complete secession from the Soviet Union,
the Communist Party newspaper Pravda said Monday.
   Grassroots groups in Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania are issuing
demands that are extremist and even nationalist, the newspaper said.
   Referring to resolutions passed at a mid-May assembly of Baltic
popular movements in Estonia, Pravda said: ``In total, although no
one talks about this directly, they make sense only if their
authors have in mind the complete secession of the three republics
from the Soviet Union.''
   The Baltic assembly stopped short of endorsing secession, but
many members of the Estonian and Latvian People's Fronts and the
Lithuanian movement Sajudis openly espouse complete secession.
   The Pravda article came three days before the opening of a new
national parliament at which at least one Baltic delegation, the
Lithuanians, have threatened to walk out if their desires are
ignored.
   ``We think Uzbeks or Russians don't understand our problems,''
said Alfredas Smailys, a Lithuanian delegate to the new Congress of
People's Deputies from Kaunas. ``We demand the right of veto. If,
however, our protest is not taken into account, we're prepared to
leave the hall.''
   A deputy from Estonia, Ulo Vooglaid, would not specify what
tactics the Estonians will use, but he said the delegation ``will
not retreat'' from the platform worked out at the Baltic assembly.
   Baltic nationalists issued a call May 14 for ``economic
independence'' from Moscow by next year. Sixty-one deputies who
belong to the popular movements also hammered out a joint platform
asserting the right of the country's 15 republics to set their own
policies.
   Last week, the Baltic popular movements saw some of their
economic proposals approved by the Estonian and Lithuanian
parliaments.
   They passed measures taking virtually all control over local
industry away from Moscow as of 1990. Lithuania's economic law
includes provision for printing its own money, and Estonia's would
allow limited private property.
   Lithuania on Thurday also duplicated Estonia's ``declaration of
sovereignty'' and claimed veto power over Soviet laws on its
territory.
   Moscow proclaimed Estonia's sovereignty law was invalid last
fall, but Estonia still considers it in force and neither side has
forced a showdown.
</TEXT>
