<FIRST>u w PM-Rabin-Cheney     05-22 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rabin-Cheney,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rabin, Cheney Review Military Situation in Middle East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
reviewed the military situation in the Middle East with Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney today without broaching any requests for new
weapons deals, defense officials said.
   The officials, who asked not to be named, said Rabin and Cheney
met privately and with other officials for more than an hour at the
Pentagon, with Rabin offering the newly installed Cheney a progress
report on the overall situation in the Middle East.
   Rabin and Cheney did not discuss ``in any detail'' Israel's
latest regional peace initiative, the sources said. Rabin and
President Bush are expected to delve more deeply into that issue
during White House talks on Tuesday.
   The Pentagon, in a prepared statement, described today's talks
as ``upbeat (and) friendly.''
   ``Most of the time was spent talking about the current status of
the military situation in Israel,'' the statement said. ``Mr. Rabin
identified the most significant recent development in the region as
the end of the Iran-Iraq war.''
   The defense sources said Rabin had declined to predict for
Cheney what the current cease-fire in that war would mean to Israel.
   ``Basically, Rabin said he didn't know what the cease-fire would
mean or whether it would hold,'' said one official. ``He told
Cheney the war had dominated the region for the past decade. He
also said despite the cease-fire, the arms race in the Middle East
goes on.''
   Iran and Iraq, after more than eight years of fighting, agreed
to a cease-fire last August.
   The Pentagon said in its statement that Rabin ``expressed the
hope that the United States will continue to support Israel.''
   ``Mr. Cheney indicated that we will do our best within the
constraints of the budget to continue our current level of support
to Israel.''
   The Israeli defense chief, however, ``did not get specific about
U.S. support and did not press for any new arms deals or discuss
specific weapons,'' added one source.
   ``This meet was very low key,'' the official said. ``Neither
side asked the other for anything.''
   The meeting ended with Rabin extending an invitation to Cheney
to visit Israel. The secretary accepted the invitation without
committing to a specific date, the sources said.
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk said today Rabin would meet
with Bush on Tuesday to discuss Middle East peace efforts and
Israel's controversial proposal for Palestinian elections.
   President Bush has said he supports the idea of elections as a
way to get the peace process underway.
   The plan calls for voting to chose Palestinian representatives
to negotiate self-rule for the 1.5 million residents of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. Negotiations on a permanent solution would
start after three years.
   The PLO Executive Committee rejected the Israeli plan, and other
Palestinian critics say it fails to deal with Palestinian
aspirations for an independent state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
