<DOCNO> AP890522-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1417EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Court     05-22 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Court,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Limits Scope of `Discreditation' Decree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Supreme Court said Monday that citizens
may not be thrown in jail for expressing truthful criticism of
officials, limiting the scope of a new decree widely criticized by
reformers and dissidents alike.
   The court reviewed a decree passed by the Presidium of the
Supreme Soviet on April 8 because citizens already have been
arrested under differing interpretations of the law, according to a
report distributed by the Tass news agency.
   Critics charged that a provision of the decree banning
discrediting officials and government bodies was written in such a
way that a person could be prosecuted for telling the unpleasant
truth.
   Alvydas Juozaidis, a spokesman for Lithuania's grassroots
Sajudis organization, called the decree ``pure Stalinism.'' Among
its other critics were human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov.
   Some opponents have called for the Congress of People's
Deputies, the new parliament that meets for the first time
Thursday, to overturn the law.
   The court said, ``Well-founded, argumentative criticism of the
action and decisions of these organs and officials by citizens,
acting publicly in the framework of socialist law, cannot be viewed
as a criminally punishable act.''
   The court's action, taken as President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
seeks to strengthen the role of law in Soviet society, constituted
one of the rare times the court has acted to ensure a controversial
measure is applied consistently.
   The Supreme Court instructed lower courts the decree touched
only ``intentional public distribution of slanderous inventions''
that undermines faith in officials.
   It said that the decree did not include ``dispatches in the
press and any other form of information reflecting insufficiencies
in the activity of these organs, social organizations and
officials.''
   The court said its declaration was a balance between protecting
officials from insults and slander, and protecting the rights of
individuals to express their views.
   Tass did not say how many criminal cases have been filed on the
basis of the new law nor did it address any of them in detail.
   But it said that in the month and a half since the decree was
published, differences in interpretation already had come to light.
   Soviet officials have said that the new decree is more specific
and less subject to abuse than Articles 70 and 190 of the criminal
code that for years have banned ``anti-Soviet agitation and
propaganda'' and ``anti-Soviet slander.''
   Politically controled courts used those laws for years to
imprison dissidents. Last year the Soviet Union said it intended to
radically alter those laws. It stopped arresting people under them,
and in the past two years has released hundreds of people arrested
under them.
   But dissidents and reformers alike reacted angrily to the
decree, claiming the provision against discrediting officials
actually was worse than the previous law.
   The law also bans public calls to overthrow the government, and
``premeditated'' acts aimed at inciting national or racial
animosity.
   In other action that also expressed its desire to right the
legal abuses of the past, Tass said the Supreme Court continued its
rehabiliation who were unlawfully convicted of anti-Soviet activity
in the 1930s through the 1960s.
   Those rehabiliated Monday included former midlevel officials who
were accused under Josef Stalin of being German spies or taking
part in a conspiracy to kill the popular Leningrad party chief
Sergei Kirov in 1934.
   A Latvian poet, K.E. Skueniek, who was convicted in 1962 of
anti-Soviet agitation, also was cleared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     05-22 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,530</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   UNIFICATION CHURCH
   
   The court refused to shield the Rev. Sun Myung Moon's
Unification Church from being sued by two former members who say
they were duped into joining it.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that religious
freedom protects the church against allegations of ``brainwashing''
and fraudulent recruiting.
   The case is Holy Spirit Association vs. Molko, 88-1600.
   
   JOHN WAYNE GACY
   
   The court turned down an appeal by mass murderer John Wayne
Gacy, convicted and sentenced to death in 1980 for killing 33 boys
and young men.
   The justices rejected arguments that Illinois' death penalty law
wrongly gives county prosecutors ``complete and unguided discretion
to determine whether to seek the death penalty in murder cases.''
   Gacy's appeal also had contended that he was denied a fair trial
because the presiding judge limited the testimony of an expert
psychiatric witness for the defense.
   The case is Gacy vs. Illinois, 88-6828.
   
   EVIDENCE
   
   The court l Limited federal judges' power to exclude potentially
prejudicial evidence from civil trials, ruling against a young
Pennsylvania man who lost his arm in a car wash accident.
   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, said Paul Green's product-liability
lawsuit was not denied a fair trial when lawyers representing the
sued manufacturer were allowed to tell jurors about Green's
criminal record.
   The case is Green vs. Bock Laundry Machine Co., 87-1816.
   
   SOCIAL SECURITY
   
   The court agreed to study a federal regulation aimed at saving
the government time and money when it mistakenly overpays some
Social Security recipients.
   The court said it will study a ruling in a Colorado case that
struck down the regulation.
   The case is Sullivan vs. Everhart, 88-1323.
   
   AIRPORT NOISE
   
   The court refused to shield Chicago from being sued for monetary
damages in state court for allegedly allowing excessive noise and
air pollution at O'Hare International Airport.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that the court
allow such lawsuits.
   The cases are Chicago vs. Beineman, 88-1496; Bieneman vs.
Chicago, 88-1497; and American Airlines vs. Chicago, 88-1670.
   
   FRAUD
   
   The court rejected an appeal by a former Chicago councilman
convicted of fraud for illegally conspiring to buy and sell
tax-delinquent properties.
   The court, over one dissenting vote, refused to use the case of
Thomas E. Keane to set guidelines on when some people may challenge
their fraud convictions after completing prison terms for those
convictions.
   The case is Keane vs. U.S., 88-1178.
   
   ACHILLE LAURO
   
   The court ruled that a lawsuit stemming from the terrorist
hijacking of the cruise ship Achille Lauro in 1985 may be tried in
a federal court in New York City.
   Voting 9-0, the justices rejected an appeal by the ship owners
aimed at transferring the suit to a court in Naples, Italy.
   The case is Lauro Lines vs. Chasser, 88-23.
   
   PRISONER
   
   The court made deadlines for the filing of civil rights lawsuits
by some prison inmates more flexible.
   The court unanimously ruled in a case from Michigan that states
may give prisoners extra leeway on when they file such federal
suits.
   The case is Hardin vs. Straub, 87-7023.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
