<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1428EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Scandal     05-22 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bribery Charges Filed Against Two Leading Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bribery charges were filed against two leading
politicians in the Recruit influence-buying case Monday, but
critics said prosecutors had not dug deeply enough into the
scandal, which has shaken politics and business.
   Those charged were Takao Fujinami, a former cabinet minister and
member of the governing Liberal Democratic Party, and Katsuya
Ikeda, former secretary-general of the opposition Komeito (Clean
Government) Party.
   If convicted, they could be imprisoned for up to seven years.
   Fujinami, 56, and Ikeda, 52, were not taken into custody.
Japanese law protects members from being jailed while Parliament is
in session unless the legislative body grants permission.
   They are widely expected to be the only politicians charged,
although 17 legislators or aides are known to have received bargain
unlested shares of stock from the Recruit Co.
   Thirteen are from the governing Liberal Democratic Party,
including 11 members of former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone's
cabinet.
   Nakasone said he ``received the news of the charges solemnly''
and wished to apologize to the Japanese people.
   Prosecutors said Fujinami and Ikeda received donations and
heavily discounted stock shares from Recruit in exchange for using
political influence to help the information conglomerate's magazine
publishing business.
   All 14 others arrested or charged in the Recruit scandal were
bureaucrats or businessmen.
   Ikeda, a former journalist and four-term member of the lower
house, said the charges were ``a fabrication of reality'' and he
would prove his innocence in court.
   He announced last week he would resign from both Parliament and
the Buddhist-affiliated Komeito Party.
   Yuichi Ichikawa, current secretary-general of the party, said it
was ``extremely regrettable'' that charges had been filed against a
member, but added that prosecutors should carry the investigation
further.
   Actions taken to date ``aren't enough to clarify and get to the
core of the scandal,'' he said. ``If the investigation ends now, it
will have failed to reach the people who were most responsible.''
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said last month he would resign
to take responsibility for the scandal, which has eroded public
trust in politics. The governing party's search for a successor has
been complicated by the scandal's links to most of its senior
members.
   Ichikawa and other opposition party leaders said they would
continue pressing for a full investigation.
   Eiji Suzuki, head of the Japan Federation of Employers'
Associations, said Monday all members of Parliament who received
Recruit shares should resign, the Japan Broadcasting Corp. reported.
   Fujinami, the chief government spokesman in Nakasone's Cabinet
and an eight-term member of the lower house, was considered a
rising star in the party. He submitted his resignation to the party
Monday but said he would retain his parliament seat.
   He has acknowledged that an aide bought 12,000 shares of stock
in a Recruit subsidiary at a discounted price in 1986, then made a
profit of about 30 million yen ($215,000) when the stock went on
public sale. News reports say Fujinami used some of the profit to
buy a house in Tokyo.
   The former labor minister also is said to have received about 90
million yen ($640,000) in political donations from Recruit.
   Ikeda has admitted his brother bought 5,000 shares of stock in
the Recruit subsidiary and made a profit of about 10 million yen
($71,000). Reports also say Ikeda received 14 million yen
($100,000) in donations from Recruit.
   Both politicians have denied personal involvement in the stock
transactions, but some of the profits allegedly were deposited in
their bank accounts.
   Prosecutors said Ikeda and Fujinami used political influence to
persuade officials to continue a ``gentlemen's agreement'' among
government agencies and private companies on a uniform date for
hiring of graduating college students.
   Recruit considered the agreement critical to the sales of its
employment magazines.
   With the filing of charges against Ikeda and Fujinami,
prosecutors said their bribery investigation was complete and they
would focus on illegal donations made by the conglomerate, news
reports said.
   Japanese law restricts a company of Recruit's size to 15 million
yen ($107,000) a year in political donations.
   Takeshita alone has acknowledged receiving more than 130 million
yen (about $1 million) from Recruit in 1985-87.
</TEXT>
