<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Congress     05-22 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Congress,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Supports Gorbachev for President, Sakharov Too</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leadership of the Communist Party on Monday
endorsed Mikhail S. Gorbachev to be chosen again for the post of
Soviet president when the new parliament convenes for the first
time later this week.
   At a separate meeting of deputies to the congress, human rights
activist Andrei D. Sakharov also endorsed Gorbachev, but with
reservations.
   ``My position is that we have no leader except for Gorbachev.
But he is not immaculate, not immaculate in terms of a very large
number of actions,'' Sakharov said in a speech.
   The official Tass news agency said the party's Central Committee
met to discuss the activities of the Congress of People's Deputies,
which will meet Thursday.
   Among the duties of the new congress are to elect the president
and a smaller, more active Supreme Soviet legislature.
   Tass said the Central Committee recommended election of
Gorbachev as Soviet president. He was elected president Oct. 1 by
the old Supreme Soviet parliament, which is being replaced by the
congress and the new Supreme Soviet it will elect.
   The 251-member Central Committee, the party's policy-making
body, had been expected to meet prior to the congress to set its
approach to the stronger legislative branch being formed as
Gorbachev attempts to strengthen the Soviet government.
   Many questions of the congress' exact functions have not been
clarified yet, just days before it meets.
   The vast majority of deputies are members of the Communist
Party, but there is a large block of reformers who are impatient
with progress so far implementing Gorbachev's reforms.
   Many of them, especially radicals from the Baltic republics of
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, cannot be counted on to follow the
Central Committee's dictates.
   On Sunday, Moscow firebrand Boris N. Yeltsin and others told a
rally that they had formed their own program of radical changes
that includes urgent action to heal the economy and multicandidate
elections for the presidency.
   Yeltsin told the rally that Moscow deputies had drafted an
agenda that demands ``radical decisions on the economy, social
justice and glasnost.''
   The deputies are demanding laws on pensions, children's rights
and property, Yeltsin said.
   Tass said Yeltsin was among 34 speakers Monday at the Central
Committee meeting, but it provided no details of his remarks.
   One deputy, Alexander Tolstoukhov, told the Sunday gathering
that Yelstin should be elected president. Yeltsin has denied in the
past that he is interested in challenging Gorbachev, and no clear
opposition to Gorbachev has formed.
   On Monday, scores of deputies signed a letter to Gorbachev,
backing a draft agenda by Moscow deputies.
   The agenda calls on Gorbachev to make a report to the congress
on the state of the Soviet Union before the election for president
is held.
   Sakharov, speaking at the deputies' meeting, said: ``I think we
have no other real candidate than Mikhail Gorbachev.''
   ``Compared to Gorbachev, the candidacy of Yeltsin would be
unsatisfactory,'' he said. Gorbachev's mistakes must be ``corrected
by the people's will,'' Sakharov said.
   In the past, Sakharov has criticized policy on ethnic relations
and government decisions that he sees as limiting its commitment to
free expression.
   The congress consists of 2,250 members, 1,500 chosen on the
basis of geographical representation and 750 chosen from the
Communist Party and its affiliates, social, professional and trade
union organizations.
   The party itself has 100 seats, and Gorbachev was elected a
deputy of the congress from the Communist Party.
</TEXT>
