<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Museum     05-22 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Museum,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archaeologists Dig in Parking Lot for Bombed Museum's Treasures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Britain's best regional museums that was
destroyed by German bombers and paved over as a parking lot will be
the focus of an unusual archaeological dig this year.
   The city of Hull in northeast England opened the site of the old
Hull Municipal Museum to the public Monday, turning it into a kind
of retrospective of the 1940s, with extracts from war broadcasts
and popular songs piped into the dig, said project coordinator
David Fleming.
   The six-month dig was organized by civic officials, assisted by
an American museum, to save what is left of a once-fine historical
collection.
   The neoclassical museum collapsed in an inferno of German
incendiary bombs in 1943 and was left in ruins for several years
until, for safety reasons, it was flattened and turned into a
parking lot, Fleming said.
   ``For all the world it looked like any other car park,'' said
Fleming, the principal keeper of museums in the coastal city on the
North Sea.
   ``But when we put in a ditch in 1988, we realized a high
proportion of the collection had survived intact although it was
very badly damaged.''
   Fleming said in an interview it was hoped the dig would not only
save the treasures, but reveal how some objects, especially those
made from modern materials, decay in soil.
   The collections ranged from fossils and Roman coins to the
largest prehistoric boat found in Britain and objects made from
nylon and rayon, which were new materials at the time, he said.
   ``It is bizarre,'' he said. ``We're not talking about a normal
archaeological site. We're trying to piece together a moment in
time: June 23, 1943.''
   The site ``was related to people alive here. There's a great
emotional relationship in Hull to this dig,'' he said.
   Financial support for the $192,000 project has also come from
the state-funded National Heritage Memorial Fund and the Heafitz
Museum in Boston, he said.
   City officials hadn't excavated in the post-war years because
Hull had been bombed heavily. ``There was a lot of rebuilding to
do,'' he said. ``It was just something put to the back of people's
minds.''
   Some of the treasures were lost before the rubble was cleared.
   ``We don't really like to call it looting. ... It was hard to
know the mentality at the time, and it looked to be totally
abandoned,'' he said, adding that the extent of the losses was
unknown and most museum records were destroyed.
   After the dig, any treasures salvaged will be housed at one of
the city's other museums, said Fleming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
