<DOCNO> AP890522-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RISenate     05-22 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RI Senate,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unusual Is Commonplace In Divided Rhode Island Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In most statehouses, if a legislator's
vote was cast while he was away or a bill was mysteriously
transferred from one committee to another it would be discussed
heatedly for months.
   It's all in a day's work in the Rhode Island Senate.
   Since the Democratic Party, which controls the Senate 41-9, was
torn apart in a power struggle at the beginning of the year, there
have been sharp conflicts between Majority Leader David R. Carlin
Jr. and Judiciary Committee Chairman John J. Bevilacqua.
   Fourteen of Carlin's 16 top bills were killed by committees
controlled by the Bevilacqua side, and Carlin's supporters have
defeated a few of the opposition's bills on the Senate floor.
   The Republicans helped Bevilacqua's group strip Carlin of most
of his traditional power in a series of 26-24 votes at the
beginning of the year. Minority Leader Robert D. Goldberg won the
right to unilaterally summon bills out of committee and onto the
floor for votes.
   GOP senators have emerged as power brokers and peacemakers,
siding with Carlin to defeat some questionable bills sponsored by
the Bevilacqua group.
   Similar upheavals occurred this year in Connecticut and North
Carolina, where bipartisan coalitions ousted Democratic House
speakers. An attempt in Florida failed when the Democratic speaker
formed an alliance of his own with Republicans. In Indiana, where
the House has equal numbers of Democrats and Republicans, the
parties agreed to elect co-speakers who would alternate control of
the chamber.
   In Rhode Island, with no clear-cut winner, the feuding has
continued intermittently.
   The General Assembly normally adjourns in late May or early
June, but the Senate is several weeks behind last year's pace and
the big test of the year _ budget negotiations with the House and
Republican Gov. Edward D. DiPrete _ has not yet started.
   Carlin and Bevilacqua met May 16 to try to hammer out a unified
Senate position, their first face-to-face meeting in months aside
from brief encounters on the Senate floor.
   They said later that agreement would take some time but would
not be impossible, in part because the state's tight financial
picture means little money will be left over for lawmakers' pet
projects.
   The meeting followed a tense week marked by what Carlin labeled
two ``absolutely incredible'' incidents.
   The first was when state Sen. James S. D'Ambra, a Democrat who
supports Carlin, was recorded as voting with the Bevilacqua faction
on a hotly contested bill while he was in Boston for the day.
   Bevilacqua said someone must have accidentally pressed D'Ambra's
voting button. Carlin and D'Ambra said that was impossible.
   A day later, the Carlin faction noticed that a bill assigned to
the Corporations Committee, where Carlin has a majority, had
somehow been transferred to Bevilacqua's Judiciary Committee.
   Lt. Gov. Roger N. Begin, presiding over the Senate, ruled the
bill was improperly reported out and he was upheld on a 24-24 vote.
   The Republicans helped Carlin on that vote. They also have
helped defeat bills sponsored by the Bevilacqua group that would
have allowed deer hunters to trespass on private property and
short-circuited the normal chartering procedure for a Connecticut
man who wants to open a Rhode Island bank.
   Carlin has begun looking ahead, to the 1990 elections.
   In a recent interview, he said the Bevilacqua group's successful
fight to defeat a Carlin-backed bill banning assault weapons would
be used against Bevilacqua's supporters in the election.
   ``It's a motherhood and apple pie issue, and they voted against
motherhood and apple pie,'' Carlin said.
   But the feud is not universal.
   Carlin's press secretary, Suzanne Costa, has helped several
Bevilacqua supporters, such as state Sen. James M. Donelan, to
publicize their bills.
   ``That person, Suzanne, is here for all the senators,'' said
Donelan. ``She has done a good job for me ... I think a lot of the
staff has tried to remain neutral.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
