<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three weeks of rain are giving
actress-director Lee Grant the mood-setting drizzles for her film
on the homeless.
   ``The texture of the city with that grayness, it was beautiful.
It was exactly what I wanted,'' Ms. Grant said last week after the
rains stopped.
   Ms. Grant and her husband-producer Joseph Feury are spending May
in Pittsburgh filming next season's CBS movie, ``Homeless.''
   The film stars Christine Lahti and Jeff Daniels as a couple
caught in a spiral of urban poverty.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Wayne Newton's planning a first _ a
nationally televised live concert from a Las Vegas showroom aimed
at a pay-per-view audience.
   The two-hour concert Tuesday night from the showroom of the Las
Vegas Hilton will be carried by the nation's three main
pay-per-view syndicates and be available in more than 700 cities.
   Promoters say the broadcast will determine whether similar
events will be carried live from Las Vegas. Newton, 47, is one of
the Hilton's top attractions, working more weeks per year at the
resort than any other performer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashrita Furman, who holds more Guinness
world records than anyone else, has added yodeling to his claim to
fame.
   The native New Yorker by Monday morning had yodeled for 27
hours, besting, he said, the current Guinness World Record of 26
hours set in 1984 by Errol Bird in Lisburn, Northern Ireland.
   ``I feel really good,'' he said after completing the grind at
the Guinness Museum at Fisherman's Wharf.
   If certified, the record will be Furman's 15th. His others
include running a marathon while juggling three balls _ in 3 hours,
22 minutes.
   ``I used to be the classic nerd _ a pure bookworm,'' said the
34-year-old bachelor who manages a New York City health food store.
``I had no athletic interest at all.''
   Furman began his yodeling effort Saturday night and by mid-day
Sunday the task was taking a toll on his larynx and vocal cords.
   But the physical suffering was nothing compared to the time he
performed gymnastic forward rolls nonstop for 12\ miles to set a
record. The headaches were bad, but the nausea was worse.
   He hopes to reach his goal of 25 records by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marjory Stoneman Douglas warned
``there's still a lot to be done,'' then accepted the national
Sierra Club's highest honor for her efforts to preserve Florida's
Everglades.
   ``It has been the greatest possible happiness to me to have had
this purpose and goal,'' the ``grande dame of the Everglades'' told
state and national environmentalists Sunday who gathered to honor
her.
   Ms. Stoneman Douglas, 99, said increased public interest and
political efforts to reverse developmental damage to the Everglades
have ``been the greatest possible pleasure in life.''
   Ms. Stoneman Douglas, whose book ``River of Grass'' six decades
ago helped spur the drive to create the Everglades National Park,
has continued to vigorously advocate expansion of the park and
protection of other Florida wetlands and natural resources.
   ``I think she has been to the Everglades what Winston Churchill
was to Britain in World War II,'' said Mike Finley, the national
park's superintendent. ``She has been the leader, the conscience,
the rallying point.''
