<FIRST>r a AM-AtlantisClosed     05-22 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atlantis Closed,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>First East Coast Casino Forced To Close By Financial Pressures</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ACB2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Red velvet ropes on Monday blocked
the entrances to Elsinore's Atlantis Casino Hotel, the first New
Jersey casino closed by gaming regulators for financial reasons.
   The state Casino Control Commission last week ordered the
Atlantis to close its multilevel casino floors after it ran up
debts of $150 million. Regulators are considering a bid by
developer Donald Trump to buy the Atlantis for $63 million and
convert it into a luxury non-casino hotel.
   Shortly before the normal start of gambling at 10 a.m., a small
group of customers waited at the bottom of the stalled escalators.
A security guard arrived and told them the casino was closed for
good.
   ``There are apparently some people who don't read newspapers or
watch television,'' said Henry Budniak, the Atlantis security shift
supervisor. ``But these are a bunch of people who were attached to
this place. It's sad.''
   ``We'll have to go look for another place to gamble,'' said
Mildred Kerns of Philadelphia. ``I feel so bad. I feel like
crying.''
   Two other customers said they gambled until the bitter end at 4
a.m., when casino attendants stopped handing out change for the
slot machines, the last roulette wheel stopped spinning and dealers
laid their last cards on the green felt.
   ``We came to say good-bye,'' said Antoinette Miozzi of
Philadelphia. ``We love this place. We've been coming here for all
eight years it's been open.''
   About 600 hotel and restaurant workers remain on the payroll out
of 2,000 employees. Casino workers were required to turn in their
gaming licenses, but were told officials from the Trump
Organization would visit the Atlantis on Tuesday to offer them
part-time positions as dealers or cashiers.
   Trump owns two other casinos and is building a third, the legal
limit for an individual owner. Atlantis' state-appointed
conservator, Joseph M. Nolan, has recommended that Trump's
agreement to buy the hotel be rejected in favor of subsequent
higher bids.
</TEXT>
