<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Soviet     05-22 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Soviet,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Pilot Taken to Hospital in Ankara</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet air force pilot who was wounded
while fleeing his country has been moved to an Ankara hospital from
Trabzon on the Black Sea, where he landed his MiG-29 fighter, state
radio reported Monday.
   The radio did not identify the hospital and officials would not
reveal the pilot's whereabouts.
   Officials said they doubted the government would grant the
Soviet request for extradition. Newspapers said U.S. experts had
examined the MiG-29, the most modern jet in the Soviet air force.
   Capt. Alexander Zuyev landed Saturday in Trabzon, with a
bleeding arm wound, and asked for asylum in the United States.
   On Monday a doctor in charge at the Black Sea University
hospital, said: ``Police came, took him away and we don't know
where.''
   ``The pilot is under the protection of Turkish officials
responsible for his safety,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman Nazim
Belger.
   Turkey allowed the plane to be flown back to the Soviet Union on
Sunday. It was stripped of rockets and weapons, which were returned
on a separate plane.
   Newspapers reported Monday the MiG-29 was examined by Turkish
and U.S. military experts. Turkish officials and the U.S. Embassy
refused comment.
   Walter Shonia of the Soviet Embassy told reporters Zuyev was a
terrorist and Turkey's refusal to extradite him would amount to
support for terrorism.
   A Turkish official said privately, however: ``The Russians know
that in many decades we have not sent back home any military
person, from East or West, who asked for asylum.''
   In 1983, a Soviet general in uniform walked across the border to
Turkey and was flown to the United States. His name was not
revealed in Turkey but newspaper reports claimed he was a
high-level security officer.
   Three jets have been flown from the Soviet Union to Turkey since
1970 and the government returned only those Soviets who wanted to
go home.
   Pravda, the newspaper of the Soviet Communist Party, reported
Monday that Zuyev was working as a duty dispatcher at the Tskhakaya
airfield north of Batumi and therefore was armed on the day of his
flight. It said he shot and wounded a sentry, who fired back and
wounded Zuyev.
   Two other Soviet fighters started chasing the MiG-29 but could
not intercept Zuyev because the border was so near, Pravda said.
</TEXT>
