<DOCNO> AP890522-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Stocks     05-22 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Stocks,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Fall on Hong Kong Stock Exchange</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange
fell Monday in reaction to political developments in China, as
concern continued in the British colony over its future when it
reverts to China in eight years.
   Brokers say the activity had been expected because of the tense
situation in China over student demonstrations for democratic
reforms and the Chinese government's declaration of martial law
Saturday to end the protests.
   Stock exchange executives urged investors to stay calm, but
brokers expect developments in China to continue to govern the
market's activities. Some said it might take a week for the market
to stabilize.
   The Hang Seng Index of blue chips plunged 339.06 points to close
at 2,806.57 with all key shares suffering losses. The index lost
288.27 points in 15 minutes when the market opened but recovered
slightly to end the session at 2,887.89.
   On Friday, the last day of trading before the weekend holiday,
the index fell 132.03 points in panic selling in the worst
single-day plunge since the worldwide market collapse in October
1987.
   Turnover totaled $384.4 million Monday, compared with $316
million on Friday.
   There are fears the failure of the student movement could affect
Hong Kong's future and how China will govern the territory in 1997
when it comes under Chinese sovereignty.
   Under a Sino-British agreement signed in 1984, Hong Kong will
become a Special Administrative Region of China under a ``one
country, two systems'' formula. China has promised to preserve Hong
Kong's freewheeling social and economic system that has made it an
international financial center for 50 years beyond 1997 and allow
Hong Kong people to govern the territory.
   But many of Hong Kong's 5.7 million residents remain skeptical
of Chinese promises and the viability of the concept that would
allow a capitalistic enclave to exist under communism.
   An estimated two-thirds of Hong Kong's population are refugees
from China or their descendants who fled the Chinese mainland.
   On Sunday, a crowd of Hong Kong Chinese estimated at between
400,000 and 1 million rallied in support of the pro-democracy
demonstrators in China in what was described as the largest protest
march in the British colony's history.
   The marchers, who included staffers from China's official Xinhua
News Agency and other leftist organizations, demanded the
resignation of Chinese Premier Li Peng.
   ``Hong Kong, not noted for its political activism, has found a
rallying point which has stirred its collective consciousness to an
extent that has surprised everyone,'' said an editorial in the
English-language South China Morning Post.
</TEXT>
