<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionConsent     05-22 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Consent,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Sets Hearing Without Reinstating Controversial Abortion
Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Florida Supreme Court refused
Monday to allow enforcement of a new state law requiring minors to
get parental or judicial consent for abortions, but moved up a
hearing on the law's validity.
   The decison means that single women under 18 throughout Florida
will be able to get abortions without consent of parents or judges,
at least until the high court rules following oral arguments June
27, a lawyer for the state said.
   The justices last week had decided to hear a case involving a
15-year-old girl in September, but agreed Monday to expedite the
case at the request of Florida Attorney General Bob Butterworth's
office.
   The state repeated a request to allow enforcement of the law
until the Supreme Court rules on its validity, but the justices
denied that motion for a second time.
   ``With the denial of the stay, it is our opinion that the law is
unenforceable statewide,'' said Assistant Attorney General Mitchell
Franks.
   The state's 5th District Court of Appeal, ruling in the case
involving the 15-year-old, struck down the abortion consent law as
unconstitutional.
   The case last week went from the Florida high court, which
denied a stay of the 5th District ruling sought by a lawyer
representing the rights of the girl's fetus, to the U.S. Supreme
Court, which also declined without comment to order enforcement of
the law.
   Lawyers had disagreed whether the ruling by the 5th District in
Daytona Beach would apply to Florida's other four appeal court
districts as well, but Franks said the Supreme Court's decision
erased all doubt.
   He said that under the decision, the 15-year-old girl can
legally go ahead with her abortion, if she has not already done so.
   Her lawyer, Jerri Blair of Leesburg, has repeatedly refused to
comment on whether the girl has had or plans to have the abortion,
citing her client's right to privacy. Blair did not return
telephone calls Monday.
   Gov. Bob Martinez, an abortion opponent, said he was
disappointed by the justices' decision. ``I would rather have (the
law) implemented and carried out as I have supported it in the
past,'' Martinez said.
   The girl is identifed in court records only as ``T.W., A
Minor.'' The justices ordered the case file sealed to ensure that
her identity remain a secret.
   The case began when T.W. sought consent from a judge to have an
abortion, telling him she feared physical and emotional abuse from
her parents if she sought permission from them.
   The judge said he was unable to deal with the law as written,
and the consent requirement subsequently was found
unconstitutionally vague by the 5th District Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
