<SECOND>AM-BRF--Rampless Bridge,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Handicapped Stranded On City Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People using wheelchairs can get on the Sixth
Street Bridge leading into downtown Pittsburgh, but they're stuck
if they want to get off at the other end.
   There's a ramp leading onto the bridge from the city's North
Side, but not even a sign warning that on the downtown side, those
in wheelchairs must either jump the curb or ride in traffic.
   City traffic engineers say they know of no safe solution,
because cutting into the curb could expose a structural beam.
   Larry N. Thomas of the Pittsburgh chapter of Open Doors for the
Handicapped said the matter is being considered by the mayor's
handicapped accessibility committee.
   ``Some people said it was the state's responsibility, some said
the county or the city. Now the city is saying, `It's our
responsibility ... but it's an architectural problem,''' Thomas
said.
