<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Drugs     05-22 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Drugs,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Addicts Will Go to Labor Camps, More Traffickers Hanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian drug addicts who don't kick the
habit by July 23 will be rounded up and thrown into labor camps for
at least one year, Tehran TV reported Monday.
   The broadcast quoted the governor general of southeastern Kerman
province as telling a news conference that special segregated camps
for men and women have been built to rehabilitate addicts.
   Tehran Radio als reported that 15 convicted drug traffickers
were hanged Monday. That raised the number of smugglers executed in
the last 10 days to 94.
   Iranian authorities have executed more than 650 drug smugglers
and traffickers since a crackdown was launched in December.
   State-run TV did not identify the Kerman official, but he was
quoted as saying rehabilated addicts will be quarantined with their
families until they could be allowed back into society.
   He said reformed addicts would undergo regular medical
examinations to ensure they were drug-free, said the TV report,
monitored in Nicosia.
   Anyone who turned to drugs again would be returned to the camps,
the official said.
   The law mandates the death penalty for anyone possessing even
small quantities of drugs. More than 2,500 addicts have been
reported picked up since January.
   Unofficial reports estimate that 2 million of Iran's 50 million
people are involved in drug abuse.
</TEXT>
