<FIRST>r i AM-Hunger     05-22 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunger,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than Enough Food For World's Hungry, U.N. Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world produces more food than it needs
but neglect, complacency and incompetence have left at least half a
billion people hungry, participants in a U.N. conference on hunger
were told Monday.
   The World Food Council, a U.N. agency that deals with the
political aspects of food supplies, opened its 15th annual
conference with conflicting but generally grim assessments on the
state of hunger in the world.
   Council Chairman Eduardo Pesqueira of Mexico said ``peace is a
basic prerequisite'' to ending worldwide starvation.
   ``Wars in Central America and Africa make their scarce resources
go to arms rather than food programs. Detente is important for
developed and developing countries,'' he said.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, in a statement
read at the opening of the conference, said hunger still can be
eliminated.
   ``Five years ago, the council noted that hunger ... was largely
a man-made phenomenon: human error or neglect created it, human
complacency perpetuated it and human resolve could eradicate it,''
the statement said. ``That is equally true today.''
   Pesqueira said comprehensive figures on world hunger are
difficult to determine. The conference heard widely divergent
figures.
   Youssef Wali, Egypt's deputy prime minister and minister of
agriculture, cited statistics that said 512 million people in the
world suffer from hunger, and that the figure is increasing
annually by 10 million people.
   But Ide Oumarou, secretary-general of the Organization of
African Unity, said in a statement that 800 million people are
either temporarily or permanently hungry.
   He said the world produces 10 percent more food than it needs,
meaning the cause of hunger is ``a question of distribution and
imbalances created by international trade, not of shortage.''
   According to World Food Council reports, most malnourished
people live in Asia and Africa. Among seriously troubled countries,
it cited Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and
Sri Lanka in Asia and Ethiopia, Nigeria, Zaire, Tanzania, Kenya,
Uganda and Mozambique.
   Young children, pregnant and nursing women and the elderly are
the most vulnerable to hunger, the council says.
   It says malnutrition coupled with diarrhea and infectious
diseases kill an estimated 14 million children under age five every
year, and 83 percent of the malnourished people under five live in
Asia and about 12 percent in sub-Saharan Africa.
   The World Food Council urges help for poor countries to start
projects to become self-sufficient in food rather than depending
totally on deliveries of surplus food from richer countries.
   The 36-member council is to meet for four days, during which
delegates will tour projects north of Cairo where large sections of
desert are being reclaimed for agriculture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0129 </DOCNO>
