<FIRST>r w AM-CocaineEmergencies     05-22 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Emergencies,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Admissions For Cocaine on Rise, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Admissions to hospital emergency rooms for
cocaine-related abuses last year increased in 15 of 19 cities
surveyed by the National Institute on Drug Abuse, a congressional
panel said Monday.
   The leaders of the House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and
Control attributed this trend, in part, to ``a surge nationwide in
the supply and demand for crack,'' a cheap cocaine derivative.
   In a joint statement, Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., the
committee's chairman, and ranking Republican Lawrence Coughlin of
Pennsylvania also noted dramatic increases in marijuana emergency
room cases, with 16 of 19 cities reporting increases.
   ``This report documents the increasing seriousness of the drug
crisis,'' they said. ``Hospitals are facing a terrible public
health emergency because of drug-related cases. We have got to
develop a national strategy addressing supply and demand.''
   Emergency room admissions for cocaine abuse skyrocketed by 210
percent last year in New Orleans, and shot up by more than 100
percent in Philadelphia, Seattle and Washington.
   Admission rates also rose significantly in Atlanta; Boston;
Chicago; Detroit; Minneapolis; Newark, N.J.,; New Yor; Phoenix; San
Diego, and St. Louis. Record levels of admissions also were
reported for the states of Colorado and Texas, although no
statistics were available for individual cities in those states.
   Cocaine emergency room admissions fell in Miami and were stable
in Los Angeles and San Francisco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1549EST</FILEID>
