<FIRST>r a AM-LongtimeFugitive     05-22 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Longtime Fugitive,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers Push for Pardon for Woman Who Made New Life After Escape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted robber who escaped and created
a new life for herself during 10 years of freedom should be granted
a pardon because of her extraordinary success rehabilitating
herself, her attorney contends.
   The state Department of Probation, Parole and Pardon Services
will hear the case for pardoning Kay Smith, 37, on Tuesday. Mrs.
Smith, who was recaptured because of a tip from her ex-husband,
would be the first inmate to be pardoned since at least the 1940s
for any reason other than terminal illness.
   In South Carolina, pardons can be granted only by a special
board, and before it will consider a hearing, five of the seven
members must vote to approve an investigation.
   ``It is very rare that inmates request pardon hearings,'' board
spokesman David Allen said.
   In 1975, Mrs. Smith, then known as Pamela Rodgers, was convicted
in South Carolina on five counts of armed robbery and sentenced to
12 years in prison. She walked away from a work release program in
1978 and hitchhiked to Maryland.
   During the next decade, she earned her high school diploma,
overcame drug and alcohol abuse, married Ray Smith, raised a foster
child and two sons, and became a successful real estate agent.
   ``Her story is the most extraordinary story any of us has ever
heard about someone who has ever rehabilitated herself,'' said
Richard Harpootlian, her attorney in Columbia.
   ``Someone who was convicted of several armed robberies and a
drug problem, on the run took herself and pulled herself up by her
bootstraps to become a productive member of society.''
   Mrs. Smith's happy life ended in May 1988 when her previous
husband, convicted of murder in Idaho, tipped authorities to her
whereabouts. Mrs. Smith was returned to South Carolina to finish
her original prison sentence and one additional year for escape.
   Under an interstate agreement, Mrs. Smith was transferred last
fall to the Women's Correctional Institution in Jessup, Md., so she
could be closer to home.
   ``There's no reason for her being in there other than just
punishment,'' her husband said in a telephone interview from his
home in Severn, Md. ``She's made changes in her life, and it hasn't
cost anyone anything except her.''
   Smith, 40, said he and the couple's two teen-age sons from Mrs.
Smith's previous marriage would be at the hearing in Columbia.
   Mrs. Smith was unlikely to be allowed to attend because the
board did not request her presence, said her attorney in Baltimore,
John Hassett.
   Despite the lack of precedent, Hassett said he was optimistic.
   ``I spoke to her on Friday, and she and her family are also
extremely optimistic,'' he said. ``Dick Harpootlian and I both
believe we've put her case in the best possible posture for
consideration.''
   Should the pardon request be refused, Mrs. Smith will be
eligible for parole in April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
