<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--IntruderShot     05-22 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Intruder Shot,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Officer Wrestles With Intruder, Kills Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired police sergeant, who never
fired his gun during 26 years on the force, fatally shot an
intruder during a struggle in his home, authorities said.
   Earle Wolthausen, 76, drew his gun only once while with the Long
Beach Police Department.
   Sheriff's deputies said a man crashed his car into a garden wall
about a quarter-mile from Wolthausen's home Sunday morning. The man
walked past several homes and smashed Wolthausen's front window,
falling inside.
   The retired officer tried to restrain the struggling intruder
but couldn't. ``I was getting weaker and he was getting stronger,''
said Wolthausen, who retired in 1968 and has a heart condition.
   He called for his wife to bring him his gun and then had to
struggle with the intruder for control of it. Wolthausen wrestled
the weapon free and shot the intruder in the head. The dead man was
not immediately identified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
