<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1637EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FishStory 1stLd-Writethru a0630 05-22 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish Story, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0630,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grouper Diet: 5 Pounds Smelt and $600 Snacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT tropical to saltwater, since not all from
tropics, and subs the 10th graf, ``In the last,'' to CORRECT imperator
angels from $500 to about $250 each.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Question: What's 3{ feet long, weighs 35
pounds and lives on 5 pounds of smelt a day, plus nearly $5,000
worth of assorted exotic saltwater fish? Answer: The grouper that
ate Terry Haley's pet store aquarium.
   ``Day after day he got progressively larger and our inventory of
fish got progressively lower,'' said Haley, owner of Terry's
Aquarium &amp; Pet Center.
   The spotted jewfish, a type of grouper, was purchased for $150
and arrived at a petite one foot long and 3 pounds just 18 months
ago. It was caught off the Florida Keys.
   Haley put it in the store's 1,100-gallon saltwater show tank,
which once contained about 75 fish.
   Groupers are known to prey on smaller fish, but Haley thought he
could control what it ate by hand feeding it.
   That didn't work.
   ``He's eaten everything in the aquarium,'' Haley said Monday
from his store in this southern Chicago suburb. ``That's about
$3,000 to $5,000 worth of fish.''
   It's also the last straw for Haley, who said he plans to ship
the fish back to its native environment, where it can swim for its
own supper.
   The fish is fed 5 pounds of smelt a day, but the list of its a
la carte snacks from among its tank-mates is impressive.
   In the last six months, the grouper ate a clown trigger fish
worth $600, two imperator angels worth about $250 each, two queen
angels worth $150 each, one blue racer worth $50, and 50 yellow
tangs worth $20 each.
   Haley said he gave little thought to placing the expensive clown
trigger in the tank because groupers have not been known to include
them in their diet. But it didn't stop the grouper, which experts
say can grow to as much as 8 feet.
   ``It's in there for a day and turns into food,'' he said.
   Thinking a swift fish would be safe from the lumbering grouper's
jaws, Haley placed a 12-inch blue racer in the tank.
   ``The racer was in there about a month,'' he said. ``The grouper
just lay there and waited. It raced too slow one day and he was
gone.''
   In fact, the grouper has devoured everything except a couple of
6-foot moray eels and a nurse shark. But not for lack of trying.
   ``We came in one morning and it had the shark in its mouth about
halfway down,'' he said. ``We beat him with a broom handle and he
spit him out.''
   Haley bought the fish from Noyes Marine Life, an aquarium
supplier in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. and plans to return it to the sea
off that city on July 5. The fish will be flown to Florida and
released by divers, he said, adding that he doesn't know yet how
much that will cost.
   Haley offered the grouper to zoos and the Shedd Aquarium in
Chicago, but they said there was no room. The owners of a nearby
restaurant had another idea.
   ``They'd put their hands up to the tank and measure him and
smile,'' he said. ``They were really eying him up, but I can't
imagine anybody having our fish for dinner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
