<FIRST>u i AM-China-Glance     05-22 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Glance,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developments in China at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Developments on China at a glance:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MILITARY VOW</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   BEIJING _ More than 100 top military leaders vowed to refrain
from entering Beijing to confront or suppress the masses of
citizens who have seized control of the capital to demand
democratic reforms. The promise, in a letter to the People's Daily,
was a serious blow to Prime Minister Li Peng and other hardliners
who have tried to quell the demonstrations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MARTIAL LAW</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   BEIJING _ Members of the National People's Congress, China's
legislature, began gathering signatures needed to open a special
session on the legality of martial law, indicating a further
erosion in Li's support.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CLASH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   BEIJING _ Witnesses said soldiers with sticks and belts clashed
with crowds about 15 miles southwest of Tiananmen Square in an
apparently isolated incident whose cause was unclear. The clash,
which began late Monday and ended about 1 a.m. Tuesday (noon EDT
Monday), reportedly injured about 15 people. Tens of thousands of
students continued their peaceful occupation in Tiananmen Square in
defiance of martial law.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S.-CHINA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Wan Li, the head of the People's Congress, met
Monday with Vice President Dan Quayle and Secretary of State James
A. Baker III. Wan refused comment but Quayle said: ``We certainly
hope that the public demonstrations that have gone on in China and
continue will be successfully concluded without any violence.''
   President Bush came under pressure from a coalition of
conservative organizations and the Americans for Democratic Action,
a liberal group, to take a firmer stand in support of the
demonstrators.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HONG KONG STOCKS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   HONG KONG _ Share prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange
plummeted Monday as concern continued in the British colony over
its future when it reverts to China in eight years.
</TEXT>
