<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RooftopCo-Op     05-22 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rooftop Co-Op,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rooftop Co-Op: A Place in the Sun for $38,682</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   God's Little one-sixty-ninth of an Acre is now
available to sun-loving city-slickers for $38,682. The catch: it's
a slab of rooftop.
   ``The idea developed out of my own observation of the
marketplace and the general high demand for outside space that most
apartment buyers prefer,'' said Sheldon Stein, vice president of
Jacob Holm Inc., a development company.
   Stein decided to divide the roof of a Greenwich Village building
into 14 patio spaces and sell them to people who first buy a one-to
four-room apartment in the building for $130,000 to $212,000.
   ``New York, unlike most cities, has few park spaces or open
areas. And apartments are smaller, which makes New Yorkers desire a
little more freedom,'' he said Monday.
   Escape to this roof to view the Hudson River to the west,
midtown Manhattan to the north and Wall Street to the south. This
building is a story or two taller than its neighbors and zoning
restrictions have kept skyscrapers at bay.
   On the roof, $12,894 plus a monthly maintenance of $42.84 gets
you 235 square feet of tar beach with lights and running water,
enclosed by a 6-foot-high fence.
   Big spenders can pay $38,682 for 625 square feet, or just over
1-69th of an acre, with a maintenance charge of $128.52 _ 60
percent tax deductible.
   A 10-foot-wide common area will be decorated with plants.
   ``We wanted to give it a feeling of graciousness, so that people
weren't being corralled,'' said Stein.
   Security will be provided so that no one steals lawn chairs or
exercise bicycles.
   ``One guy may have dinner there, another may have a garden and
one may fly a kite,'' said Stein. ``On the issue of barbecuing,
we'd rather not discuss it. Technically, it's primarily for
sunbathing.''
   The management company has just started advertising the
apartments. The 300 people who called last weekend were told about
the added incentive of a rooftop co-op, and some of them seemed
interested, said Stein.
   In a city where parking spaces and yacht slips already are sold
for hefty prices, is there any limit to the type of property that
can turn co-op?
   ``I'm a real estate man _ that's a broad question,'' said Stein,
who once dreamed that co-op car ownership would be ``the way to
go.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
