<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Coehlo-Finances     05-22 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coehlo-Finances,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whip Supplemented Salary With Speeches, Rents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Finances, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tony Coelho, the House Democratic whip,
supplemented his salary by giving speeches and collecting rent on
property in California, his financial disclosure forms showed
Monday.
   The lawmaker's income ranged from $123,525 to $136,025 in 1988.
   His base salary was $89,500, boosted by rents of $5,000 to
$15,000, honoraria after charitable donations of $26,525 and
interest from a federal credit union of $2,500 to $5,000.
   Coelho, whose personal finances have recently drawn public
attention because of what he said was an error in his 1986
financial disclosure form, put most of his assets in a qualified
blind trust in June 1988.
   At the time, the California Democrat's holdings were worth
$65,000 to $150,000, with the largest investment _ a rental duplex
in Merced, Calif., _ valued at $50,000 to $150,000.
   The assets that Coelho kept out of the blind trust include
another rental property in Merced, valued at $50,000 to $100,000,
and savings accounts, money market accounts and individual
retirements accounts worth $25,000 to $80,000.
   Coelho listed no purchases or sale of property, stocks or bonds
in 1988, but he did refinance his principal residence in the
Virginia suburbs.
   That arrangement allowed him in October to pay off loans of
$80,000 to $200,000, the forms show. Coelho satisfied a commercial
loan of $50,000 to $100,000 from Federal City National Bank, a
$15,000 to $50,000 line of credit from Security Pacific National
Bank and the same line of credit from Wells Fargo Bank.
   Coelho also sent his trustee, I. Barry Mehler, a check for
$60,000 for inclusion in his blind trust last November, according
to an amendment filed to his 1987 financial disclosure. He did not
say where the money came from; his aides said they would ask.
   Excluding his blind trust, Coelho was left with one liability, a
50,000 to $100,000 mortgage on his Merced rental house from the
Tracy Savings and Loan institution.
   Under the 1978 Ethics in Government Act, lawmakers are not
required to reveal any details of transactions dealing with their
principal residence.
   Another exemption is details of a spouse's income. Coelho's
wife, Phyllis, works as an assistant to Rep. Andrew Jacobs, D-Ind.
   Coelho, a top fund-raiser for the Democratic Party and former
head of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, was an
active speaker on the lecture circuit last year, collecting
honoraria of $90,100. He gave $63,575 to charity, keeping $26,525,
a few hundred dollars short of the maximum allowed.
   Among those who gave Coelho $2,000 for speaking was Drexel
Burnham Lambert, a brokerage house that also picked up the tab for
Coelho to fly from Iowa to Los Angeles.
   The Washington Post has reported that Coehlo had not listed on
his 1986 disclosure forms a loan he obtained to buy $100,000 in
high-yield Drexel Burnham junk bonds. Coelho blamed the omission of
an oversight by his California accountant.
   Coelho, a member of the House agriculture committee, accepted
speaking fees from a number of groups that could have potential
business before the panel.
   They included the California Grocers Association, the American
Horse Council, The Fertilizer Institute and the Connell Rice and
Sugar Co.
   Coelho did a fair amount of traveling at other people's expense
to give speeches in 1988. Sometimes, the destinations were resorts.
But the only overseas trip was five days he spent in Israel on a
trip paid for by Project Interchange.
   The congressman and his wife spent two nights at Marco Island,
Fla., paid for by Puccio and Associates; he visited Palm Springs,
Calif., two times at the invitation of the Mexican-American Grocers
Association and the Tobacco Institute, and spent three days in
Yosemite National Park on a fact-finding trip paid for by the
Yosemite Park and Curry Co.
   Coelho, who suffers from epilepsy, traveled to New York once and
California three times for The Epilesy Foundation of America. He
also visited Texas, California and New York for the ``Tony Coelho
`Yes I Can' Disability Foundation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
