<FIRST>u w AM-AIDS-Colleges     05-22 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Colleges,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campus Survey Finds Higher Rate of AIDS Infection than Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College students are testing positive for the
AIDS virus more frequently than expected, but at a lower rate than
the population as a whole, researchers said Monday.
   A survey by the American College Health Association and the
Centers for Disease Control showed that 30 of the 16,861 students
who sought medical attention in their campus health centers tested
positive for the AIDS virus, for a rate of 0.2 percent.
   Nationwide, researchers believe 1 million to 1.5 million people
are infected, a rate of 0.4 percent to 0.6 percent.
   The study is the nation's first survey attempting to determine
the prevalence of AIDS among college students.
   The testing was done anonymously, and results were not broken
out for the 19 campuses selected to represent a cross section of
higher education in the United States
   Of the 30 students who tested HIV positive, all but two were
male. Officials did not release the gender breakdown of those
tested.
   No student tested positive at 10 of the schools, while five of
the schools had rates of 0.4 percent or higher. The highest campus
rate was 0.9 percent.
   Richard Keeling, director of student health services at the
University of Virginia and president of the American College Health
Association, said the 0.2 percent rate is higher than health
officials had projected. They had expected it would have been
closer to the rate for military recruits.
   Keeling said his advice to college students is that
``uninformed, unprotected, unsober sexual activity is highly
risky.''
   His message to the campuses is that they must be more aggressive
about AIDS education, working with students in small groups and
asking sensitive questions like: ``What do you say to him when he
says he won't wear a condom?''
   He said college health services must start offering more HIV
services, including testing and care for those who test positive,
including close medical surveillance of their immune systems. A
majority of college health services do not provide testing for HIV
infection and only a small number offer anonymous testing, he said.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious,
fatal disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. Spread
through contact with blood and semen of infected people, its chief
victims have been homosexual men and intravenous drug users. A
small percentage of cases have been caused by transfusions of
contaminated blood, heterosexual contact and spread from infected
pregnant women to their offspring.
   The survey was restricted to students who had routine blood
tests done at their student health centers, and Keeling said it was
not clear to researchers whether the sample may be overestimating
or underestimating the prevalence of the disease on the campuses.
   Helene Gayle, an epidemiologist at the Centers for Disease
Control who worked on the survey, said it is intended to give an
indication of the magnitude of the AIDS problem on college campuses
and is not an exact figure.
   The association said it will continue the study during the next
academic year and wants include several more schools, including
historically black institutions and some with predominantly
Hispanic students.
   The schools included in the survey were:
   Central Missouri State University-Warrensburg; Emory University,
Atlanta; Mississippi State University-Starkville; Northwestern
University, Evanston, Ill.; Rutgers University, New Brunswick,
N.J.; San Diego State University; Southern Illinois
University-Carbondale; University of California-Berkeley.
   University of Colorado-Boulder; University of
Connecticut-Storrs; University of Georgia-Athens; University of
Kansas-Lawrence; University of Maryland-Baltimore County and
College Park;
   University of Massachusetts-Amherst; University of New
Hampshire-Durham; University of Southern California-Los Angeles;
University of Texas-Austin and University of Washington-Seattle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
