<FIRST>r a AM-GrizzlyDogs     05-22 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grizzly Dogs,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Officials Hope Dogs Can Control Grizzlies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CODY, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Shoshone National Forest are
trying to find ways to teach grizzly bears to avoid humans and plan
to see if a Russian breed of dog used by bear hunters will do the
trick.
   Wyoming Game and Fish Department biologists have been
experimenting with bear aversion techniques in recent years, and
this year will continue testing a ``thumper gun'' that fires
plastic bullets to see if that will teach grizzlies to avoid people.
   But recently U.S. Forest Service officials received permission
to see if Russian bear dogs, a breed rare in this country, can be
used to scare off bears.
   The Russian hounds were not available in the past because
neither the Soviet Union nor Finland, where they are trained to
hold a bear at bay until a hunter arrives, would export the
animals. But Soviet restrictions have been loosened under the
glasnost campaign, and some of the dogs have found their way to the
United States.
   Monte Barker, a Forest Service wildlife biologist, said the dogs
now in this country haven't been trained as bear dogs, but he's
confident they could be.
   The small, quick dogs have been used primarily for bear hunting
and protection in the Soviet Union, where they are trained with
European brown bears, he said.
   The dogs' characteristics include fearlessness, courageousness,
speed, and a highly-developed sense of smell.
   ``Near as I can tell, it has the best nose of any dog there
is,'' Barker said.
   A proposal approved by the Management Subcommittee of the
Interagency Grizzly Bear Committee calls for Barker to collect
information on the dogs and try to get owners to bring the animals
to the Shoshone forest.
</TEXT>
