<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1830EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Missile     05-22 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Missile,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Joins Small Group of Nations with Ballistic Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India launched on Monday a rocket named
Agni, the Sanskrit word for fire, and became only the seventh
nation to develop a ballistic missile of its own.
   The missile has a range of more than 1,500 miles, enough to
reach targets as far away as Iran in the west, Hong Kong in the
east, China to the north and islands around the equator to the
south, Western military officials said.
   It can also hit any target in neighboring Pakistan, with whom
India has fought three wars since they became independent of
Britain in 1947.
   Military officials reached by telephone said the missile was
launched Monday at Chandipur, 750 miles southeast of New Delhi.
   By successfully firing the missile, India joined the United
States, Soviet Union, Britain, China, France and Israel in
developing its own such weapon.
   Monday's test was for a range up to about 620 miles, the
military officials said on condition of anonymity. One said the
guiding system, not the range, was the most implortant factor in
the test.
   ``Agni is not a weapons system,'' Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
said in a statement. ``However, the technologies proved in Agni are
deeply significant for evolving national security options.''
   He said the missile accurately followed a predetermined flight
path and ``fully met the objectives we had set for it.'' He did not
say how far the rocket traveled.
   It was the third attempt to launch the Agni missile. The first
launch date, April 20, was set back by problems with the ignition
system. A second date, May 1, was scrubbed because of an error in a
subsystem.
   Western military experts said the 1-ton payload capability means
the 7.5-ton Agni could carry a nuclear warhead, but Gandhi denied
the possibility was being considered.
   ``What Agni does is to afford us the option of developing the
ability to deliver non-nuclear weapons with high precision at long
ranges,'' he said. ``This provides us with a viable non-nuclear
option of the greatest relevance to contemporary strategic
doctrines.''
   Defense experts say a sophisticated guiding system would not be
needed for the missile to deliver a nuclear charge.
   ``You need accuracy or a point target if you are using a
conventional warhead,'' a Western analyst said privately, ``but if
you are using a nuclear warhead the exact target does not matter. I
am not saying that the Indians are going to use a nuclear warhead,
but the question is why not?''
   India exploded a nuclear device 15 years ago and Western nuclear
experts believe its scientists can assemble an atomic weapon in a
week.
   The government says its nuclear program is for such nonmilitary
purposes as power generation, and firing the missile was only a
``demonstration of the country's capabilities.''
   Agni is the fourth missile India has developed since 1983. Three
surface-to-surface and surface-to-air missiles with ranges of 20 to
about 150 miles also have been test-fired.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
