<SECOND>AM-Buffalo Mayor,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Griffin To Run For Fourth Term As Buffalo Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Griffin announced his candidacy
Monday for a fourth term as Buffalo mayor in typical fashion for
the maverick Democrat _ saying he'd seek the nomination of the
Republican Party.
   Griffin, who twice before has been defeated in Democratic
mayoral primaries, said it didn't matter how he got re-elected.
   ``If it goes like last time, fine,'' Griffin said. ``The people,
they make the decision, not the parties.''
   In 1985, Griffin lost in the Democratic primary, then switched
affiliations and won re-election to a third term on the GOP and
Conservative tickets.
   In 1977, Griffin lost the Democratic primary and won on the
Conservative ticket.
   State Assemblyman William Hoyt is the endorsed candidate for
mayor of the Democratic and Liberal parties. He could have as many
as four challengers in the Sept. 15 Democratic primary _ Griffin,
state Sen. Tony Masiello, former Chief City Judge Wilbur Trammell
and City Comptroller Robert Whelan.
   Griffin, 59, is expected to receive the endorsement of the
Republican Party sometime this week. The Conservative Party, which
supported him in his three previous campaigns, is expected to
endorse him Tuesday.
   Griffin said Monday that when he became mayor in 1977 Buffalo
was ``on the verge of bankruptcy.''
   He said its downtown was a disaster, unemployment rampant and
its housing decayed.
   ``Today the city has been brought back to life,'' he said,
noting numerous development projects, such as a new transit system,
minor league baseball stadium and waterfront projects.
   The mayor said 23,000 jobs had been ``saved or created'' and
that unemployment has fallen to 5 percent from 15 percent.
</TEXT>
