<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Nagy     05-22 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Nagy,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>1956 Revolt Leaders `Martyrs,' Should Be Rehabilitated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's foreign minister on Monday
said Imre Nagy and ``fellow martyrs'' who led the failed 1956
revolt against Stalinism were victims of show trials.
   Another senior communist urged the political and legal
rehabilitation of Nagy and his associates, captured and executed in
1958 after Soviet tanks and troops violently crushed the
short-lived 1956 revolt.
   The statements reflected growing demands for Nagy's
rehabilitation before June 16, the 31st anniversary of his
execution, and public questioning of the role of former leader
Janos Kadar in Nagy's demise.
   The state news agency MTI quoted Foreign Minister Gyula Horn as
saying Monday that it can ``be unequivocally stated that former
premier Imre Nagy and his fellow martyrs became the victims of
politically inspired show trials.''
   His statement before about 400 communists and non-party members
at a meeting in the northeastern city of Eger followed a weekend
demand from 400 communist reformers for Nagy to be rehabilitated
politically.
   Central Committee secretary Matyas Szueros was quoted Monday in
the communist party daily Nepszabadsag as saying ``we definitely
have to come to terms with the meaning of 1956 and the role of Imre
Nagy'' and his associates.
   ``There is a need for their political and legal rehabilitation,
as well as for the reinstatement of their human dignity,'' Szueros
was quoted as saying on Italian television Saturday night.
   A government commission is investigating the trial of Nagy and
other revolt leaders, who may be legally rehabilitated when the
probe is completed. Political rehabilitation would require the
Hungarian Socialist Workers' (communist) Party to revise its
official version of Hungary's history.
   Kadar, 76, has come under increasing fire since losing the party
leadership a year ago Monday. This month, the party's Central
Committee stripped him of his last political posts and said serious
mistakes had been committed in his 32-year rule.
   Kadar came to power at the end of the revolt, when Nagy and
leading associates were captured and imprisoned. They were executed
after summary trials in June 1958 on charges of counterrevolution.
   Previously buried in unmarked graves in a remote corner of a
Budapest cemetery, they are to be reburied at a June 16 ceremony
expected to draw tens of thousands of sympathizers and to be
broadcast live on Hungarian state television.
</TEXT>
