<FIRST>r a AM-TrailSuit     05-22 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trail Suit,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appalachian Trail Backers Sue Interior Department over Killington
Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUTLAND, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deal allowing a private ski resort to
cross the Appalachian Trail was improperly struck, three
environmental groups charged in a lawsuit filed Monday.
   The National Park Service in January approved an easement to let
the Killington Ski Area cut trees from a 200-foot corridor across a
1.2 mile stretch of the trail and cross it twice with ski runs.
   The park service also waived its right to review future
development by the resort at Mendon, the Appalachian Trail
Conference, Sierra Club and Vermont Natural Resources Council said
in their U.S. District Court lawsuit.
   The National Park Service and Interior Department were named in
the lawsuit. The park service and Killington officials have said
the easement was granted properly.
   ``Such wide-ranging development in the corridor of the
2,000-mile trail, much less waiver of future review of adjacent
development, has never been permitted in more than 1,750 other
negotiations with landowners from Maine to Georgia,'' the
environmental groups said in a statement.
   Environmentalists and Vermont's congressional delegation asked
the Interior Department in January how the Killington deal was
struck.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., has charged that the park service
ignored staff recommendations and decided the easements on
political grounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
