<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     05-22 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Stone-Throwers Kill Arab; Arabs Shoot At Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian was killed Monday by a rock
Israelis flung at his car, and gunmen attacked Israeli police in
the West Bank and soldiers who were hitchhiking in the Negev Desert.
   The Palestinian's death was the first reported since residents
of southern Israel began stoning Arab-owned cars after a soldier
was found killed in the area two weeks ago. Police blame
Palestinians for the soldier's death.
   At least 497 Palestinians have been killed in the uprising that
began more than 17 months ago in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Twenty-two Israelis also have been slain.
   Concern grew over Palestinian threats to increase the level of
violence and start using guns in the uprising, coupled with the
army's discovery of an arms cache in the Gaza Strip.
   Palestinian farmers in Gaza said soldiers bulldozed about 20
acres of Arab orchards and seized the land to build what appears to
be a military road along the territory's eastern border with Israel.
   Hashem Abba Shawa, head of the local Citrus Producers' Union,
said he complained to military authorities and requested
compensation for eight families. Army spokesman said they were
checking the report.
   In Gaza and the occupied West Bank, Israeli troops wounded seven
Palestinians with gunfire and shot seven others with rubber-coated
steel pellets in clashes with stone throwers, Arab doctors said.
   Among those injured by the pellets were six women aged from 12
to 55, they said.
   The stoning victim was identified only as a 42-year-old man from
Dura, near Hebron in the West Bank. He was hit by a rock apparently
thrown from a passing car near the coastal city of Ashkelon, police
spokesman Eli Elimelech said.
   Nili Nir, spokeswoman for Barzilai Hospital in Ashkelon, said
the man was dead of a head wound when he arrived.
   An army spokesman said no one was injured in Monday's shooting
attacks on Israeli police in Bethlehem and soldiers in the Negev
Desert.
   West Bank police spokesman Mordechai Baraket said unidentified
gunmen fired three pistol shots at police near Manger Square. One
shot hit the policmen's vehicle, he said, but no one was injured
and police arrested four suspects.
   In Navatim, five miles south of Beersheba, an assailant driving
a truck with Israeli license plates fired with an automatic weapon
at three soldiers waiting at a hitchhiking spot, Israeli radio
reports said.
   Army radio said the soldiers ran into a field and the gunman
fled. The soldiers were quoted as saying they thought the attacker
was an Arab.
   Police sealed the area, searched with a helicopter and
surveillance plane, and arrested dozens of Arab suspects, the radio
said. It said all were released after questioning.
   The arms cache, discovered during a six-day curfew in the Gaza
Strip, included 18 weapons, pistols, U.S.-made and Soviet automatic
rifles, Israeli submachine guns and Swedish Karl Gustav rifles, an
army announcement said.
   It was found during the roundup last week of of 250 activists of
the Moslem fundamentalist movement Hamas (Zeal).
   ``We are trying to detain as many Hamas activists as possible,''
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said in an Israel television
interview from the United States. In Gaza, he said, Hamas ``is more
than anything else responsible for crimes against the Palestinians
and the Israelis.''
   Itim, the Israeli news agency, quoted military officials as
saying a senior Hamas leader in the West Bank, Sheik Bassam Jarar,
was detained several days ago in Gaza, a Hamas stronghold.
   Hamas issued a statement in Nicosia, Cyprus, urging Arab nations
to ``open their borders to all those who want to fight against
Israel,'' Israel radio reported.
   Col. Renaan Gissin, deputy army spokesman, said Palestinians had
increased the use of firearms and noted that leaflets being
distributed by the Palestine Liberation Organization threaten to
kill an Israeli for every Palestinian who dies in the uprising.
   ``We are seeing more use of firearms generally. We see it as a
grave development,'' Gissin said in an interview.
   He added, however, that it was too early to tell whether
underground leaders of the rebellion were changing their policy
against the use of firearms.
   An Israeli paratrooper force raided the West Bank village of
Batir on Monday and arrested about 20 Palestinian suspects.
   Israel television showed blindfolded and handcuffed Arabs
sitting in a schoolroom. A Palestinian flag was painted on the wall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
