<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Cuba     05-22 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Cuba,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Sets Conditions for Improving Ties With Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday said the United
States won't consider improving relations with Cuba unless it makes
democratic reforms and frees political prisoners.
   Bush called on Cuban President Fidel Castro to reject the Soviet
military presence, hold a national plebiscite, free all political
prisoners, allow free emigration and grant unrestricted access to
international human rights monitoring groups.
   ``I am unalterably committed to a free, united and democratic
Cuba and I will never falter in that support,'' Bush said in
remarks before a group brought to the White House to recognize the
Cuban holiday celebrating independence from Spain.
   He accused Castro of squelching basic rights, such as freedom of
religion, assembly and speech.
   ``In response, our demand is plain and simple. Democracy and
respect for human rights, not sometimes, not someday, but now.''
   Bush said Castro should ``free all political prisoners and to
conform to accepted international standards regarding human rights.
I challenge him to allow unrestricted access to the United Nations
and other organizations monitoring their compliance, and a policy
of non-intervention in the internal affairs of other states.''
   Bush's tone contrasted with the restraint he has used in talking
about the pro-democracy demonstrations rocking China.
   In his speech, Bush mentioned China in passing, saying ``It is
important that the people of Cuba know the truth, and we will see
that the people of Cuba do know the truth about their dicator and
about the world...''
   ``And totalitarian systems everywhere are feeling new pressures
from the people. You see it today on the televisions sets coming
out of China. We've seen the those beginnings of it in the Soviet
Union and many, many other countries around the world.''
   Bush said he was challenging Castro ``to take concrete and
specific steps leading to free and fair elections and full
democracy. A useful first step would be to accept a proposed
plebiscite in Cuba.''
   Havana has not responded to international calls for a plebiscite
in which the Cuban people could vote for or against the communist
government that was installed when the Castro-led revolution came
to power in 1959.
   ``This I pledge,'' Bush said, ``Unless Fidel Castro is willing
to change his policies and behavior, we will maintain our present
policy toward Cuba.
   Bush referred to speculation that the change in administrations
in Washington this year might be an opening for a more relaxed
attitude toward Cuba after the long chill in relations.
   ``Knock off this wild speculation as just that _ some suggesting
that our administration is going to unitlaterally shift things with
Fidel Castro. I am not going to do that,'' Bush said.
   Bush said U.S. opposition to Cuba's re-entry into the
Organization of AMerican States would continue unless Castro
changed his policies. And he vowed to continue beaming radio
broadcasts into Cuba via the U.S.-government Radio Marti.
   ``In short, what we want to do is to advance that day when Cuban
independence day achieves a new and a richer meaning, freedom from
the evil of tyranny and oppression, freedom from the economic
misery wrought by the communist rule,'' he said.
   In February, a United Nations team that visited Cuba last
September reported on allegations of human rights abuses, which the
government denied.
   The investigating team said it received more than 1,600 human
rights complaints from Cuban prisoners, including 137 of torture,
cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
