<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     05-22 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Envoy Pleads For Release Of Missing Briton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Ambassador Allan Ramsay appealed
on television Monday for the release of 75-year-old Briton Jack
Mann, a World War II pilot believed kidnapped in Moslem west Beirut
10 days ago.
   ``My government does not make deals with hostage-holders,''
Ramsay said, speaking in Arabic over the Christian-run Lebanese
Broadcasting Corp. network.
   ``There must be something wrong with the mentality of those who
kidnap an old gentleman of 75 years of age to accomplish certain
objectives,'' he said.
   ``There's no way any gains would be won from such an abduction.''
   Mann disappeared May 13 and a group calling itself the Cells of
Armed Struggle later claimed it had kidnapped an unidentified
Briton.
   Ramsay indicated he believed the Briton held was Mann, who has
lived in west Beirut with his wife Sunny for more than 40 years.
   The Cells of Armed Struggle demanded release of unidentified
prisoners it claims are held in Britain in connection with the 1987
murder of leftist Palestinian cartoonist Naji Ali in London.
Scotland Yard said no one was detained or charged with the slaying.
   Ramsay said Mann and all other foreign hostages held in Lebanon
should be freed unconditionally. Besides Mann, 17 others are
missing _ nine Americans, three other Britons, two West Germans, an
Irishman, an Italian and a Belgian.
   The longest held hostage is American Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
   Pope John Paul II meanwhile appealed in a letter to 16 heads of
state and the U.N. secretary-general for steps ``to prevent the
destruction that threatens Lebanon,'' the Vatican said Monday.
   The pope said the violence wracking Lebanon was ``linked to the
intervention of armed forces of neighboring countries,'' and ``was
the responsibility of the entire international society.''
   He did not mention specific countries, but among heads of state
receiving the letter were leaders of Syria and Israel, who have had
forces in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
