<FIRST>u i AM-ArabSummit 1stLd-Writethru   05-22 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arab Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0646,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptian Wins Warm Welcome at Arab Summit; Gadhafi Hints He Will
Attend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Gadhafi hinting he will attend.
Edits to trim and conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
arrived Monday and received a warm embrace from Morocco's King
Hassan II that ended the Arab League's 10-year ostracism of Cairo.
   The 22-member league holds a special summit starting Tuesday,
and Libya's Moammar Gadhafi hinted that he dropped his plans to
boycott the meeting despite his opposition to Mubarak's presence.
   His statement came after he met with other Arab leaders in
Tripoli on Monday.
   As a 21-gun salute boomed, Hassan, wearing a traditional white
djellaba cloak and red fez, hugged Mubarak, who wore a Western
business suit.
   Although differences remain over Lebanon, Palestine and other
issues, Moroccan Foreign Minister Abdellatif Filali called Egypt's
readmission ``an important historic event ... that will boost Arab
solidarity.''
   Egypt's membership was suspended in 1979 after the late
President Anwar Sadat signed the Camp David peace accords with
Israel.
   The official Libyan news agency JANA, monitored in Rome, said
Gadhafi reached agreement with the leaders of Algeria, Syria and
Tunisia to oppose ``any concession at the Arab summit and to
boycott it if there was any hint of recognizing Israel.''
   Algeria's Chadli Bendjedid, Syria's Hafez Assad, and Tunisia's
Zine Abidine Ben Ali _ flew to Tripoli early Monday to persuade
Gadhafi to change his mind about skipping the meeting.
   Later Monday, Gadhafi flew to the western Algerian city of Oran,
where he was to meet again Tuesday with the three presidents,
Libyan television reported. It was not clear whether the summit
would be delayed by Gadhafi's meetings Tuesday.
   The Lebanese chair may stay vacant because of the dispute
between Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun and Moslem acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss. Their governments have been competing for
legitimacy since September, when Parliament failed to elect a
successor to President Amin Gemayel.
   A ministerial subcommittee on Lebanon met Sunday and Monday but
failed to resolve the bitter quarrel.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, initially insisted only
Hoss attend. Iraq, Syria's main Arab rival and Aoun's only
outspoken Arab backer, threatened to walk out if only Hoss were
invited, a conference source said.
   The source said Syria and Iraq ``reluctantly agreed'' the summit
should ask both men to express their views, but neither would be
considered the official representative of Lebanon.
   A second ministerial subcommittee met to consider rival working
papers on the Palestinian issue submitted by Syria and Yasser
Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organisation.
   The PLO paper complained Arab states have failed to pay promised
donations of a one-time lump sum of $128 million followed by $43
million a month to support the uprising in Israeli-occupied
territory.
   A PLO spokesman said only Saudi Arabia and Libya have paid a
total of $52 million. He said a possible cause was Arafat's
recognition of Israel and renunciation of terrorism.
   The preparatory committee agreed to a compromise between the PLO
and Syrian positions drafted by Egypt. It was the first substantive
Egyptian contribution to the Arab League since 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
