<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     05-22 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Solution of Missile Dispute Hinges on Timing of Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO Rift, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ending the dispute between the United
States and West Germany over short-range nuclear weapons depends on
the timing of U.S.-Soviet negotiations on the devices, officials
said Monday.
   Most of NATO's short-range nuclear warheads are deployed in West
Germany, and West Germany has been insisting on prompt superpower
talks on the weapons.
   The United States has taken the stand that such talks cannot
begin until the Soviets make substantial reductions in conventional
weapons in Europe.
   Diplomatic sources in Bonn, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said both sides ``have a along way to go'' in resolving the
conflict before a North Atlantic Treaty Organization summit opens
May 29.
   ``Progress has already been made because the United States is no
longer rejecting outright the notion of the talks,'' one source
said. ``We still have to work out the timing of when talks should
begin.''
   He said West Germany seeks a compromise with language making it
clear that the talks would begin ``within the foreseeable future
and not next century.''
   That is in line with West Germany's position that progress in
conventional-arms negotiations with the Soviets in Vienna should
lead quickly to talks on the short-range nuclear devices.
   Chief government spokesman Hans Klein said Monday discussions
with the United States are centered on conditions for the beginning
of such talks.
   A U.S. compromise accepting the talks in principle is coupled
with a demand that West Germany drop its insistence on ``prompt''
talks.
   Klein was asked about that and he said the word ``prompt'' ``can
have a broad interpretation.'' He declined to elaborate.
   He said Chancellor Helmut sent a letter to President Bush on
Monday outlining the West German position on Washington's
compromise proposal, but he declined to give details of the
letter's contents.
   He said Kohl would telephone Bush Tuesday for further
consultations.
   U.S. officials say that as part of a compromise Washington would
agree in principle to short-range weapons negotiations at some
point linked to progress in the Vienna talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
