<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     05-22 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Gather in Cambodian Capital for `Day of Hate'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 6,000 people gathered at a
memorial in Cambodia's capital to observe an annual ``Day of Hate''
marking the mass killings of the former Khmer Rouge government, the
Vietnam News Agency said.
   The ceremony took place Saturday at the 129-foot-high Buddhist
shrine in Phnom Penh's Cheung Ek district, where the Khmer Rouge
executed 20,000 people, the report said. The report was dated
Sunday and seen in Bangkok Monday.
   It said hundreds of Buddhist monks, Cambodians living overseas
and foreign diplomats attended the ceremony. Vice Premier Chea Soth
said in a speech that any settlement of the Cambodian conflict must
guarantee the Khmer Rouge do not return to power.
   The report said people laid wreaths at Toul Sleng Museum of
Genocide, an old school building the Khmer Rouge used as a torture
chamber.
   The Khmer Rouge overthrew the U.S.-backed government of Lon Nol
in April 1975. The fanatical communists then tried to fashion a
primitive agrarian society by moving people into slave labor camps.
More than a million died.
   Vietnam invaded in late 1978, drove the Khmer Rouge to the Thai
border and installed another communist government in Phnom Penh.
The Khmer Rouge is the strongest of three guerrilla groups fighting
the Vietnamese, whose announced total pullout by Sept. 30 triggered
fears of a Khmer Rouge return.
   Disagreement over the future role of the Khmer Rouge has stalled
talks between Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the main non-communist
guerrilla leader, and Hun Sen, prime minister of the Phnom Penh
government.
   According to a Vietnam News Agency account monitored Monday, Hun
Sen told the president of the non-aligned movement, Zimbabwe's
President Robert Mugabe, in a message last week that he would let
the Khmer Rouge run in a general election only as a political
party, with no military force.
</TEXT>
