<FIRST>r w AM-Conservatives-Fiske     05-22 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Conservatives-Fiske,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Choice Opposed by Conservatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservatives opposed to Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh's choice of a deputy attorney general are trying to
scuttle the nomination before it is sent to the Senate by President
Bush.
   The conservative Washington Legal Foundation has distributed
press packets containing material critical of Robert B. Fiske Jr.
as part of an effort to persuade Bush not to nominate the New York
attorney for the No. 2 job at the Justice Department.
   Fiske, a moderate Republican who once chaired the American Bar
Association's judicial screening panel, is accused by conservatives
of trying to thwart many of former President Reagan's appointees to
the federal bench.
   Representatives of various conservative organizations, such as
the American Conservative Union and the Free Congress Foundation,
have privately urged Bush administration officials not to send the
nomination to the Senate.
   ``I can't see how conservatives can do anything but be in
opposition to him becoming deputy attorney general,'' said Patrick
McGuigan, a scholar at the Free Congress Foundation.
   The conservative interest groups have enlisted support from Sen.
Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee
who has expressed misgivings about Fiske.
   On Monday, Humphrey wrote Bush to question Fiske's party
loyalty, citing the $1,000 that Fiske donated to a Democrat who ran
unsuccessfully last year for senator from Vermont.
   Humphrey, who released copies of his letter to Bush, wrote that
the $1,000 donation to the campaign of Democrat William Gray showed
that ``Fiske is not truly committed to the goals of a Republican
administration.''
   The donation ``raises profound questions about Mr. Fiske's
commitment to the Republican platform and your own judicial
philosophy,'' Humphrey said.
   In his letter, Humphrey said his concerns were shared by ``other
Republican members of the Judiciary Committee.''
   McGuigan said he has had numerous conversations with officials
at the White House and the Justice Department expressing
conservative opposition to Fiske.
   ``There can be no doubt in the minds of the White house and the
Department of Justice as to where its normal allies stand on the
Fiske nomination,'' McGuigan said.
   David Runkel, the attorney general's press secretary, said
Fiske's donation to Gray's campaign was based on personal
friendship, not politics.
   ``This guy is a personal friend, he served as U.S. attorney in
Vermont the same time Bob was U.S. attorney in Manhattan,'' Runkel
said.
   Meanwhile, the man Fiske wants to replace, Deputy Attorney
General Harold G. Christensen, will leave his job on June 1, the
department said.
   Christensen, who took office last fall following his
confirmation by the Senate, will return to private legal practice
in Salt Lake City, the department said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
