<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HouseFinances 1stLd-Writethru a0622 05-22 0950</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Finances, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most House Members Earn Money Outside Jobs, Disclosure Forms Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Wright blind trust and reworks in top 17 grafs,
picking up in 15th graf pvs, House Majority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of House members boosted their income
last year with speaking fees, investments and money from such other
sources as jewelry making and TV residuals, disclosure forms showed
Monday. House Speaker Jim Wright paid off at least $105,000 in debt
but may have had to dig into personal assets to do it.
   The most common addition to congressional pay was in fat fees
from interest groups in exchange for giving speeches.
   Almost all House members have outside investments, some
substantial.
   Some earn money from previous careers _ including pensions.
   Some moonlight.
   For example, Rep. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, D-Colo., a Northern
Cheyenne Indian, earned $5,000 last year for his jewelry designs.
   Rep. Tom McMillen, D-Md., a former National Basketball
Association player, received deferred income totaling $45,000 from
the Washington Bullets and Atlanta Hawks. He also reported $10,000
in income for renting space and equipment to his re-election
campaign.
   The disclosure forms filed annually by all 535 members of the
House and Senate provide a look at Congress' outside income and the
wealth _ or lack thereof _ of each member. Each form lists a
member's money received, his assets and liabilities.
   The Senate reports were released last Friday.
   House members are limited to earning an additional 30 percent _
or $26,850 _ in honoraria for appearances. Most lawmakers donate
anything over that to charity.
   The forms do not provide precise data on congressional income,
listing only ranges. For example, properties worth $52,000 and
$98,000, respectively, both would be listed in the
$50,001-to-$100,000 range. An asset worth millions could be listed
simply as more than $250,000 unless a member chose to spell it out.
   This often shrouds the true wealth of an individual member but
does provide a guide to where that lawmaker derives investment and
other income.
   Wright, who has been under investigation for allegations that he
used his leadership position for financial gain, got out of debt in
1988, according to his disclosure statement.
   His debt: Somewhere between $105,000 and $200,000 was paid off,
leaving Wright with no financial liabilities.
   His assets: Somewhere between $31,005 to $100,000, compared with
a range of $155,000 to $435,000 in 1987. But the current accounting
does not include holdings in the blind trust he established in 1987.
   House members' homes also needn't be listed.
   The financial disclosure statements show that honoraria _
generally fees for outside speeches _ were an important part of the
incomes of many of the 435 House members, supplementing a federal
salary which in most cases comes to $89,500.
   House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., the third-ranking
House Democrat, doubled his salary last year with $90,100 from 53
paid speeches. To get under the House ceiling in honoraria, he gave
$63,575 to charity in 177 separate donations.
   House Republican leader Bob Michel of Illinois reported income
of $165,865 to $180,864 and assets of $165,000 to $400,000. He
earned twice the $30,000 Wright earned in speaking fees, giving
$30,900 out of the total $60,500 to charity.
   Michel listed some of the side benefits of taking part in
charity golf tournaments: $966 worth of golf clothing and
paraphernalia from the Bob Hope Desert Classic, the Kemper Open,
the Jerry Ford Invitational and others.
   House Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., reported income
of $134,250 to $138,250. Most of the excess over his $99,500
leadership salary came from fees for speeches.
   Foley was among many House members who accepted trips. The Japan
Society in New York picked up the air fare and hotel tab for travel
to Hong Kong and Tokyo to attend a conference.
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia, who said his
assets are no more than $45,000, did not list any royalties in 1988
from his book, ``Window of Opportunity.''
   A complaint is pending before the House ethics committee in
connection with a limited partnership formed in 1984 to promote the
book.
   Gingrich's expenses were reimbursed on 11 trips for speeches to
various groups. GOPAC, a political action committee chaired by
Gingrich which promotes Republican candidates, paid the expenses on
14 trips by Gingrich and three by his wife.
   Here is how some lawmakers _ including two former actors and a
major league pitcher _ added to their congressional incomes in 1988:
   _ Fred Grandy, R-Iowa, reported $20,021 in residual income from
the ``The Love Boat,'' the long-running series in which he played
Gopher.
   _ Rep. Ben Jones, D-Ga., reported $11,212 in residuals. Jones
appeared on the ``Dukes of Hazzard.''
   _ Rep. Jim Bunning, R-Ky., a former pitcher, got a $350 royalty
check from the Major League Baseball Players Alumni Association.
   _ Rep. Mervyn M. Dymally, D-Calif., was reimbursed by a variety
of groups last year for two sweeps across Africa and trips to
Israel, Japan, Korea, Puerto Rico, Brazil and Saudi Arabia.
Expenses also were paid for seven trips inside the United States.
   While 1988 was a story of income enhanced for many House
members, some did less well.
   Rep. Barton Jennings Gordon, D-Tenn., lost nearly $68,000 when
his investment in a trust fell from 118,355 to $50,461. ``A
partnership trust that he was in went bankrupt,'' said spokesman
Harrison Wadsworth.
   The disclosure forms call for listing gifts valued at $100 or
more.
   Rep. Andrew Jacobs, D-Ind., listed as gifts ``zero things and
zero money.''
   Among Jacobs' assets: A Great Dane, ``Friend,'' housebroken and
listed as priceless and a cocker spaniel, ``Annie,'' not completely
housebroken and listed as a current liability.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0182 </DOCNO>
