<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Cabinet     05-22 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Cabinet,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Debates Bill On Letting Blacks Join Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators opened debate Monday
on a bill to let blacks serve in the Cabinet while remaining
excluded from Parliament.
   The government says the aim is to bring a black into the Cabinet
for the first time, possibly as minister or deputy minister in
charge of black education.
   The governing National Party supports the bill but parties to
its left and right oppose it. The measure would allow the president
to appoint people to the Cabinet even if they were not members of
Parliament.
   Parliament includes a chamber for Asians, a chamber for people
of mixed-race, and the dominant white chamber. The black majority
has no formal role in national affairs.
   The Rev. Allan Hendrickse, leader of the mixed-race chamber,
said during Monday's debate that he knew of no prominent black
leaders who supported the bill and described the government move as
``tokenism.''
</TEXT>
