<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-22 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Scattered Across The Plains, Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms brought locally heavy rain Monday to the southern
and northern Plains and the Southwest.
   Thunderstorms across southern Oklahoma and southern Arkansas
produced strong wind and large hail during the morning.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
1.06 inches at Little Rock Air Force Base, Ark.
   Power lines were blown down at Stringtown, Okla., and several
trees were toppled by thunderstorm wind near Valliant, Okla., the
National Weather Service said.
   Recent heavy rain in the region made rivers rise across eastern
Oklahoma, southern Missouri and sections of Arkansas. The North
Canadian River at Woodward, Okla., was almost 2 feet above flood
stage, the weather service said.
   A cold front moving across the northern Plains triggered strong
thunderstorms over eastern North Dakota with locally heavy rain and
hail.
   Warm, moist air from the Gulf of Mexico generated thunderstorms
across southern Mississippi, eastern Tennessee, northwestern
Georgia, and from northeastern Florida to eastern North Carolina.
   Scattered showers fell over the Pacific Northwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Redmond, Ore., and Oak Harbor, Wash., to 100 at Midland,
Texas. Monday's low for the 48 contiguous states was 28 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the eastern half of the Gulf Coast to the Appalachians, the
eastern half of the Ohio Valley and the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast, and from central Nebraska across Iowa to the upper
Great Lakes. Scattered showers were forecast over the northern and
central Pacific Coast and inland to the northern Rockies, and over
northern Maine.
   Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted from the northern and
central Pacific Coast to the northern Rockies; in the 90s across
Florida, the Gulf Coast, much of the central and southern Plains,
the southern Rockies and interior Southern California; between 100
and 105 degrees from southwestern Texas into the desert Southwest;
and generally in the 70s and 80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
