<HEAD>Former Westinghouse Executive Chosen for Commerce Slot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday he would nominate
Thomas Joseph Murrin, a former senior executive of Westinghouse
Electric Corp., to be deputy secretary of Commerce.
   If confirmed by the Senate, Murrin would succeed Donna F. Tuttle.
   Murrin, who lives in Pittsburgh, was president of the
Westinghouse Energy and Advance Technology group from 1983-87.
Previously he served in a variety of vice president posts at
Westinghouse divisions.
   He would hold the No. 2 job at Commerce, after Commerce
Secretary Robert Mosbacher.
</TEXT>
