<HEAD>Increased Fighting Reported at Kandahar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem rebels killed 61 soldiers in
weekend attacks around Kandahar in southeastern Afghanistan, the
guerrillas' Afghan News Agency reported Monday.
   It said Latif Aryan, identified as the provincial chief of
secret police, and four of his agents were among those killed.
   Other rebel sources earlier reported increased fighting around
the battered, ancient city where rebels have put communist forces
under intermittent siege for almost two years.
   ANA said mujahedeen, or Islamic ``holy warriors,'' concentrated
weekend rocket attacks on Kandahar's military airport, destroying a
jet bomber, a tank, two other vehicles and a fuel pumping station.
The agency said four mujahedeen were wounded. There was no
independent confirmation.
   Both sides in the Afghan war often make exaggerated and
contradicting claims and verification is rarely possible.
   The Soviet-backed People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan
seized power in a bloody 1978 coup. Mujahedeen, backed mainly by
Pakistan and the United States, are fighting to topple it and
establish an Islamic system of government.
</TEXT>
