<FIRST>r a AM-Non-FallingTower     05-22 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Non-Falling Tower,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dynamite Couldn't Bring Tower Down Despite Being Deemed Structurally
Unsafe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neighbors of a high-rise apartment
building were kept away Monday while demolition experts worked out
plans to bring down the building that wouldn't fall.
   ``We told you so,'' said a grass-roots neighborhood organization
which had argued the building and two others were solid enough to
be renovated for low-income housing.
   More than 550 pounds of dynamite failed to bring the 36-year-old
building down Sunday, although a second round of explosives knocked
out the first two floors, leaving the main part of the building and
a wing leaning against each other.
   Two businesses in the area remained closed and four homes
evacuated. Police posted a 14-man detail around the building, and
traffic was rerouted.
   The neighborhood organization, Project BASIC, had tried
unsuccessfully in federal court to stop the demolition of the
10-story Hartford Park building, claiming it was structurally sound.
   Group officials said they hoped the failure of two blasts to
bring down the building would help their case when they try to stop
the demolition of two other 90-unit buildings in the project.
   ``It makes our position better,'' said group spokesman Anthony
Hempfer. ``We will be submitting this as evidence.''
   ``Some people might find this amusing,'' said Stephen O'Rourke,
head of the city's housing authority. ``To me it's a nightmare.''
   ``Why didn't it fall? That's an open question,'' said David R.
Evans, the explosives expert who coordinated the blasts. ``I
knocked out the two floors I wanted to knock out and, by all
indications, the building should have fallen.''
   ``It's the way it's built,'' Evans said. ``It's built like a
honeycomb.''
   Earlier this month, an 87-year-old grain silo in Forth Worth,
Texas, came down only after repeated blasts with more than 700
pounds of dynamite.
   The Providence Housing Authority decided to switch from
explosives to a wrecking crane, which will begin work Tuesday, said
O'Rourke, who said the process could take up to two weeks.
   U.S. District Judge Raymond Pettine had allowed the housing
authority to continue with its plans to raze the building after
engineers testified the 2,300 holes drilled in the building to hold
the dynamite had made it structurally unsafe.
   During a hearing earlier this month, a housing authority
engineer testified that the building probably would not withstand a
40-mph wind, said Project BASIC.
   Project BASIC had argued that the low-rise units slated to
replace the building would not provide enough affordable housing to
compensate for the lost units.
   The failed attempt to bring the building down ``clearly
demonstates the structural integrity of the Hartford Park
highrises,'' the group said in a statement. ``We told you so.''
   ``Given the strength of these buildings, they can and should be
rehabilitated and occupied by families and individuals in need of
safe, decent and affordable housing,'' it said.
   O'Rourke, however, said the structural safety of the building
was not at issue.
   ``They were coming down for sociological reasons, to lower the
density of the site,'' he said.
   A hearing on Project BASIC's attempt to stop the demolition of
two other Hartford Park buildings was scheduled for June 6.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
