<FIRST>r w AM-Ruder-Takeovers     05-22 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ruder-Takeovers,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Chief Says Congress Should Consider Limiting Takeovers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission said Monday that Congress should consider passing
legislation to restrict the power of states to limit corporate
takeovers.
   David Ruder said the state and federal partnership governing
securities laws is undergoing a severe test because of a growing
tendency by states to pass restrictive laws asserting state control
over outside takeover attempts of local companies.
   In remarks prepared for a New York conference on corporate
financing, Ruder noted the SEC has stated previously the agency's
belief that anti-takeover statutes passed by state legislatures in
New York and Delaware were unconstitutional.
   He said he believes Congress could eventually be forced to
address this question by limiting the power of states to restrict
takeover attempts.
   ``Limitations on the free transferability of securities of
corporations that are owned by shareholders nationwide diminish the
efficiency, depth and liquidity of the nation's securities
markets,'' Ruder said.
   ``Federal law should control in this area by pre-empting state
statutes that unduly interfere'' with the buying and selling of
securities, he said.
   Ruder, who announced last week that he was stepping down as SEC
chairman to return to teaching at Northwestern University's law
school, said that unless state legislatures on their own stop
passing antitakeover legislation, Congress should enact
restrictions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
