<FIRST>r w AM-Arms     05-22 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Leaders Urge Security Through United Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders in six countries will press an
initiative for disarmament through the United Nations, they said
Monday in a statement sent to Presidents George Bush of the United
States and Mikhail Gorbachev of the Soviet Union.
   They are Presidents Raul Alfonsin of Argentina and Carlos
Salinas de Gortari of Mexico, former President Julius Nyerere of
Tanzania and Prime Ministers Rajiv Gandhi of India, Ingvar Carlsson
of Sweden and Andreas Papandreou of Greece.
   Five years ago, leaders of the six countries launched their
appeal directly to the leaders of the United States and the Soviet
Union.
   ``The international situation has seen important changes,'' they
said in their statement. ``The relationship between the two
superpowers has improved... We now believe that the purpose of the
initiative can best be pursued through the United Nations.''
   The statement was accompanied by letters to Bush and Gorbachev,
the contents of wwhich were not disclosed.
   It called for a comprehensive treaty to ban nuclear tests or any
use of nuclear weapons, with a schedule for eliminating the
weapons, a ban on the use in new weapons of nuclear material from
disarmed weapons, a U.N. verification system on disarmamanemt, a
convention on chemical weapons, and prevention of the use of outer
space for military purposes.
   The statement was released by Argentine Ambassador Enrique
Candioti, who delivered the letter to U.S. authorities.
</TEXT>
