<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-China     05-22 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-China,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Official Says Restrained Use of Power Intended</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese official told Vice President Dan
Quayle on Monday the Beijing government had agreed at the start of
ongoing mass demonstrations that authorities would refrain from
violence, an administration official said.
   But Wan Li, head of China's National People's Congress, the
Chinese legislature, also told Quayle that restoring order in China
would be the first priority and no progress can be made toward
promised reforms during the current upheaval.
   Wan met with the vice president and later with Secretary of
State James A. Baker III during an 11-day visit to the United
States.
   He refused to comment on the situation despite persistent
questioning by reporters, and was described as ``very careful'' in
his talk with Quayle.
   ``He was careful to position himself on either no side or every
side of this thing,'' in that meeting, said the administration
official, who said also that Wan was careful to point out that most
of the tension in Beijing and the imposition of martial law has
occurred since he left the country for his trip.
   However, Wan did say that before he left the country several
days ago, ``They agreed not to use violence,'' against the
demonstrators, said the source.
   His visit to Washington came as more than 100 top military
leaders vowed Monday to refrain from entering Beijing to suppress
the demonstrators who have seized control of the capital.
   Also Monday, members of Wan's People's Congress began gathering
signatures needed to open a special session on the legality of
martial law, sources said, indicating a further erosion of Wan's
support.
   Early Tuesday, witnesses said soldiers clashed with crowds at
one intersection. Witnesses said soldiers hit people with sticks
and belts, but did not open fire. The incident appeared isolated.
   One report said 15 residents were injured.
   The administration declined immediate comment on the violence,
in part because it was unclear whether the incident was ordered as
part of a strategy or was just an isolated occurrence, said one
official.
   Quayle, asked about the matter, told reporters during a photo
session with Wan that he hoped for a nonviolent solution to the
Chinese strife.
   ``We support the advancement of democracy, freedom and human
rights around the world,'' he said. ``We certainly hope that the
public demonstrations that have gone on in China and continue will
be successfully concluded without any violence.''
   During his meeting with Wan, Quayle underscored the U.S.
``interest in human rights and democratization worldwide, and the
hope that China would continue its political development and
economic reforms,'' the vice president's press office said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
