<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     05-22 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rally in Armenia Demands Leadership Be Deposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crowd estimated at 200,000 demanded at a rally
in downtown Yerevan that Armenia's president, prime minister and
Communist Party chief be replaced, a local activist said Monday.
   Rafael Popoyan said in a telephone interview that the
demonstration, held Sunday in the Armenian capital, also demanded
resolution of the long-festering conflict over Nagorno-Karabakh, a
largely Armenian enclave in Azerbaijan.
   Ethnic clashes over Nagorno-Karabakh, which many Armenians want
annexed to their southern republic, killed more than 90 people last
year.
   Popoyan said the rally decided to suspend a 4-day-old general
strike in anticipation of Thursday's opening of the nation's new
parliament, the Congress of People's Deputies. He said the strike
may be renewed if the congress fails to address the question of
Nagorno-Karabakh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
