<FIRST>u i AM-China-Politics     05-22 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Politics,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tiananmen Square, Symbol and Battleground</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiananmen Square has become a garbage-strewn
encampment for students demanding more freedom and a symbolic field
of battle in the political struggle within China's leadership.
   A citizen said late Monday night, while manning a roadblock to
keep soldiers out of the the city: ``Every four years you have
elections in America and change your government. Every 10 years we
have riots and change ours.''
   The main political combatants are Premier Li Peng, who is cool
to political reform and appears to have support from Deng Xiaoping,
the 84-year-old leader; and Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang,
known as a relative liberal.
   Both have tried to manipulate the students.
   Under Deng's orders, according to reports, Li has equated the
movement with ``turmoil'' and tried to give the impression of
strong leadership by crushing it.
   Zhao has tried to use the discontent as a springboard back into
the favor of both people and party.
   Neither has succeeded.
   Li ordered martial law Saturday, but the soldiers surrounding
Beijing have yet to enter the city.
   Zhao won points with the people by visiting hunger-striking
students last week, tears in his eyes, but Chinese sources say he
has lost support in the party.
   Those apparent failures introduced two new elements: the
military and representatives of the National People's Congress.
   On Monday, seven leading generals expressed opposition to
martial law and said the People's Liberation Army should not enter
Beijing.
   Nie Rongzhen and Xu Xiangqian, the nation's last living
marshals, said Sunday night the army would not suppress the
students. Their announcement in all official media clearly limited
Li's order, which gave the military the right to taken any steps
necessary to restore stability.
   The military appears to be saying it is not willing to be used
as a pawn and wants the political squabble to stop.
   Also Monday, sources said representatives of the National
People's Congress, China's legislature, were collecting signatures
on a petition for a special meeting to consider the legality of
Li's martial-law order.
   The Science and Technology Daily reported Monday that 24
deputies sent a letter saying the disturbances should be ended ``by
democratic and legal methods.''
   Students and intellectuals have been part of other political
power struggles in Communist China's 40-year history, such as the
1956 Hundred Flowers campaign and the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution
by the radical left.
   A brief student campaign for democracy in the winter of 1986-87
led to the downfall of Communist Party chairman Hu Yaobang, a
relative liberal whose death April 15 inspired the current movement.
   Beijing is a sea of rumor and innuendo, with no free press to
help sort it out. Within one week, various sources have reported
that Li and three others had seized power, that Zhao had resigned,
that Li and Deng had stepped down and that President Yang Shangkun
was preparing a coup.
   To that confusion can be added the contradictory tone of the
official press. On Monday, the front page of the People's Daily
carried both an editorial favoring the crackdown and a story
criticizing martial law.
   The student movement is largely a product of Deng's opening to
the West and his economic reforms.
   Students know of the People Power uprising that ousted President
Ferdinand E. Marcos of the Philippines three years ago and about
student protest in South Korea. It would be difficult to close
China again.
   Lacking a victory by one of the three top leaders, a vacuum at
the top could result.
   Right now, Li appears weakest because he declared martial law
but could not enforce it.
   Zhao's position has not been strong for months. He has been
blamed for record-high inflation and an overheated economy,
associated with his policy of introducing elements of a market
economy in the state-run system.
   Deng has been is shaken because 11 years of popular economic
liberalization were not accompanied by political reform.
   ``Right now the stage is empty,'' a government source said.
``All the people in the audience are on their feet clapping for a
new leader, but no one is coming out. I think this is a tragic
moment in our history.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   John Pompret is a correspondent for The
Associated Press in Beijing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
