<FIRST>r w AM-US-NATO 1stld-writethru a0727 05-22 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-NATO, 1st ld-writethru, a0727,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Germany Responds to US Missile Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To Update with official saying issue unsettled, adds 2 grafs
after 3rd graf previous, ``Popadiuk said''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said Monday it is
studying a response from West Germany to a proposed U.S. compromise
on the issue of short-range missiles in Europe.
   Deputy White House press secretary Roman Popadiuk said the
response, received Monday afternoon, had been discussed with
President Bush by national security adviser Brent Scowcroft.
   Popadiuk said he had ``no details or characterization'' of the
latest proposal to cross the Atlantic. ``It is being studied,'' he
said.
   However, another U.S. official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the issue was ``still unsettled.''
   The official said the reply had neither advanced nor lessened
prospects for a settlement. ``We're not home yet,'' the official
said.
   Bush on Sunday voiced optimism that the U.S.-West German dispute
which has split NATO would be resolved before the alliance's
40th-anniversary meeting begins next Monday in Brussels.
   The flap centers on whether to negotiate with the Soviets on
reducing the size of NATO's nuclear arsenal in western Europe.
   The West German government, responding to heavy political
pressure for disarmament, has supported such talks. The United
States has generally held that East-West negotiations on the
weapons should begin until the East's superiority in conventional
arms is erased.
   Last Friday, the U.S. side gave West German Defense Minister
Gerhard Stoltenberg a compromise offer that West German officials
privately said opened the door to eventual U.S.-Soviet negotiations.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, who spent the weekend in
Kennebunkport, Maine, with Bush at the president's oceanside
retreat, said Saturday the German stance was ``too vague'' for a
deal.
   The Germans thus far have insisted on leaving open the option of
eliminating all NATO and Warsaw Pact short-range missiles in any
negotiations.
   Under the U.S. proposal, meanwhile, negotiations would be held
only after NATO and and Warsaw Pact nations agreed on cuts in
conventional forces that would reduce the East's superiority.
   Earlier Monday, Popadiuk called the issue a ``NATO-wide issue,
and it's one that affects all members, and all members have a view
on it, and of course, all views are welcome.''
   ``The issue will be worked and hopefully will be resolved before
the NATO summit so that we can have a successful NATO summit,''
Popadiuk said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
