<FIRST>u a AM-SwindallTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0626 05-22 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0626,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unsealed Briefs Show Govt Plans In Former Congressman Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with unsealing of prosecution
briefs; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecution briefs unsealed Monday for the
perjury trial of former U.S. Rep. Pat Swindall show the government
hopes to show that he plotted how he would lie publicly about a
shady loan deal.
   In one brief unsealed in U.S. District Court on the eve of juror
questioning, the prosecution argues that public statements Swindall
made after his allegedly false grand jury testimony are relevant to
the case because they point to ``a continuation of Swindall's
attempts to limit his own potential criminal exposure.''
   Swindall, 38, is accused of lying under oath in 1988 to a
federal grand jury investigating his dealings with Charles
LeChasney, an associate and now-admitted money launderer, and
``Mike Martinez,'' actually Mike Mullaney, a federal agent posing
as a money broker for probable drug dealers.
   Swindall was indicted Oct. 17 on 10 counts of lying to a federal
grand jury, each of which carries a penalty of 10 months to five
years in prison. The indictment contends he lied in concealing from
the grand jury his discussions on how the movement of money would
be concealed to protect him.
   Swindall, a two-term Republican congressman from Atlanta's
eastern suburbs, lost his seat last November to Democrat Ben Jones.
An attempt at a speedy trial before election day collapsed after
jurors received Swindall campaign material proclaiming his
innocence in the mail.
   In the brief, the prosecution says it wants to enter as evidence
statements Swindall made in later interviews and news conferences
which are ``clearly false,'' as shown by a tape-recorded phone
conversation between the congressman and the agent.
   At one point in that conversation, the agent, posing as a broker
funneling Swindall money through LeChasney as middleman, asked the
congressman what he would say if anyone started asking questions.
   ``What's wrong if I say I sold the note to someone Charles
LeChasney introduced me to and I don't know what his name is and I
really didn't care,'' Swindall replied.
   ``There's no question in this transaction that I am basically
using Charles as my buffer,'' Swindall said in another conversation
related in the prosecution brief.
   Swindall's attorney wants to prevent any use of post-grand jury
statements by the congressman, on the grounds that they are not
relevant to the issue of whether he lied to the panel.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Freeman unsealed several motions and
trial briefs after objections from news organizations. But two
other government briefs must remain secret because they contain
``highly sensitive'' information not previously reported in the
media, he said.
   Since potential jurors might read or hear new news reports,
there is a substantial chance that reporting on the sensitive
information might taint the jury, Freeman ruled.
   The judge set aside Monday for 75 potential jurors to fill out
questionnaires and for lawyers on both sides to study them.
Courtroom questioning of the potential jurors is expected to begin
Tuesday.
   Freeman has said he wants to see if an impartial jury can be
seated before ruling on Swindall's request to move the trial out of
town because of prejudicial publicity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
