<FIRST>r a AM-KermitRobberyTrial     05-22 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kermit Robbery Trial,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Starts Tuesday for Two Accused in Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men accused of helping stage the
state's biggest bank robbery go on trial Tuesday in a case in which
authorities say one witness was murdered, another died of unknown
causes and jailed suspects plotted to kill other witnesses and flee
to the Cayman Islands.
   ``I've been wracking my brain, trying to find a way to summarize
it for the jury,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Ben Bryant.
   ``These people are just too zany,'' Bryant said of the
defendants. ``They've been watching too much television.''
   John P. McCoy, 43, of Slater's Branch, Ky., and Doyle David
Moore, 27, of Lovely, Ky., go on trial Tuesday in U.S. District
Court in Huntington on charges of conspiracy to commit bank robbery
and intimidating witnesses.
   McCoy also faces a murder charge in the shooting death of
Russell M. Davis of Martin County, Ky., who was part of the robbery
gang.
   The Matewan National Bank in Kermit was robbed of more than
$286,000 on Jan. 3, 1987. Authorities say McCoy masterminded the
heist, in which he was joined by Moore, Davis and Harold D.
``Boonie'' Runyon, 39, of Forest Hills, Ky.
   Davis met with Secret Service agents in Jacksonville, Fla.,
shortly after the robbery and agreed to become a government
witness. A few days later, authorities say, Runyon and McCoy took
him to the top of a Kentucky mountain and shot him in the head.
   ``He was a threat to us,'' Runyon said Friday in pleading guilty
to the Davis killing and to a charge of conspiracy to commit
robbery. ``There was no reasoning with him. We took him to a hill
and shot him.''
   Runyon said he and McCoy buried Davis in a shallow grave on Ford
Mountain in Pike County, Ky. The body was not discovered until last
February.
   McCoy, Moore and Runyon were indicted by a federal grand jury in
March in the robbery, and a murder charge later was added against
McCoy and Runyon. Moore was not charged in the Davis killing.
   Runyon, who had been scheduled to stand trial with McCoy and
Moore, could be sentenced to life in prison on the murder count and
five years for the robbery charge, plus $500,000 in fines.
   Earlier this month, Timothy Lynn Sammons, 30, of Beauty, Ky., a
friend of Davis who appeared before the grand jury, was found dead
in his car. Martin County Coroner Jay Hinkle said Monday the cause
of death still has not been determined but said foul play is not
suspected.
   McCoy, Runyon and four others _ including McCoy's son _ were
charged May 6 in an alleged plot to break McCoy, Runyon and another
man out of jail, kill five witnesses and help the prisoners flee to
the Cayman Islands in the Caribbean.
   Prosecutors said the six asked an imprisoned burglar to kill the
trial witnesses and then help them break out in return for $20,000
in cash and $100,000 in counterfeit money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0241 </DOCNO>
