<FIRST>r w AM-Smog     05-22 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smog,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Understates Smog Problem, Environmentalist Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency routinely
understates the severity of the smog problem in urban areas because
it relies on too few monitoring devices, a private environmental
group said Monday.
   The Natural Resources Defense Council said that in many large
American cities unhealthy levels of smog are twice as frequent
during the hot summer months as EPA estimates would indicate.
   Last March the EPA released 1988 air pollution figures that
showed ozone pollution, which is a chief component of urban smog,
as being the worst in a decade and ``clearly the most pervasive air
pollution problem'' the country faces.
   The agency indicated nearly 100 areas of the country have
unhealthy levels of ozone pollution during at least some periods of
the summer.
   Nevertheless, according to the environmental group, those EPA
statistics reflect only a fraction of the ozone pollution problem,
according to the NRDC.
   The environmental group said the EPA estimates of days in which
there are unhealthy levels of smog in an area are often based on
smog readings from a single monitor.
   ``This approach seriously underestimates the extent of the smog
problem in most large urban areas,'' said David Hawkins, an
attorney for the environmental group and a former assistant
administrator at the EPA.
   EPA officials could not immediately be reached for comment on
the NRDC's assertions.
   Hawkins said that an analysis conducted by the NRDC showed that
unhealthy levels of smog occurred about twice as often in many
American cities than the EPA statistics suggest.
   In urban areas in most parts of the Northeast and across some
areas of the Southeast and Texas smog levels were found to be
considerably worse than implied by the EPA reporting, he said.
   Hawkins said the group counted the number of ``smoggy days'' in
1987 and 1988 in 48 large urban areas and found the levels higher
than the EPA suggested, based on its monitoring system.
   For example, according to the NRDC, the Houston, Tex.,
metropolitan area had 54 smoggy days, compared with 21 cited by the
EPA during the time period; Washington, D.C., had 18, instead of
the EPA figure of 10.5; and Cincinnati had nine instead of the two
in the EPA report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
