<FIRST>r i AM-Australia-Antarctica     05-22 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Antarctica,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Australia Against Treaty; To Push For Protected Wilderness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke said Monday
he will not sign a treaty limiting mining in Antarctica and called
instead for tougher action _ declaring the mineral-rich continent a
wilderness park.
   As one of the seven original claimant nations to the Antarctic,
Australia has veto power over the U.S.-supported treaty, which must
be signed by November to take effect.
   ``Although we recognize that (it) is very much better than no
protective regime of any kind ... we believe that it is both
desirable and possible to seek stronger protection for what remains
the world's last great wilderness,'' Hawke said.
   Hawke announced the Cabinet decision jointly with Foreign
Minister Gareth Evans and Environment Minister Graham Richardson.
   Supporters of the proposed Convention on the Regulation of
Antarctic Mineral Resource Activities, drawn up last year in
Wellington, New Zealand, argue limited protection is better than
none at all.
   Australia has land claims totaling 38 percent of the continent,
making it the largest claimant.
   France is the only other original claimant nation not to have
signed. The other claimants are Argentina, Chile, New Zealand,
Norway and Great Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
