<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 2152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DiscriminationTrial     05-22 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Discrimination Trial,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>1973 Bias Case Against Navy Goes To Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony began Monday on a federal
lawsuit filed in 1973 alleging that the Navy discriminated against
black civilian workers in promotions at Jacksonville Naval Air
Station.
   U.S. District Judge Howell W. Melton is hearing the non-jury
trial, which may involve up to 450 witnesses and 4,000 exhibits in
the case that became a class-action suit after it was filed.
   Attorneys for both sides estimated the trial may take up to 12
weeks. Melton said if it is not over by the end of June, he will
have to recess it until September because of other court business.
   The lawsuit was filed by six blacks in 1973 after their
complaints were rejected by their bosses. One of the six workers
has died since the lawsuit was filed.
   Ten years after the case went to court, it was declared a class
action, with the outcome potentially affecting 1,200 to 1,700
blacks who work or have worked at the Navy Aviation Depot, formerly
the Naval Air Rework Facility.
   To win, lawyers for the NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund
Inc. must prove there was a sweeping pattern of sometimes subtle
personnel decisions that promoted white workers ahead of more
qualified blacks.
   ``We think the promotion process is a largely subjective
procedure. When you have that kind of subjective decision-making,
discrimination can enter the process,'' said Clyde Murphy, one of
the lawyers with the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People.
   The Navy has denied any discrimination and also has defended its
system for evaluating and promoting civilian workers.
   If Melton decides the Navy has discriminated, another trial
would be needed to determine which employees were treated unfairly
and how they should be compensated. The plaintiffs in a subsequent
lawsuit could seek back pay and promotions, Murphy said.
   ``It's a big case, and when you litigate against the federal
government, they have a lot of resources,'' he said.
   A variety of reasons are behind the 15-year delay since the
original 1974 trial date.
   A major issue has been the changing nature of how civil rights
employment laws apply to the federal government. That resulted in
years of delay until the U.S. Supreme Court clarified the
application of the law, Murphy said.
   In addition, the two sides haggled for years over what
information they were required to give each other. Government
attorneys ``aggressively litigated'' the case, Murphy said.
   And for several years, only one federal judge was available in
Jacksonville and he was required to put criminal cases ahead of
civil actions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 2159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Drop-A-Dime     05-22 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drop-A-Dime,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presidential Award-Winning Urban Group Running Out Of Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crime hot line that won a volunteerism award
from President Bush just a month ago is on the verge of closing its
doors for lack of contributions.
   ``We happen to be one of those thousand points of light that the
president is talking about that is now about to flicker out,'' said
Georgette Watson, who runs the Drop-A-Dime service from an office
in Boston's Roxbury section. ``It's an operation where when the
money comes in it's just about spent. ... We need serious money.''
   Drop-A-Dime has been taking anonymous tips about drugs and other
criminal activity since 1983.
   According to police, one in 12 anonymous tips from Drop-A-Dime
results in arrests. Last year, the organization received more than
2,000 tips about drug activity, gangs and weapons.
   In February, Drop-A-Dime passed on a tip about a high school
student carrying a gun at school. The tip led to the arrest of an
18-year-old carrying a loaded 9mm handgun.
   ``We can't afford to lose an orgnization like Drop-A-Dime,''
Police Commissioner Francis M. Roache said. ``Policing in this
country will never be effective without groups like that. The
information we have gotten from the group has been very fruitful,
and I fully support Georgette.''
   Drop-A-Dime's original $700 annual budget has jumped to $120,000
as the operation has become more sophisticated, but it was down to
its last dime by the end of March. Now its organizers are dialing
for dollars trying to make it through the last two months of the
fiscal year.
   The tip line, known officially as Drop-A-Dime - Report Crime,
Intelligence Data Inc., handles between 300 and 600 calls per week.
   In April, Drop-A-Dime received a citation signed by Bush. The
award was for volunteer action since Drop-A-Dime has only two
salaried employees, including Watson, and uses about 10 Vista
volunteers for much of its work.
   Watson says she will have to decide by the end of this month
whether to hang up the service for good.
   ``Since April, I've been paying the small bills out of my own
pocket,'' Watson said.
   The organization relies largely on private donations from banks
and private corporations for its annual budget.
   Watson said some donors apparently gave to other projects this
year. ``Some have given us less this year, and others nothing at
all. I guess some have chosen other issues, like homelessness or
AIDS,'' she said.
   The Boston Police Department also chips in $20,000 each year and
this year provided an emergency infusion of $3,000 as cash
dwindled. Next year's $20,000 installment will not come until late
summer or early fall.
   The Rev. Bruce Wall, a co-founder of Drop-A-Dime as well as a
minister and assistant clerk magistrate, said he wrote Mayor
Raymond L. Flynn asking him to support a proposal requiring police
to allocate some assets confiscated in drug-related arrests to
groups such as Drop-A-Dime.
   ``If Drop-A-Dime has to turn off its telephones because this
city's public officials failed to support, then I am forced
seriously to question whether the `war on drugs' is a reality,'' he
wrote.
</TEXT>
