<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     05-22 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Admits Government Not Strong Enough to Risk Marcos Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said Monday
her government was not strong enough to risk allowing Ferdinand
Marcos to return _ dead or alive.
   She has refused to let the ailing, 71-year-old deposed president
return from Hawaiian exile to die in his homeland and has ruled out
burying him here.
   Marcos remained in critical condition Monday in a Honolulu
hospital after suffering renal, cardiac and pulmonary failure last
week.
   Mrs. Aquino said on Monday that the country is recovering from
20 years of abusive rule by Marcos, but the recovery is still too
fragile to risk allowing Marcos to come home even in death, she
said.
   ``Let's say a person has been ill for 20 years and now, after
three years, he is slowly recovering,'' she told reporters. ``Just
because he is growing stronger does not mean you are going to
expose him to infection.''
   Mrs. Aquino recalled how anti-Marcos groups exploited the 1983
assassination of her own husband, Benigno Aquino Jr. Aquino was
slain at Manila airport moments after returning from the United
States to challenge Marcos.
   The killing stirred such outrage it led to the popular uprising
that toppled Marcos in 1986 and forced him into exile.
   ``I appealed for peaceful demonstrations,'' she said. ``I
appealed to them not to engage in violence. Will all of Marcos'
followers do the same thing? We cannot allow anyone to create
trouble or we will be fighting again. We cannot allow these
things.''
   The president conferred on the issue Monday with her Cabinet
Crisis Committee and later officials said the ban on the former
president remained.
</TEXT>
