<FIRST>u a AM-Teachers     05-22 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teachers,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>11 Arrested in Los Angeles Strike, `Reform' Contract Reached in Boston</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA6,9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A teachers' strike in Los Angeles went into a second week Monday
with 11 arrests and a break in talks, while negotiators in Boston
agreed on a contract school officials called a landmark in
educational reform.
   The arrests were the most in one day during the walkout that has
crippled education in the nation's second-largest school district.
   They occurred after a rally at which more than 10,000 teachers
hoisted picket signs and cheered wildly when United Teachers-Los
Angeles President Wayne Johnson called school board members
``desperate, despicable people.''
   Johnson accused board members of lying when they say the
district cannot afford to meet teachers' demands for a 26 percent
raise over three years, including 10 percent in the first year.
   The Boston Teachers Union and Superintendent Laval S. Wilson
tentatively agreed on 7 percent pay increases for teachers for each
of three years despite warnings from officials that the city cannot
afford it.
   The contract, which requires ratification by the School
Committee and the union, comes at a time when Massachusetts Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis has proposed tax increases and spending cuts to
balance the state budget. Mayor Raymond Flynn said he did not
believe money would be available to support the contract, but he
supported provisions aimed at decentralizing school management.
   Wilson and Edward Doherty, president of the 6,000-member
teachers union, said the contract would give teachers greater
control over the schools, would reduce the power of seniority and
would hold teachers more responsible for the performance of their
students.
   In a joint statement, Wilson and Dougherty called the pact a
``landmark.'' Union and school officials noted, however, that it
was modeled after teachers' contracts in Dade County, Fla., and
Rochester, N.Y., which gave teachers a greater stake in how school
systems are run.
   In Los Angeles, school district police arrested 11 people for
investigation of roadway obstruction and trespassing during a
sit-in outside district headquarters. Ten teachers, including two
union vice presidents, were arrested along with a 17-year-old, said
district spokeswoman Tammy Sims.
   School board President Roberta Weintraub emphasized after the
breakdown in talks that the district had boosted its offer of a
21.5 percent pay raise over three years to a 24 percent raise over
three years, contingent on extra state funding.
   Superintendent Leonard Britton said he did not know why talks
collapsed Sunday night. ``I am led to the conclusion that the
union, and its officials particularly, were looking for any reason
to break it off,'' he said.
   Education in the district has slowed to a crawl since the union
representing 22,000 of the district's 32,000 teachers, counselors,
nurses and librarians went on strike May 15.
   The district claimed a small gain in student attendance Monday,
following a week of losses. There were 293,482 students in class,
up 34,362 from Friday. The district has more than 550,000 students.
</TEXT>
