<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     05-22 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Ask Bush to Settle Cambodia Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three senators want President Bush to give top
priority to blocking a return to power in Cambodia by the Khmer
Rouge, the communist group blamed for more than a million deaths
during its 1973-78 rule.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Foreign Relations
Committee, and Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and Mark Hatfield,
R-Ore., sent Bush a letter that also urged rejection of a proposal
for U.S. arms aid to non-communist guerrillas in Cambodia.
   The weekend letter, obtained by the Associated Press, asked Bush
to settle the debate between two groups of U.S. legislators and
experts.
   Both agree the Khmer Rouge should be stopped from returning to
power and the argument is whether the various proposals would help
or hinder this.
   ``We urge you to make unconditional United States opposition to
the Khmer Rouge and support for a diplomatic settlement your top
priorities, rather than a new program of U.S. lethal assistance,''
the senators declared.
   The other side favors arms aid for the non-communist Cambodian
factions to strengthen their hand in future power-sharing
negotiations.
   The State Department says U.S. policy is under study. White
House reaction to the senators' letter was not immediately
available.
   U.S. policy for settlement of the decade-old war includes
safeguards against future Khmer Rouge domination, along with
self-determination for the people and total withdrawal of the
Vietnamese military forces that invaded in 1978.
   The three senators voiced concern that Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
the West's choice to head a future Cambodian state, ``remains
allied with the murderous Khmer Rouge.''
   They added that ``any military assistance at this time simply
would reinforce Prince Sihanouk's alliance with the Khmer Rouge and
discourage him from attempting to reach a diplomatic settlement
which excludes the Khmer Rouge.''
   ``We do not need to remind you of the genocide committed by the
Khmner Rouge...nor do we need to remind you that the incredible
brutality of the Khmer Rouge continues today in the refugee camps
its forces control in Thailand and inparts of Cambodia,'' the
letter said.
   But Sihanouk's backers have argued that the Khmer Rouge can be
controlled more effectively as part of an alliance.
   The senators also said any military aid provided Sihanouk's and
other non-communist Cambodian groups ``invariably would fall into
the hands of the Khmer Rouge,'' and would also increase civil
strife.
</TEXT>
