<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Holiday     05-22 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Holiday,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis Celebrate Holiday With Bonfires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israelis lit hundreds of bonfires Monday night
to celebrate an ancient Hebrew victory over the Roman occupiers of
the Holy Land.
   The bonfires of the Lag Ba-Omer holiday, which ends at sundown
Tuesday, commemorate the fires lit by the soldiers of Simon
Bar-Kochba who led Jews in a rebellion against the Romans between
135 A.D. and 138 A.D.
   Jewish legend also holds that Lag Ba-Omer marks the end of a
plague in which 24,000 disciples of the famed Rabbi Akiva died
because they did not properly honor one another.
   Another legend says Akiva's disciples died fighting the Romans.
Israeli children often make bows and arrows during the holiday to
re-enact the battle.
   Police estimated that about 200,000 people, mostly Orthodox
Jews, will spend the holiday at Mount Meron near the northern city
of Safed to celebrate Lag Ba-Omer with picnics and prayers.
   Mount Meron is the burial site of Rabbi Simeon Bar-Yohai,
believed to be the author of the ``Zohar,'' a central book in the
mystical Jewish teaching, the Kabbalah. The kabbalists see Lag
Ba-Omer as the anniversary of Bar-Yohai's death.
</TEXT>
