<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 2239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     05-22 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anita Gillette Stars at American Place</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Blessing,'' the new play at the
off-Broadway American Place Theater, conveys the message that
mothers should not object if a daughter becomes a lesbian.
   But in the telling, playwright Clare Coss has made her story
long, unpleasant, tedious, inconsistent and boring.
   Louisa Horton plays a New Orleans woman in a spacious Long
Island old-age home who has periods of confusion, but most of the
time complains loudly that she wants to live with her daughter.
   The photographer daughter, played by Anita Gillette, experiences
guilt but realizes she'd have to hire full-time caretakers for her
mother. She patiently accepts her mother's abuse during weekly
visits. The daughter's supportive lawyer roommate-lover, Nan, is
played by Kelly Bishop, who was the original brash Sheila in ``A
Chorus Line.''
   The playwright has the mother proclaiming aspects of her own
personality, some of them news to everybody else on stage. More new
personality traits for Mom are written into the daughter's
throbbingly delivered eulogy while her mother is still alive.
   This apparently is meant to show the mother as a complex person.
But it comes across as the writer throwing in everything she can
think of and creating no person known to humanity.
   Three practical nurses often watch TV in the mother's room. Beth
Fowler plays an Irish woman obsessed with the Catholic Church,
Leila Boyd a mothering black woman and Olga Merediz a sympathetic
Hispanic girl. Anne Shropshire plays another old lady in the home,
vague but saintly.
   The play of seemingly innumerable scenes is directed by Roberta
Sklar.
</TEXT>
