<FIRST>u a AM-PayolaPlea     05-22 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Payola Plea,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Promoter Admits Giving Cocaine for Air Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record promoter pleaded guilty Monday to
three charges involving payola, and admitted giving cocaine to a
Fresno radio employee to win air time for songs by Bruce
Springsteen and other artists.
   Ralph Tashjian, 41, of San Mateo pleaded guilty in U.S. District
Court to a misdemeanor payola charge for sending the cocaine in a
Federal Express envelope to the radio station program director.
   He also pleaded guilty to two felony charges of filing a false
corporate tax return and obstructing a grand jury investigation.
   Tashjian said he sent less than a gram of cocaine to the Fresno
program director to encourage the broadcasts of records by
Springsteen, Laura Branigan and Elvis Costello.
   Tashjian was the first person convicted under amended 1960
payola statutes, which outlaw the exchange of gifts for radio time,
said Department of Justice attorney Richard Stavin.
   Three counts of tax violations against Tashjian's wife, Valerie,
were dismissed last week.
   Judge Pamela Ann Rymer agreed with a defense motion that the
couple was the victim of vindictive prosecution, and labeled the
government's prosecution ``reprehensible.''
   As part of a plea agreement, other counts in a 175-count
indictment filed against Tashjian will be dismissed. But Tashjian
must testify before any federal grand juries or trial juries.
   Defense attorney Anthony Brooklier said Tashjian has not been
subpoenaed to testify, and refused to say if Tashjian would testify
against his ex-boss, record promoter Joseph Isgro.
   The plea agreement also allows Tashjian to withdraw his guilty
pleas if Ms. Rymer sentences him to more than nine years in prison
and a $265,000 fine at his sentencing set for July 31.
   The government agreed not to use Tashjian's testimony against
him in any future prosecutions unless he has perjured himself or
unless he withdraws from the plea agreement.
</TEXT>
