<FIRST>u a AM-PrattsTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0752 05-22 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pratts Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0752,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Admits Facts of Crime Spree</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling to Greene in 8th graf, `Bruce Green.' Moves
up material on defense strategy from final graf to new 4th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers who ran with spy
Christopher Boyce went on trial Monday in the slaying of the first
U.S. Forest Service officer killed in the line of duty, and a
defense lawyer conceded their involvement.
   Pellets from a shotgun carried by James Pratt struck Brent
``Jake'' Jacobson, causing him to bleed to death, Pratt's lawyer,
Jonathan Cottrell, told jurors. Jacobson was a Forest Service law
enforcement officer who helped track the two suspects for 20 hours
through deep snow.
   Cottrell said he wouldn't challenge much of the prosecution's
evidence, thus avoiding lengthy technical testimony from FBI
experts, but contested circumstances that would warrant the death
penalty under state law.
   Cottrell suggested the defense would try to show that the Pratts
fired in self-defense at pursuers, and that Jacobson was acting as
a volunteer, not as a law enforcement officer in the manhunt.
   James Pratt, 29, of Indian Hills, Colo., and his brother Joseph,
27, of Sandpoint, are charged with first-degree murder and 16 other
felony counts stemming from an abortive Jan. 11 burglary.
   The Pratts gained notoriety in 1982, when their testimony helped
send escaped spy Christopher Boyce back to federal prison.Boyce,
whose sale of CIA satellite information to the Soviets was
chronicled in the book ``The Falcon and the Snowman,'' had escaped
from prison in California and taken refuge in northern Idaho.
   Cottrell told the Kootenai County jury that the Pratts were the
two black-clad figures who burst into a tavern owner's home on Jan.
11, intent on robbery. They briefly took a hostage from among the
nine people in the home, fired shots at a pursuing sheriff's
deputy, and shot it out with Jacobson and a deputy when cornered in
a ravine the evening of Jan. 12, Cottrell said.
   ``If they thought they were master criminals, they were kidding
themselves,'' Cottrell said of the robbery that netted little of
value.
   Bruce Greene, representing Joe Pratt, reserved his opening
statement until after Bonner County Prosecutor Phil Robinson has
presented his case.
   Robinson said he intends to seek the death penalty if the Pratts
are convicted of murder.
   Cottrell asked jurors to ``use your common sense'' when deciding
whether the shootout was a continuation of the burglary and robbery
of the night before, or a separate series of crimes.
   If the jurors find that Jacobson was shot as part of a robbery
or in his capacity as a law-enforcement officer, they could find
the Pratts guilty of first-degree murder, which is punishable by
death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
