<FIRST>u a AM-CaveWoman 1stLd-Writethru a0676 05-22 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cave Woman, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0676,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Told She Is Near End of 4-Month Stay in Cave</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 20 grafs to UPDATE with Follini reaction to word
she is to leave cave Tuesday; picks up 8th graf, `In the absence....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stefania Follini, who has spent more than
four months sealed in a cave, learned Monday evening that her
isolation experiment was almost over. She heard a human voice,
laughed and said it was like an alarm clock.
   Minutes after Miss Follini was notified on a computer screen
that the experiment would end Tuesday, she heard another person's
voice for the first time in four months and nine days.
   ``Stefania, I'm your God talking to you,'' experiment
coordinator Maurizio Montalbini said over an intercom.
   The 27-year-old Italian woman looked at a video camera trained
on her, laughed and said: ``I didn't think you would find me down
here.''
   Miss Follini woman has been living 30 feet underground since
Jan. 13 without sunlight, clocks or other ways of measuring time.
On May 4, she guessed it was March 7, though she said she might be
two weeks off.
   Montalbini broke the news first by typing it in Italian over a
computer connected to Miss Follini's.
   ``Stefania, a real adventure doesn't stop. It never ends,'' he
wrote.
   Miss Follini frowned and watched the screen.
   ``You have lived 130 days in temporary isolation,'' Montalbini
wrote.
   Miss Follini watched the screen, stone-faced.
   ``And now, the adventure continues,'' Montalbini wrote. ``You
are returning on your trip to eternity.''
   Miss Follini continued watching the computer screen,
expressionless. Montalbini, who once spent six months isolated in a
cave, explained to the 40 reporters clustered around two TV screens
that she was having trouble believing what she was reading.
   Finally, Miss Follini typed in a reply.
   ``How come?'' she wrote, an uncertain smile on her face.
   Montalbini assured her he was telling the truth _ the experiment
was over.
   ``Are you really serious?'' Miss Follini wrote.
   Montalbini wrote that the end of the isolation experiment meant
the end of daily, boring mental and physical tests. With that, Miss
Follini laughed and clapped her hands, and Montalbini talked to her
over the intercom.
   After several verbal exchanges with the various Italian
researchers, Miss Follini remarked that ``the feeling she had was
like when the alarm clock goes off on Monday morning,'' interpreter
Rita Fraschini said.
   The isolation set a duration record for women. The National
Aeronautics and Space Administration and several U.S. universities
cooperated with Montalbini and other researchers from his and Miss
Follini's hometown of Ancona, Italy.
   The experiment in 30-foot-deep Lost Cave in the hills of west
Carlsbad simulated some of the effects of interplanetary space
travel.
   In the absence of clocks and sunlight, Miss Follini's sleep-wake
cycle has been altered radically. She tends to stay awake 20 to 25
hours and sleep about 10 hours.
   Miss Follini's menstrual cycle hasn't helped her guess at the
passage of time because it stopped in the absence of light days and
dark nights, researcher Andrea Galvagno said.
   Miss Follini, an interior decorator, has coped with the
isolation by livening up her 10-foot-square Plexiglas living area
with colorful figures cut out of construction paper and glued to
the plastic walls. She also reads, plays solitaire and keeps in
shape with calisthenics and judo moves.
   Monday morning, eight hours before she was scheduled to find out
she was coming out Tuesday, Miss Follini appeared to be cutting out
figures for another poster.
   Occasionally, researchers summon her to perform computerized
tests of mental power and concentration. She also monitors her
temperature, heart rate, blood pressure and lung capacity.
   For the first three months, she was grouchy, but she has become
more cheerful in the past month, researchers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
