<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Wilson ADV23   05-22 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Wilson, ADV 23,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23, ^For Release Tuesday PMs, May 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hugh Wilson Sees New Show as ``Getting Even''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producer-director-writer Hugh Wilson, who's
gone a few rounds with entertainment's movers and shakers, smiled
at the opportunity presented to him in his new CBS series about
Hollywood, ``The Famous Teddy Z.''
   Wilson's last show, the critically acclaimed ``Frank's Place,''
was summarily dumped by CBS. He doesn't use the word revenge, but
he says he does expect to take a few shots in his new series,
premiering in the fall.
   Jon Cryer (``Pretty in Pink'') stars as a mail-room clerk at a
big talent agency who suddenly finds himself representing the
agency's biggest star.
   ``It's a Cinderella story,'' Wilson said. ``A kid gets an
enormously lucky break, and we show how he deals with it. His
naivete and inborn honesty seem to work for him in a business where
there's no naivete and little inborn honesty.
   ``It's a fun little way for me to get even with some people the
public thinks are wonderful and that we know are monsters.''
   Wilson was the creator of ``WKRP in Cincinnati,'' which ran on
CBS in 1978-82, the short-lived ``Easy Street'' on NBC in 1986-87,
and the ``Police Academy'' movie series.
   He also wrote and directed ``Rustler's Rhapsody,'' a send-up of
singing cowboy movies, and ``Burglar.''
   ``After `Burglar,' I realized I could do better work with a
freer hand in television and that I wouldn't be pigeon-holed as I
was in films,'' Wilson said. ``You have more people telling you
what to do in films than you do in television. I'd like to do more
movies, but what I'd like to do are terrific movies.''
   ``Frank's Place,'' which made its debut in September 1987, was
one of the most critically acclaimed series of that season. But
that was the year of the ``dramedy,'' a hybrid between comedy and
drama, and neither CBS nor the audience knew what to do with it.
   The sophisticated show was given an 8 o'clock (Eastern) time
period when it should have been on no earlier than 9, then it was
bounced around the schedule and taken off the air with the promise
of a return. It never did.
   Other ``dramedies'' got similar treatment. NBC sporadically
aired ``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd,'' then dropped it, and
ABC canceled ``The `Slap' Maxwell Story.''
   Wilson's newest offering has gotten a better time slot _ 9:30 on
Monday, sandwiched between the successful ``Murphy Brown'' and
``Designing Women.''
   ``I couldn't believe it when they put `Frank's Place' in at 8
o'clock,'' he said. ``They also put `WKRP' in at 8 and the only
time it was a big hit was when they moved it to 9 o'clock. It's now
a huge success in syndication, which proves my theory that people
like the show, but that it was in the wrong time slot.''
   Wilson's new show is loosely based on a real incident that
occurred about 30 years ago. A mailroom clerk was sent to pick up
the agency's newest star and when he returned, the actor insisted
he be made his agent. The erstwhile clerk soon represented the
biggest names in Hollywood.
   Wilson said ``The Famous Teddy Z'' is a fish-out-of-water story.
``He's a guy who has no idea what he is doing,'' he said. ``He
lives in Torrance, and his mother think's he must be dealing dope
to make so much money. She's very suspicious of Beverly Hills. The
show is a send-up of celebrities.''
   Wilson began in the advertising business in Atlanta, then came
to Hollywood to go into films.
   ``In 1971, I raised $40,000 and tried to make a low-budget
feature,'' he said. ``I wrote it, acted in it and never finished it
so nobody knows how bad it was.
   ``I came out here and through two friends, Jay Tarses and Tom
Patchett, met Grant Tinker. He agreed to take me on as a director
trainee, but I saw that in the comedy series, the most important
person was the head writer. The first thing I wrote was a `Bob
Newhart Show.'''
   Tinker was then head of MTM Enterprises and Tarses and Patchett
were producing ``The Bob Newhart Show.'' Tarses most recently
produced ``Molly Dodd'' and ``Slap Maxwell.'' Patchett created
``ALF.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   SUPER MARIO _ Lou Albano, the pro-wrestler and manager, will
play Mario in ``Super Mario Bros. Super Show.'' Danny Wells will
play brother Luigi. The half-hour show will combine animation with
live action in which celebrity guests visit the Brooklyn basement
apartment of the Mario brothers. Steve Binder, who produces
``Pee-Wee's Playhouse,'' will produce the live-action sequences.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, May 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
