<DOCNO> AP890522-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-NewPeronist Adv29   05-22 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Peronist, Adv 29,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, May 29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A New But Still Unknown Peronist to Take Argentina's Helm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Juan Carlos Zamudio says he
believes in President-elect Carlos Saul Menem, the newest heir to
Juan D. Peron.
   ``He has the same thoughts as Peron,'' Zamudio said. ``He
understands the feelings and the pain of the people.''
   Zamudio, a 39-year-old former custodian who uses a wheelchair,
is one of the 7.9 million Argentines who voted for Menem and the
Peronist Party in the presidential election May 14 and said he is
convinced that if Menem is made aware of a problem, he will fix it.
   Zamudio wants the government to refurbish a hospital that Peron
opened 40 years ago but later fell into disrepair and now is closed.
   But Menem, the 58-year-old governor of La Rioja Province, is a
new and still largely unknown face of Peronism. Zamudio may have to
wait for the hospital.
   Menem still is tied to organized labor that has been the
backbone of the party for 40 years but insists ``at no point did we
make promises'' to anyone, except to provide ``work, work and more
work.''
   The new Peronist will have a severe economic problem to deal
with when he takes office Dec. 10 _ one of keeping the country from
sliding into economic and social chaos and the policies of the old
Peronism are not apt to work to that end in today's Argentina.
   Argentines who didn't vote for Menem accepted his victory with
resignation.
   ``The Peronist Party used to say it could solve everything in
two or three months,'' said Alejandro Nunez, a lawyer. ``Menem is
saying it's going to take two or three years. It's good he says
that because it's going to take at least that long.''
   The first real insights into how Menem's Peronists will
government are not likely until he names his Cabinet in June and
when he presents his own economic program and takes responsibility
for it.
   Argentina's $59-billion foreign debt, on which $3.5 billion in
interest is overdue, will be a chief concern. Peronist economists
selected by Menem have been assigned to a delegation of President
Raul Alfonsin's incumbent government for meetings in the United
States with Argentina's creditors.
   Peronists also have become involved in government actions aimed
at stabilizing the deteriorating economy, which poses perhaps the
biggest threat to a smooth political transition in December.
   Menem stresses his party is merely cooperating with Alfonsin,
not co-governing. But the political risk is much the same.
   Politics in Argentina for four decades has been polarized by
love for or hatred of the party founded by Juan Domingo Peron in
1946.
   Workers and the poor, who receive essential benefits and
protections, are unswervingly loyal.
   ``The great contribution of the Peronist Party to Argentina is
the incorporation of workers into the national political life,''
said Italo Luder, a constitutional attorney and the party's 1983
presidential candidate.
   The middle class and the political right see it as fascist,
authoritarian, corporative, corrupt, incompetent, dominated by the
unions and unable to control the host of movements that gather
under its banner.
   Menem has worked to dispel what he calls his party's ``black
legend.''
   Peronists were the victims of violence as much as anyone else,
he says, reminding Argentines that the party had been banned or
restricted for 25 of the past 34 years and that he was jailed for
nearly five years following the military coup that ousted Peron's
widow, Isabel, from the presidency in March 1976. She had been her
husband's vice president and succeeded him on his death in 1974.
   ``Peronist violence was a response to violence exercised against
Peronism,'' Menem has said. ``I'm not justifying one or the other,
but let's be a little more evenhanded.''
   But skepticism of Peronism remains among Argentines who remember
churches that were burned, newspapers that were taken over,
dissidents who were harassed and industries that were nationalized
by Peron.
   Javier Vazquez Torrielli, 24, a business broker, said his father
took to wearing a gun in 1940s because he wasn't a Peronist and
felt threatened.
   Mirta Candolfi, 40, an employee of the state telephone company,
recalls Peronists coming into her grammar school and taking down
the picture of Gen. Jose San Martin, the father of the country, and
replacing it with Peron's.
   ``The fear of Peronism wasn't invented. It stems from peoples'
memories of things that happened,'' said Nunez, the lawyer.
   But even critics say Menem seems to accept ideas that the party
once rejected, such as selling off state-owned companies. He acts
on the basis of explanation and compromise, and he actively seeks _
and receives _ public support.
   ``Menem has an extreme ability to reach out and put his arm
around his enemies,'' a diplomat said. ``He draws people in rather
than pushes people away. That's his strategy. We have to wait and
see what the policies will be.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 29</NOTE>
