<FIRST>s i BC-MideastChristians-Crusades Adv28   05-22 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mideast Christians-Crusades, Adv 28,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Mideast Christians _ The New Crusaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, one of a package of three stories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslems recognize Jesus as a prophet, but
the Crusades in the Middle Ages planted suspicions among them that
Christians were allied with those who wanted to subvert Islam.
   Those suspicions are rekindled today by a new kind of Crusader,
Christian evangelists such as Americans Jerry Falwell and Pat
Robertson.
   They preach that Israel fulfills Biblical prophecies predicting
the arrival of a new Messiah and seek to convert Moslems.
   ``The Crusaders came out of the conviction that we were not
Christian enough,'' said Gabriel Habib, General Secretary of the
Cyprus-based Middle East Council of Churches.
   Crusader castles dot the modern states of Syria, Lebanon, Israel
and Jordan, symbols that Christianity, although born in the Holy
Land, was later a colonizer.
   Now the Christian fundamentalists are ``projecting an image of
Christianity of political and economic power. It's the image of a
new crusade, this time allied with Israel,'' Habib said.
   The fundamentalist groups have opened the so-called
International Christian Embassy in Jerusalem, where Israel has its
capital, to spread their teachings.
   A glossy tract published by a California church says: ``Jesus is
coming to rule _ from Jerusalem.''
   Robertson's Christian Broadcasting Network has a television
station in an Israeli-held sector of south Lebanon. It has been
destroyed twice in bombing attacks.
   The station's administrative manager, who agreed to be
interviewed only on condition of anonymity, said Robertson's
support for Israel is a personal statement and the station tries to
avoid politics.
   Almost 70 percent of its programming ranges from U.S. football
to ``Magnum P.I.,'' he said.
   But he noted that the rest are ``programs to inspire people in
their faith.'' Pro-Iranian Moslem militants in Lebanon would like
to see these off the air, he said.
   Evangelical groups say they work in the Middle East because the
region's Christians, isolated in minority pockets around the Arab
world, are not forceful enough.
   Seeking converts ``is what the Gospel calls them to do among
their own people,'' said a missionary with the Assembly of God who
did not want his name used because it might limit his ability to
travel in the region.
   ``I wish every Coptic priest, every Roman Catholic priest would
do it,'' he added.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-MideastChristians-Glance Adv28   05-22 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mideast Christians-Glance, Adv 28,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Mideast Christians at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One of a package of three stories.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   These are the five main Christian groups of the Middle East:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ORIENTAL ORTHODOX CHURCHES _ Founded in Christianity's early
years, these are independent churches linked to specific nations or
ethnic groups. The Coptic Orthodox Church, believed founded by St.
Mark in the year 50, is the largest in the Middle East with about 7
million followers, mostly in Egypt. The others are the 2-million
member Armenian Orthodox Church and the Syrian Orthodox Church.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EASTERN ORTHODOX CHURCHES _ Also known as Greek Orthodox, these
are self-governing and differ from the Oriental Orthodox churches
on doctrinal decisions handed down before the year 800. The largest
is the Greek Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch and All the East, with
about 1.3 million followers, mostly in Syria. Others include the
the Greek Orthodox Patriarchate of Jerusalem, the Church of Cyprus
and the Church of Mount Sinai, represented by about a dozen monks
at the famous shrine where Moses is said to have received the Ten
Commandments.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CATHOLICS _ They consist of seven branches. All but the Maronite
Catholics, the largest Christian sect in Lebanon, broke from
branches of the Orthodox churches. The Maronites claim to have 1
million members in Lebanon and 6.7 million outside the region. The
others range in membership from 30,000 to 300,000 and include the
Chaldean Catholic Patriarchate of Babylon, the largest Christian
community in Iraq; and the Syrian Catholic Patriarchate of Antioch,
which celebrates its liturgy in Jesus' language of Aramaic.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ASSYRIAN CHURCH OF THE EAST _ Its largest group, 250,000
members, is in Baghdad, Iraq. The church long been pilloried by
others Christians, allegedly for following the teachings of
Nestorius, an excommunicated 5th century patriarch of
Constantinople.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PROTESTANTS _ Now numbering about 100,000 members, Protestant
churches were established in the Middle East in the early 19th
century by missionaries. U.S. evangelistic groups, such as those
led by the Rev. Jerry Falwell and the Rev. Pat Robertson, are
active in Jerusalem and southern Lebanon.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
