<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-ContinentinCrisis-Bolivia Adv28   05-22 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Bolivia, Adv 28,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Bolivia _ Bleak but Now Hopeful</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A sidebar box is BC-Continent-Bolivia-Glance, b0521.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   If there's a deep black hole in South America,
Bolivia has been in it. But now, as some of its more advanced
neighbors might be on the verge of falling in, Bolivia may be
coming out. The light at the top offers hope for the poorest
country on the continent but it's still only a glimmer. This is one
in a series of periodic reports by The Associated Press on the
economic, social and political turbulence that has turned South
America into a continent in crisis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BY PETER McFARREN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A remarkable economic turnaround and a
newfound political stability are giving hope to the South American
country that perhaps most needs it.
   But despite Bolivia's visions of a brighter future, its present
remains bleak:
   _Of every 10 workers, two can't find jobs and one has turned to
the illegal cocaine business.
   _One of every 10 newborns doesn't survive infancy _ the worst
rate in the Americas.
   _Of every 1,000 Bolivians, 14 die each year. That's nearly
double the South American average.
   The new leadership that will grapple with the country's grave
problems won't be known until at least Aug. 4, when Congress
convenes to choose a new president. In a general election May 7,
all candidates fell short of the absolute majority needed for
direct election, so the legislature must pick from the top three
finishers: Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada, the former dictator Hugo
Banzer Suarez and Jaime Paz Zamora.
   All three have pledged, however, to stick with an economic
program that transformed Bolivia from South America's most chaotic
nation into what some are calling a Third World model.
   Bolivia has had 76 governments since independence from Spain in
1825 _ half of them de facto military governments and the other
half democratically elected.
   From 1978 to 1982, its 6.9 million people _ many of them
descendants of an Indian culture that predated Inca conquests in
Bolivia by several centuries _ saw eight changes of government.
They included three bloody military coups.
   Democracy was re-established in 1982, but the government of
then-President Hernan Siles Zuazo proved unable to reverse an
economic tailspin and an inflation rate that soared to an
inconceivable rate of 23,000 percent a year.
   A 10-million peso note shrank in value to $5, and the Central
Bank confessed to not a penny in reserves.
   When President Victor Paz Estenssoro was elected to replace
Siles Zuazo in 1985, he declared simply but dramatically: ``Bolivia
is dying on us.''
   His government prescribed a drastic cure: a 95-percent currency
devaluation, an end to subsidized prices and a 10-fold increase in
the price of gasoline, and the layoff of 35,000 state tin miners
and other government employees. While public spending was slashed,
an effective new tax system brought in additional revenues.
   The new program was put to an immediate test when world market
prices for tin and oil, the country's main exports, plunged
drastically. The plan nonetheless took hold.
   Inflation dropped and leveled off at about 10 percent a year _
among South America's lowest rates. In 1987 and 1988, the country
enjoyed modest but steady economic growth for the first time in
many years.
   Once-scarce foreign investment is picking up, as is foreign aid.
Some factories and new homes and office buildings are going up.
With new tax revenues, the government is paving streets and
painting public buildings.
   ``Bolivia is a country that has made a complete turnaround,''
U.S. Ambassador Robert Gelbard said in an interview. ``It has
reversed the trend toward economic collapse and established the
base for recovery.''
   Gelbard said he expects the recovery to continue no matter which
of the three candidates is chosen president, since each is
committed to the program.
   ``I'm very optimistic.''
   Fernando Mendoza, World Bank representative in Bolivia, said the
Bolivian program ``represents a very important example for Latin
America and other countries that are passing through a similar
situation.''
   While such countries as nearby Brazil and Argentina try to
entangle themselves from foreign debt, Bolivia, because of its
poverty, is under less pressure from foreign creditors.
   Unlike other debtor countries, Bolivia owes most of its
$4.2-billion foreign debt to governments or international
assistance agencies, which have been more willing to reschedule
payment.
   Commercial lenders have virtually written off the $700 million
Bolivia owes them, and has allowed the government to buy half of it
back at 11 percent of its face value.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1423EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-ContinentinCrisis-Bolivia Adv28-1stAdd   05-22 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Bolivia, Adv 28-1st Add,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>LA PAZ: face value.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With economic stability has come political steadiness. When Paz
Estenssoro hands over power in August, he'll be the first elected
president to finish out his full term in 25 years.
   But the social cost of the program has been excruciating,
nevertheless, and the benefits so far have not reached many of the
jobless or the 2 million peasant farmers who know only of
subsistence.
   Unemployment rose to a staggering 25 percent _ and still remains
above 20 percent. Without government subsidies, prices for many
basic goods soared to levels similar to those of industrialized
countries, while wages remained at Third World levels. The minimum
legal wage is equivalent to $1.50 a day.
   In a wrenching upheaval, thousands of ex-miners were forced to
abandon the homes on the windy high plains. Among them were Indians
whose ancestors had lived there for millenia. About 75 percent of
Bolivia's people are of Quechua or Aymaya Indian ancestry and about
half the population lives in the countryside.
   Many moved into the swollen shantytowns on the fringes of La Paz
and other major cities. Others descended into the tropical lowlands
and began growing coca, the raw material for cocaine.
   Of a national work force of about 3 million, an estimated
300,000 make their livelihood in some aspect of the cocaine
industry _ growing, processing or smuggling. The business brings in
$200 million to $300 million a year _ equal to about half all legal
export earnings.
   Indeed, the drug profits helped cushion the impact of the
government belt-tightening policies. Some say the country must now
be gently weaned from the illicit activity.
   ``A complete curtailment of cocaine without viable alternatives
could be devastating to the national economy,'' said a Maryknoll
priest, Patrick Henry. He works with addicted and abandoned
children in the city of Cochabamba, the gateway to the country's
principal coca-growing area, the Chapare.
   The government, as well as all three top presidential
candidates, oppose forced eradication of coca farms by burning or
spraying with herbicides, as is being tried in other South American
countries.
   Instead they favor a U.S.-financed plan, now in its third year,
to persuade coca farmers to switch to other crops and to leave the
now-overpopulated Chapare.
   But they also contend that the United States and other wealthy
cocaine-importing countries must put up more money for the program
_ some $300 million to $500 million over a three-year period.
   ``The big problem is getting the developed world to cooperate,''
said Sanchez de Lozada, the presidential candidate of Paz
Estenssoro's conservative Revolutionary Nationalist Movement.
``They seem to prefer to have somebody they can blame the drug
problem on rather than finding a solution.''
   ``If you give us the resources, we have the will,'' he added in
a conversation with foreign reporters.
   The United States spends about $55 million a year on drug
interdiction and crop-switching programs in Bolivia. It provides
more than $100 million a year in aid to Bolivia.
   In all, foreign aid from the industrialized world and
international lending agencies is expected to total $365 million in
loans and donations this year. Government officials recognize that
the assistance is vital to health programs and development projects
aimed at bettering life in South America's poorest country.
   Authorities agree that the country's most desperate need is more
and better-paying jobs. They expect that to result from the
economic growth the country now is enjoying but acknowledge that
the process is a gradual one.
   Among the new private investors are several foreign mining and
petroluem companies. But the country sees a need to reduce its
heavy reliance on mineral production by promoting non-traditional
exports such as soya, lumber, fruit, flowers and alpaca wool.
   In 1992, a natural gas sales contract with Argentina that
provides more than half of the country's export earnings will
expire. Bolivia has begun negotiating with another neighbor,
Brazil, to sell them gas but the arrangements will take several
more years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
