<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   05-22 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Wabbit Twouble,'' ``Bugs Bunny Classics,'' ``The Best of Bugs
Bunny and Friends'' (MGM-UA Home Video)
   
   The fine print on the videocassette jacket of ``Bugs Bunny
Classics'' says ``pre-'50s cartoons.'' To cartoon buffs, that says
it all. These are the great ones, the Warner Bros. Looney
Tunes-Merrie Melodies classics that will keep you in stitches with
clever lines, biting satire and unrivaled cartoon artwork.
   Like Trix, they are definitely not just for kids.
   Of the three collections, top honors go to ``Bugs Bunny
Classics.'' It includes ``Racketeer Rabbit,'' which parodies movie
tough guys Edward G. Robinson and Peter Lorre. ``Hare Trigger,'' an
early Bugs-Yosemite Sam duel, is high on the hilarity list, as is
``Haredevil Hare,'' in which Bugs defends the honor of Earth
against a little Martian with high-top sneakers named Commander X-2.
   The title ``The Best of Bugs Bunny &amp; Friends,'' is a
considerable exaggeration. It includes the wonderful ``Tweetie
Pie,'' a 1947 incarnation of that not-so-innocent ``wittle bird.''
But two of the seven cartoons contain racial stereotypes of an
African hunter and American Indian that were offensive then and
remain so today.
   As the name implies, ``Wabbit Twouble'' is 54 minutes worth of
Bugs outwitting Elmer Fudd. Especially funny is ``The Old Gray
Hare,'' in which an aging Bugs (``dern this lumbago!'') is still
too much for hapless Elmer.
   But ``Wabbit Twouble'' also illustrates the built-in problem
Bugs' creators had: creating a comic foil smart enough to spar with
the Wascally Wabbit. Over time, Elmer was just too stupid to remain
interesting or funny. Others, such as Yosemite Sam came along, but
in his recent autobiography, voice impressionist Mel Blanc said
Yosemite was pretty tough on his vocal chords.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Memories of Me'' (CBS-Fox Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.98. Rated
PG-13)
   
   ``Memories of Me'' is almost a completely forgettable movie
until its final third, when there's _ finally _ some action to the
drama about a father and son trying to reconcile their years of
estrangement.
   ``Memories'' is Henry Winkler's first outing as a director and
it shows in the movie's pacing. Much of the beginning is plodding
and self-consciously slow. Poignant moments when young Dr. Abbie
Polin (Billy Crystal) reflects on his callous father hang
relentlessly on dead air.
   Crystal co-wrote the film and created a girlfriend (JoBeth
Williams) for himself, whose role in the melodrama-comedy is vague.
At times, her only purpose seems to be to admire Crystal's rear end
or his sexual prowess!
   The plot finally gets going when Crystal, after suffering a mild
heart attack, treks from New York to Los Angeles to resolve the
decades of paternal indifference. Once he's there, Abbie learns his
dad, Abe the King of Hollywood Extras (Alan King), has a terminal
illness.
   They try to win Abe a speaking part in a movie and validate his
oft-repeated claim, ``I am an actor.'' In the process, Abbie comes
to love his curmudgeonly dad, who returns the favor by softening
enough to tell Abbie he loves him, too, and that in his role as
father he was simply miscast.
   It gets a bit cornball after this, but the ending is far more
compelling than the beginning and worth slogging through the slow
start.
   _ By Patricia Bibby, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
