<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 0739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CreditWatching-Law     05-22 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Credit Watching-Law,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fair Credit Reporting Act Spells Out Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Credit Watching</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fair Credit Reporting Act, enacted in 1971, gives Americans
the right to know what's in their credit file and to challenge
whatever information they believe to be inaccurate.
   If you're denied credit, you're entitled to know what's in your
file within 30 days of receiving a rejection letter. That notice
will contain the name and location of the credit-reporting bureau
contacted in evaluating your file.
   At any other time, you can write to or visit the credit bureau
to inspect your file for a nominal fee, usually between $5 and $10.
The FCRA requires the bureau to help you if there's something in
your file you don't understand.
   The FCRA also allows access to your credit file by those
authorized in writing, such as lenders to whom you are applying for
credit, potential employers or insurers. Every time someone
requests a copy of your report, it's noted as an ``inquiry'' on
your credit file.
   You can dispute information in your file by providing evidence
to prove an error or by insisting on an investigation.
   You can also submit statements to your file explaining why
negative credit remarks were accumulated. Negative information can
remain on your report for up to seven years, while bankruptcies are
reported for 10 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890522-0319 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 0745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;Ls-BudgetBattle     05-22 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-Budget Battle,0884</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politics at Root of S&amp;L Budget Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress and the Bush administration, once
intent on rushing to the rescue of savings and loan depositors,
have paused to wage an ardent battle over a seemingly arcane
accounting question.
   Should the savings and loan bailout be on-budget or off-budget?
   One side _ composed principally of House Democrats _ wants to
include bailout spending in the budget but give it a special
exemption from the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law, to avoid the
law's automatic spending cuts in the overall budget.
   The other side _ the Republican administration _ is arguing for
an off-budget plan that would borrow $50 billion for the bailout
without counting it toward the deficit.
   A third variation _ pushed by Senate Democrats _ includes the
spending in the budget but loads all of it into the 1989 fiscal
year ending Sept. 30. That indirectly evades Gramm-Rudman because
the deadlines that could have triggered spending cuts for this year
already have expired.
   The terminology of the debate is obscure and the arguments
confusing to nearly everyone but a government accountant.
Occasionally the debaters throw in a jibe about dishonest
accounting or the breakdown of budget discipline.
   To the taxpayer, it doesn't seem to matter that much. All of the
sides, after all, simply are proposing different ways of getting
around the Gramm-Rudman law and no matter what plan is eventually
adopted, the public ends up picking up most of the tab, upwards of
$300 billion over 30 years.
   But to the debaters, it matters a lot. Congressional Democrats
think their position is important enough to risk being blamed for
delaying S&amp;L legislation and allowing the crisis to get worse.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady is threatening to recommend
a veto of any bill with on-budget financing, inviting Democrats to
tag the administration with a similar obstructionist label.
   Publicly, the arguments run something like this.
   Democrats: Our plan is cheaper. It allows the government to
borrow at a lower cost. And, it's more honest because all of the
S&amp;L spending will show up in the deficit.
   Republicans: Your plan destroys any spending discipline imposed
by Gramm-Rudman. If adopted, Congress will be tempted to evade
Gramm-Rudman to pay for any costly problem and that threat will
scare the financial markets into driving up all interest rates,
negating any savings produced by the on-budget plan.
   But, the ardor of both sides has very little to do those
arguments and very much to do with the constant dance of politics
that surrounds the Republican effort to avoid getting blamed for
any future tax increase and the Democratic desire to block further
spending cuts.
   George Bush got elected to the presidency on his ``Read my lips,
no new taxes'' pledge and Democrats would dearly love to force him
to mouth different words.
   The administration and Congress reached a relatively easy budget
accord for 1990, avoiding both taxes and painful spending cuts. But
that will become more difficult and the hardball will become harder
as the 1992 election draws closer.
   Democrats know there's an advantage to their plan beyond any
savings it might produce. Even with the threat of automatic
spending cuts removed, an on-budget S&amp;L plan would embarrass Bush
and increase the pressure on him to abandon his tax pledge.
   The Senate proposal would add $50 billion to the 1989 deficit,
ballooning it within range of the all-time record of $221 billion
set in 1986. Not an auspicious start for Bush.
   The House method, approved last Thursday by the Ways and Means
Committee, adds only about $10 billion to the 1989 deficit but it
inflates 1990 red ink by about $25 billion and the 1991 budget gap
by about $15 billion, destroying any hope of maintaining an
illusion of progress on the deficit.
   The maneuvering between Congress and the administration has
deteriorated now into a game of chicken, with each side trying to
blame the other for holding up the S&amp;L rescue and hoping in the end
that neither side will be willing to scuttle the rescue over the
budget question.
   The next hurdle is the full House. Chances are good that an
on-budget plan could pass there in early June. Then comes a
conference committee between the House and Senate, where the Senate
delegation will be led by Banking Committee Chairman Donald Riegle,
D-Mich., an on-budget advocate.
   Assuming the conference committee approves an on-budget plan,
one last and major hurdle remains. Both the House and Senate would
have to separately approve any conference legislation. And, because
the bill will by necessity change the 1989 budget adopted by
Congress, the Senate must pass the funding part of it by 60 votes.
   There are 55 Democrats in the Senate, so Democrats would have to
hold all of their own votes and peel off five Republicans. Thus, it
will likely fall to Senate Republicans to save the administration
from having to choose between making good on its veto threat or
publicly backing down.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dave Skidmore has covered the savings and loan crisis for The
Associated Press since 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
