<FIRST>r f PM-HollyFarms 1stLd-Writethru f0014 05-22 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holly Farms, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0014,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Board Accepts Sweetened ConAgra Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Tyson extending its
tender offer; edits for transition. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Under the ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Holly Farms Inc. has approved
a sweetened $1.38 billion buyout bid from ConAgra Inc. more than a
month after Holly Farms shareholders turned down an earlier
agreement with the rival poultry producer.
   But Tyson Foods Inc., which has been trying to take over Holly
Farms since October, today extended its $63.50-a-share offer.
   Tyson's tender offer will expire on Tuesday at 5 p.m. EDT. Tyson
said it had received tenders of about 8.9 million shares of Holly
Farms common stock by the close of business Friday, which was the
previous deadline.
   ConAgra's new $74.81-a-share stock swap proposal to acquire
Memphis-based Holly Farms is worth a total of $1.38 billion at
current stock prices.
   That is significantly higher than a $1.1 billion proposal turned
down at a Holly Farms shareholders meeting April 14 and higher than
Tyson's all-cash offer, which comes to $1.15 billion.
   Under the new agreement, each of Holly Farms' 18.4 million
outstanding shares would be exchanged for 2.1 ConAgra shares.
Conagra stock closed at $35.62{ a share in New York Stock Exchange
composite trading Friday, meaning Holly Farms shareholders would
receive stock worth $74.81 per share.
   Holly Farms closed at $62.62{ on the NYSE on Friday.
   ``We're not through trying to compete for the company,'' James
Blair, Tyson's general counsel, said in an interview in New York
Sunday.
   Blair said Tyson would consider its options and see how
investors react to the new agreement. He also noted that litigation
connected with the takeover battle continues in courts in Delaware,
and said Tyson would await the outcome of the lawsuits before
deciding what it would do.
   Holly Farms management has consistently shunned Tyson's bids,
although they have been higher than previous ConAgra proposals.
ConAgra first bid for Holly Farms in November.
   After shareholderse rejected the deal with Omaha, Neb.-based
ConAgra, Holly Farms reopened bidding. Tyson has charged the
auction process was unfair, and Blair said Sunday his company was
trying to ``find a way that we could compete on a level playing
field and compete fairly.''
   A Delaware Chancery Court judge last week agreed that the
bidding procedures were unfair to Springdale, Ark.-based Tyson, but
said there were no legal grounds to halt the auction.
   Under the previous Holly Farms-ConAgra agreement, Holly Farms
agreed to sell ConAgra certain of its assets if the proposed buyout
fell through. However, the agreement approved by the Holly Farms
board late Saturday night removed that provision, known as a
``lock-up'' agreement.
   The newest offer is subject to approval of the Holly Farms
shareholders, which were lobbied heavily by Tyson before the last
vote.
   Holly Farms vice president Ted Bailey said the company hoped to
have another shareholder vote by the end of July.
   Bailey said the new agreement also allows Holly Farms to
terminate the deal if it receives a higher offer. Holly Farms
agreed to pay ConAgra a fee of $15 million plus actual expenses if
the agreement fails.
   Tyson has objected to that fee agreement. Blair said Sunday
Holly Farms shareholders were being forced to vote for the
agreement, or have millions of dollars taken away from the firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
