<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   05-22 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld - Writethru,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Bankruptcy Case at Critical Juncture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Leads with 4 new grafs to UPDATE with hearing adjourned until
Tuesday, editing to conform. Picks up 4th graf pvs, On Wednesday... ^By
MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge today gave Eastern
Airlines another day to consider rival buyout offers for its
Northeast shuttle business.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland adjourned until Tuesday
a hearing at which attorneys for Miami-based Eastern, its unions
and its major creditors were to meet to discuss competing offers
for the shuttle by America West Airlines and developer Donald Trump.
   Eastern and a committee representing its major creditors sought
the additional time so they could continue evaluating the bids.
   Last week, court officials labeled as inadequate buyout
proposals for Eastern submitted by two investor groups; Lifland
approved the idea of selling the airline's prized Northeast
shuttle; and Eastern's own plan to sell $1.8 billion in assets and
reorganize as a smaller carrier gained momentum.
   On Wednesday, Lifland gave Eastern permission to lease 14 Boeing
727-200s to Pan Am Corp. for $57.9 million over three years as part
of its restructuring plan. Eastern had signed a tentative agreement
with Pan Am to lease the jets for $96.6 million over five years.
   Eastern has announced similar agreements with other carriers in
recent weeks, but the Pan Am deal was the first approved by the
bankruptcy court.
   Eastern has been under Chapter 11 protection from creditors
since March 9, five days after the start of a paralyzing strike by
its Machinists union that was supported by pilots and flight
attendants.
   The bankruptcy court must approve any sale of Eastern or any of
its assets, including the shuttle service.
   David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed bankruptcy examiner for
Eastern, said last week there were no ``real live offers'' to buy
the entire carrier. He challenged the prospective suitors to risk
at least $100 million of their own cash for any purchase.
   Two investor groups, one headed by Chicago commodities trader
Joseph Ritchie and the other led by former Piedmont Airlines
chairman William Howard, have submitted formal bids.
   Florida Gov. Bob Martinez may try to use the state's $17 billion
pension fund to back a buyout by the Ritchie or Howard group, in an
effort to protect jobs provided by the airline, according to
newspaper reports Sunday.
   The Miami Herald and the Palm Beach Post reported that a state
investment of at least $50 million was being considered, given the
proper guarantees against loss.
   At the time the strike began, Eastern employed about 30,000
workers, including 12,000 in Florida.
   Lifland, meanwhile, said Eastern had provided valid reasons for
its plan to sell the New York-Washington-Boston shuttle. Eastern
already has an agreement to sell the shuttle to developer Donald
Trump for $365 million, but last week Lifland gave the airline
until today to consider a higher bid by America West Airlines.
   Joel Zweibel, the attorney representing Eastern's major
creditors, said they supported a prompt sale of the shuttle.
   The growing likelihood of a shuttle sale, coupled with the
apparent lack of sufficient buyout offers for the whole airline,
bolster Eastern's proposed plan to cut its size and sell another
$1.4 billion or so in assets separately, some observers believe.
   Phoenix-based America West has offered to pay $415 million for
the shuttle and $336 million for 10 Boeing 757s in a total package
worth $751 million.
   Trump's agreement with Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp. expires
May 27. Under their contract, the developer would receive $8
million from Eastern if the shuttle deal collapses.
   America West has said it would not employ Eastern workers if it
purchased the shuttle, while Trump has recognized the Eastern
unions as representatives for employees of his shuttle.
   On Thursday, pilots union leaders at Eastern reversed their
earlier position and said 170 Eastern pilots could work for the
shuttle if it is sold to Trump.
</TEXT>
