<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Time-Warner     05-22 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner Says Pact With Shareholder Clears Path for Merger with Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. said today it settled
a longstanding dispute with its largest shareholder, clearing
another potential obstacle to the entertainment company's planned
$18 billion merger with Time Inc.
   The shareholder, Chris-Craft Industries Inc., joined Time and
Warner in announcing the settlement that the companies said would
permit the Time merger with Warner to proceed ``without any delay
or adjustment.''
   The merger would create the world's largest media and
entertainment concern, with $10 billion in assets.
   Warner and Chris-Craft had entered an agreement in 1984 in which
they acquired stakes in each other in what was seen as a defensive
manuever by Warner to avoid a hostile takeover.
   Warner bought about 42.5 percent of Chris-Craft's broadcasting
subsidiary, BHC Inc., while Chris-Craft bought a stake in Warner
that now amounts to about 17 percent. Warner agreed to refrain from
acquiring a television station or making make certain changes in
control while the pact with Chris-Craft was in effect.
   But in the years since the pact was signed, relations soured
between Warner and Chris-Craft and there was some concern it could
delay the proposed Warner merger with Time.
   Earlier this month, Warner sued Chris-Craft, seeking an order
that would have compelled Chris-Craft to resolve any objections to
the merger. That litigation was resolved under the settlement,
Warner spokesman Geoffrey Holmes said.
   Under the settlement, Warner said it will offer to sell its
shares in BHC to third parties. Chris-Craft would have the right of
first refusal to purchase Warner's interest in BHC or require
Warner to spin off its interest in BHC to Time Warner shareholders
after the merger.
   Warner is ending its right of first refusal on the Warner shares
held by Chris-Craft as part of the agreement.
   ``We are delighted that despite our earlier differences, the
relationship between WCI and Chris-Craft is ending on a
constructive and amicable basis and in the best interests of all
the shareholders and the concerned parties,'' the chairmen and
chief executives of both companies, Steven J. Ross of Warner and
Herbert J. Siegel of Chris-Craft, said in a joint statement.
   Siegel was quoted as saying ``Time Warner will be the premier
media and entertainment company in the world, and I wish it well.''
   Siegel was said to be unavailable for comment. Upon the merger,
BHC will be Time-Warner's largest shareholder, owning about 11
percent of Time Warner stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
