<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   05-22 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0325</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply lower
this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade, with the drop in prices
based largely on weather factors.
   There was precipitation during the weekend in major crop areas.
And the National Weather Service's 6- to 10-day forecast starting
Thursday calls for normal or above-normal rainfall for most areas.
   The strong dollar also was a drag on the market. Most affected
are soybeans futures. Foreign demand for U.S. soybeans has dropped
with the dollar's rise and some countries are turning to Brazil for
supplies.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter's announcement over the
weekend that he may allow farmer-owned grain reserves to come to
market this summer and fall caused only a minor stir among corn
futures traders.
   ``If it were not for other news it would have been a major
factor on the market,'' said Frank Kouba, an analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was 4{ cents to 5} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.95\ a bushel; corn was 6\ to 7{
cents lower with July at $2.65{ a bushel; oats were 5 cents lower
with July at $1.79\ a bushel; soybeans were 17{ cents to 21} cents
lower with July at $7.01{ cents a bushel.
   Livestock prices were lower and pork prices mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .38 cent lower with June at 70.45
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .23 cent higher
with May at 77 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with June at 48.75 cents a pound; pork bellies were .10 cent
lower to .82 cent higher with May at 35.40 cents a pound.
   Livestock prices settled mixed and pork prices higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
