<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru f0005 05-22 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0005,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steadies At Higher Level After Intervention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with central bank intervention.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar steadied at higher levels in Europe
late Monday after central banks intervened to push the U.S.
currency lower.
   Gold prices fell as much as $6.50 an ounce in morning trading.
   The dollar surged in the first hour of European trading and
continued to gain momentum as it broke through several important
resistance points.
   After peaking in midday dealings, the dollar settled in a fairly
narrow range before a wave of central bank intervention pushed the
currency lower late in the session.
   With the U.S. Federal Reserve reportedly intervening in concert
with several major European central banks, the dollar slipped
temporarily back toward the end of the day, but quickly recouped
some of its losses.
   The Deutsche Bundesbank, following its recent pattern, abstained
from the intervention.
   The Bank of Italy confirmed it participated in a concerted
effort to push the dollar lower as did the Bank of Belgium.
   The British and Swiss central banks also participated, dealers
said.
   But dealers said they expected the impact of the dollar sales to
be fleeting.
   In Rome, one trader attributed Monday's surge to panic-buying
based on the market's perception that the Group of Seven
industrialized nations cannot agree on policies to stabilize
currency rates.
   ``The market is very violent and rather irrational,'' said
another trader.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.5815 late in the
afternoon, compared with $1.5750 at midmorning and $1.6190 late
Friday.
   Other dollar rates at late afternoon, compared with late rates
on Friday, and with midmorning rates in parentheses included:
2.0075 (2.0135) West German marks, up from 1.1995; 1.7925 (1.7985)
Swiss francs, up from 1.7583; 6.7895 (6.8140) French francs, up
from 6.6700; 2.2640 (2.2598) Dutch guilders, up from 2.2210;
1,455.75 (1,462.50) Italian lire, up from 1,435.00; and, 1.1955
(1.1935) Canadian dollars, up from 1.1911.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar rose despite sizeable Bank of Japan
intervention, closing 1.68 yen higher at 140.45 yen, the first time
the dollar has closed above 140 yen since Oct. 28, 1987. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 142.55 yen.
   The dollar's rise hit precious metals sharply.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $361.80 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $365.75. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $359.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price for gold was $360 compared with $365.25
late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $6.01 to close at a bid of
$361.21.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.07 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $5.35.
</TEXT>
