<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-22 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End Sharply Lower on Interest Rate Fears</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing prices, edits throughout.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged on London's Stock Exchange
Monday, amid heightened fears that European interest rates might
have to rise to halt the dollar's latest surge.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 35.7
points, or 1.6 percent, lower at 2,169.0, after losing as much as
41.1 points in the afternoon. At its best, the index was up 5
points at the opening.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 33.9 points lower at
1,803.6. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 19.04 points to
finish at 1,233.20.
   Volume was moderate, with 614.4 million shares changing hands,
down from Friday's 856.8 million shares.
   Besides the interest rate worries, dealers and analysts agreed
that the market's strong advance last week, which added 69 points
to the 100-share index, was based more on hope than economic
fundamentals.
   Touching off Monday's plunge was the dollar's rise above 2 West
German marks. This in turn boosted British money market interest
rates, as market participants reasoned that only rate hikes in
Europe and Japan would be sufficient to counter the U.S. currency's
strength.
</TEXT>
