<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     05-22 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Well Above 2 Marks in Europe, Gold Falls Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar surged in hectic European trading
Monday, but ended well below its session peaks as profit-taking
slowed the currency's rapid advance.
   Heavy, repeated, central-bank intervention had little impact,
dealers said.
   Gold prices, hurt by the strong dollar, fell more than $5 an
ounce.
   The dollar pushed through the 2-West German mark level early in
the European day, for the first time since December 1986. That
prompted a wave of new buying that took the U.S. currency up to a
session high of around 2.0190 marks.
   The dollar rose nearly 4 cents against the British pound and
more than 3 yen.
   Heavy overnight intervention by the Bank of Japan, which some
dealers estimated sold $1.5 billion for yen, had little impact on
the dollar's strength, as did intervention by the U.S. Federal
Reserve and European central banks later in the day, dealers said.
   The Fed came in a second time in the afternoon, again with
little impact, they said. The Bank of England reportedly intervened
four times, with the first round apparently the heaviest, dealers
said.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's move below its peaks to
profit-taking rather than the impact of intervention.
   In London, the dollar rose to its highest level since August
1987. It cost $1.5810 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6190 late
Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday:
2.0088 West German marks, up from 1.1995; 1.7922 Swiss francs, up
from 1.7583; 6.7990 French francs, up from 6.6700; 2.2640 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.2210; 1,455.75 Italian lire, up from 1,435.00;
and 1.1956 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1911.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar rose despite sizeable Bank of Japan
intervention, closing 1.68 yen higher at 140.45 yen, the first time
the dollar has closed above 140 yen since Oct. 28, 1987. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 142.05 yen.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $360.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $365.75. In Zurich, gold closed at a
bid $359.80 an ounce, compared with $365.25 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $6.01 to close at a bid $361.21
an ounce.
   Silver prices fell in London to a late bid price of $5.14 a troy
ounce from $5.35 Friday.
</TEXT>
