<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-22 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather, Strong Dollar Drive Down Grain, Soybean Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices dropped sharply
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors reacted to
weather forecasts and the continued rise in the value of the dollar.
   There was precipitation during the weekend in major crop areas
that were suffering from dryness. In addition, the National Weather
Service's 6- to 10-day forecast starting Thursday calls for normal
or above-normal rainfall for most areas.
   Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc. in
Chicago, said tarding remainmed in a narrow range after a drop at
the opening.
   ``But the sentiment was so negative, we couldn't mount a
rally,'' he said.
   Adding to the market's woes is the strength of the dollar, which
analysts say is likely to curtail export of grains.
   Particularly affected by the rising dollar are soybean futures.
Foreign demand for U.S. soybeans has dropped with the dollar's
rise, with some countries turning to Brazil for their supplies.
   ``The momentum in the market is on the down side,'' Karlin said,
adding that despite the low prices, no one is coming in to buy.
``There is a real deflationary sentiment in all the markets.''
   At the close, wheat was 6 cents to 7\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.94{ a bushel; corn was 5{ cents
to 9{ cents lower with July at $2.66\ a bushel; oats were 7} cents
to 9\ cents a bushel with July at $1.75 a bushel; soybeans were 25\
cents to 28} cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at
$6.93 a bushel.
</TEXT>
