<FIRST>r f AM-Celtics-Investor     05-22 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Celtics-Investor,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Investor Buys 5.1 Percent of Celtics Limited Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida investor has acquired a 5.1 percent
non-voting stake in the limited partnership that owns the Boston
Celtics, according to a securities filing made public Monday.
   David Rhodin Murphey III, president of Tampa-based Murphey
Capital Inc., disclosed that he has bought 326,100 units in the
Celtics limited partnership.
   Murphey has been purchasing the shares over several months and
his holdings recently topped 5 percent of the partnership's
outstanding units, requiring disclosure to the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   The Celtics are a limited partnership traded on the New York
Stock Exchange. The units closed at $13.62{, unchanged from
Friday's close.
   Three Boston investors, Donald F. Gaston, Alan Cohen and Paul
Dupee, purchased the team in 1983. When the Celtics went public in
1986, the three retained a 60 percent share, according to Joseph
DiLorenzo, Celtics vice president for finance.
   ``There are no voting rights associated with those units. He
just finds it a nice investment,'' said DiLorenzo.
   Murphey was away from his office and could not be reached for
comment Monday, according to his secretary.
</TEXT>
