<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   05-22 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead despite some early
selling Monday, struggling to extend the rally that has carried it
to its highest levels in more than a year and a half.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which surpassed the
2,500 level on Friday for the first time since Oct. 13, 1987, added
0.92 to 2,502.02. At one stage the average had been down about 10
points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
833 up, 695 down and 486 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 185.01 million
shares, down from 242.41 million Friday, when the total was
inflated by program trading linked to expiring options and stock
index futures.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 222.25 million shares.
   The dollar rose sharply in world currency markets Monday. That
prompted strength in the American credit markets.
   Prices of Treasury bonds, which move in the opposite direction
from interest rates, gained as much as $10 for each $1,000 in face
value.
   That all was seen as positive for stocks. Falling rates mean
less competition for stocks from interest-bearing securities.
   In addition, analysts say, they reduce the perceived chances
that the economy will have to go through a recession.
   But brokers also noted that the market has come a long way in
its rally since last November, when the Dow got as low as 2,038.
They said some traders moved today to cash in on those gains.
   Avon Products led the active list and rose 2] to 34| on
conjecture that the company, which recently fended off a takeover
bid by Amway Corp., might become a target for other offers.
   Compaq Computer, which introduced a new high-power desktop
personal computer, climbed 3[ to 87[. International Business
Machines, faced with that competitive development, dropped 1\ to
109~.
   American Family fell 1 to 16. The company said it was looking
for second-quarter operating earnings per share to be flat with the
comparable period last year, and projected lower results for the
full year than analysts had been estimating.
   Precious metals issues were conspicuously weak, with prices of
gold and other commodities falling. Amax Gold dropped ~ to 11 and
Freeport-McMoRan Gold { to 10].
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $4.28 billion, or 0.14
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .42 to 179.34.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose .33 to 369.09, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up .74 at 321.98.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slipped .27 to 441.78. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 352.98, off .85.
