<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-22 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices finished mostly lower
in moderate trading Monday amid OPEC-related concerns.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, a last-minute buying binge
drove the June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, to $20.93, up 33 cents from Friday's close.
The June contract, which traded as low as $20.10 during the
session, expired at the close of trading.
   Prices of crude oil contracts for delivery later in the year
were down across the board.
   Among refined products, unleaded gasoline for delivery in June
fell 1.29 cents to 63.90 cents a gallon, while June heating oil
fell 1.08 cents to 46.98 cents a gallon. Other contracts also
closed the session lower.
   Analysts said worries about OPEC dominated trading in the crude
market ahead of the cartel's planned June 5 meeting.
   Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc., said lower crude prices reflected concerns that
various members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries are producing above their self-imposed output quotas.
   An unconfirmed report that Kuwait would increase production
unilaterally if the cartel didn't agree to raise its target level
sparked some early selling, Beutel said.
   ``The reports said that Kuwait was willing to flood the market
or increase production because it wants an increase in its quota,''
he said.
   Another report that Saudi Arabia would ask for a $15 a barrel
floor on crude prices at the June meeting also fueled selling
activity, said Jim Steel, energy analyst for Refco Inc.
   ``It's just pre-meeting posturing, just a negotiating tactic,''
said Steel, ``but the Saudi statement moved the market.''
   Energy brokers said the continued slide in gasoline futures
reflected traders' concern that the market was overbought and that
product inventories remained higher than last year.
</TEXT>
