<FIRST>u f AM-HollyFarms-Tyson     05-22 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms-Tyson,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson Sues To Block Latest Holly Farms-ConAgra Deal; Extends Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods extended its $63.50 a share
tender offer to acquire Holly Farms Inc. on Monday and then filed
suit to block the company's latest deal with rival suitor ConAgra
Inc.
   Under a new agreement announced Sunday, ConAgra, of Omaha, Neb.,
would acquire Memphis-based Holly Farms in a $74.81-a-share stock
swap that values the company at about $1.38 billion.
   The bid tops the $1.1 billion ConAgra agreement that Holly Farms
shareholders rejected April 14 and the current all cash offer from
Springdale-based Tyson, which values Holly Farms at about $1.15
billion.
   Tyson extended its offer until 5 p.m. Tuesday.
   Under the proposed ConAgra-Holly Farms agreement, each of Holly
Farms' 18.4 million outstanding shares would be exchanged for 2.1
ConAgra shares.
   Conagra stock closed at $33.62{ a share in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Monday, down from $2. Holly Farms closed
at $67.12{ a share, up $4.50.
   Tyson chief counsel Jim Blair said Monday that the new Holly
Farms agreement with ConAgra was unfair and his company filed suit
in Delaware Chancery Court to block it.
   Blair said in a telephone interview from New York that the suit
asks the court to block Holly Farms from completing any merger with
ConAgra ``until such time as all the impediments that now keep us
from now being able to compete on a fair and equal basis are
eliminated.''
   Holly Farms has been rebuffing Tyson takeover proposals since
last October. After shareholders rejected its initial deal with
ConAgra, Holly Farms reopened bidding for the compan by Tyson has
claimed the auction process was unfair.
   Last week, a Delaware Chancery Court judge agreed that the
bidding procedures were unfair to Tyson but said there were no
legal grounds to halt the auction.
   In a news release Monday, Tyson chairman Don Tyson said he was
surprised that Holly Farms' proceeded with the auction process over
the weekend, considering the judge's criticism of the process.
   ``We are considering all of our alternatives and have not made
any decisions as to what we will do,'' Tyson said.
   Under the previous Holly Farms-ConAgra agreement, Holly Farms
agreed to sell ConAgra certain prize assets if the proposed buyout
fell through. However, the agreement approved by the Holly Farms
board late Saturday night removed that provision, known as a
``lockup'' agreement.
   The newest offer is subject to approval by Holly Farms
shareholders. Holly Farms vice president Ted Bailey said the
company hoped to have another shareholder vote by the end of July.
   Bailey said the new agreement also allows Holly Farms to
terminate the deal if it receives a higher offer. Holly Farms
agreed to pay ConAgra a fee of $15 million plus actual expenses if
the latest agreement falls through.
</TEXT>
