<DOCNO> AP890522-0350 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1903EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     05-22 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0570</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surge in the dollar and an improved outlook
for inflation propelled bond prices sharply higher and drove
interest rates downward Monday.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond was up 13-16 point, or
nearly $12 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield fell to 8.59
percent, the lowest closing yield since March 1988, and was down
from 8.70 percent on Friday. Bond prices and yields move in
opposite directions.
   The dollar broke an important psychological barrier, 2 West
German marks, and hit a 1{-year high against the Japanese yen
despite repeated intervention by central banks and a plea from the
White House to depress the U.S. currency.
   The dollar's surge helped spark a sharp drop in commodity
prices, and that in turn increased bond traders' hopes that
inflation would slow down and the economy would cool off, analysts
said.
   When the economy is slow, the Federal Reserve Board is less
likely to tighten credit, which raises interest rates and sends
bond prices lower.
   Mitchell Held, chief financial economist with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co., said money that had flowed out of bonds as
interest rates rose was changing direction and moving back into
Treasury securities.
   ``People are realizng the economy is slowing down,'' he said.
``People are underinvested in bonds.''
   Ward McCarthy, a managing director of Stone &amp; McCarthy Research
Associates Inc., a money market research firm, said he expected
bond prices to continue to move higher because ``There's a lot of
people who want to get on the bandwagon.''
   ``We've probably seen the high (interest) rates for this
business cycle,'' he said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments were up between 3-16 point and 5-16 point,
intermediate maturities were up between ] point and 13-16 point and
long-term issues advanced ~ point, according to Telerate Inc., the
financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, jumped 6.40 to 1,154.97.
   In corporate trading, industrials also were higher. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return
on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, gained 1.86 to 314.01.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 13-32 point. The average yield to
maturity fell to 7.41 percent from 7.44 percent late Friday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, slipped to 8.60
percent as the discount fell 3 basis points to 8.32 percent. Yields
on six-month bills dropped to 8.76 percent as the discount fell 7
basis points to 8.30 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.76
as the discount declined 9 basis points to 8.13 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was 911-16 percent, up from 9| percent on Friday.
</TEXT>
