<HEAD>Interco To Sell Furnisher for About $388 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc. said Monday it has agreed to sell
furniture dealer Ethan Allen Inc. to Green Mountain Holding Corp.
for about $388 million in the latest part of its restructuring.
   Green Mountain is a new company formed by senior Ethan Allen
managers and outside investors led by Castle Harlan Inc.
   Officials said Ethan Allen dealers and the Ethan Allen employees
profit sharing plan will invest in the transaction.
   In addition to the sale price, Interco said it will receive
warrants to purchase up to 8 percent of the common stock of the new
corporation during a five-year period.
   The sale is part of the Interco's restructuring program, which
it adopted last year to defend against a hostile takeover attempt.
   In December, the company sold Londontown Corp. to Elderberg
Acquisition Corp. for $178 million and earlier this month it
announced a definitive agreement to sell its Central Hardware Co.
subsidiary to an entity formed by Salomon Brothers Holding Co. for
about $245 million.
   Interco said it would retain its Converse and Florsheim footwear
manufacturers and Browyhill and Lane furniture and home furnishers
as its four core businesses.
   In the Ethan Allen deal, senior debt is being provided by
Chemical Bank and subordinated debt is being provided by Kidder
Peabody Group Inc. and Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   The deal includes $357 million in cash, real estate assets and
the assumption by the purchaser of about $23.5 million in existing
debt and capitalized leases.
