<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;Ls-Seidman     05-22 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Seidman,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seidman Says Tough Measures Needed To Solve S&amp;L Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Condominiums, shopping malls and office buildings
may go on the block as the government disposes of assets from
failing savings and loans, Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman
L. William Seidman said Monday.
   The agency eventually could control between $300 billion and
$500 billion in failing thrifts' assets and sell off between $50
billion and $100 billion in non-performing assets, such as
repossessed property, Seidman said.
   The Bush administration has proposed creating the Resolution
Trust Corp. as part of its $157 billion S&amp;L bailout plan, he said.
   ``It (RTC) will be in the sole business of restructuring all
those S&amp;Ls,'' Seidman told reporters before addressing the Economic
Club of Detroit. ``That means it will probably have to restructure
the institutions so the private sector can buy them.''
   Taxpayers will pay most of the cost of the bailout plan, which
involves closing or merging more than 500 failed institutions.
   ``What the government did was hand its credit card to a bunch of
institutions and said, `Here, you can borrow on our credit' _
that's what deposit insurance is,'' he said. ``Now that the people
who lent them the money want the money back, the government either
pays it or the deposit insurance system fails.
   ``Since the government can't allow the deposit insurance system
to fail, the taxpayers will have to pay.''
   Under the plan introduced in February, 219 insolvent S&amp;Ls have
been placed under FDIC conservatorship and another 60 have been
targeted for takeover by the agency, which will guarantee
depositors' assets.
</TEXT>
