<FIRST>r f AM-GMAppointments     05-22 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM Appointments,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Motors Moves 3 Executives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. on Monday announced three
executive appointments, including two new general managers of
car-making divisions.
   Oldsmobile General Manager William W. Lane will become GM's vice
president for dealer and customer network development, a new
position, until his planned retirement early next year, GM Chairman
Roger Smith said.
   Lane will be succeeded as head of the Oldsmobile Division by J.
Michael Losh, general manager of the company's Pontiac Division.
Succeeding Losh will be John G. Middlebrook, now GM's vice
president for marketing and the product planning staff.
   The appointments are effective June 1, and a successor to
Middlebrook will be announced later, the company said.
   Pontiac generally is seen as the performance-oriented division
of the nation's largest automaker. Oldsmobile has had a reputation
of an upscale, conservative line of cars and GM recently has been
loading its cars with a wide variety of technical and electronic
developments.
   Lane, 59, who has headed the Oldsmobile Division since 1985,
started with the corporation in 1953 as a clerk in Oldsmobile's
Chicago office. He worked mainly in sales in the Oldsmobile and
Pontiac divisions.
   Losh, 43, has been head of the Pontiac Division since 1984.
Before that, he worked in GM's treasurer's office and at GM
affiliates in Mexico and Brazil.
   Middlebrook, 48, was named to his current post in 1987 after
working in product planning and sales jobs in the corporation.
</TEXT>
