<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     05-22 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Opens Sharply Higher, Share Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened sharply higher against the
Japanese yen Tuesday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange plunged.
   The dollar started trading at 142.05 yen, up 1.60 yen from
Monday's close of 140.45 yen. It was the highest opening since Oct.
27, 1987, when the currency opened at 142.10 yen.
   Traders said the currency's jump in Tokyo followed its overnight
gain in New York.
   ``The dollar started remarkably higher but trading is quiet
right now,'' said a trader with the Bank of Tokyo. ``Buying and
selling of the currency has been mixed so far in Tokyo.''
   He said speculative investors' dollar-buying has resulted in the
U.S. unit's recent surge.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly intervened in the market to halt
the dollar's further rise. The central bank does not inform the
public of its monetary activities.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which gained 65.9 points the previous day, quickly lost
319.99 points, or 0.94 percent, to fall to 33,747.87 within the
first 15 minutes of morning trading.
   Dealers said prices were lower almost across the board.
   An analyst at Nomura Securities said the plunge was largely due
to the yen's sharp drop.
   Other dealers said expectations for the possible official
discount rate hike by the Bank of Japan also discouraged market
players.
   Market analysts and media reports have speculated that the bank
will raise the rate soon, in part to combat the U.S. dollar's
excessive rise against the yen. The central bank has made no
official announcements.
</TEXT>
