<FIRST>r f BC-Delta-Expansion     05-22 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Delta-Expansion,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta Plans Expanded Fleet, More Overseas Service by 2000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines will spend about $12 billion to
expand its fleet and increase overseas markets by the year 2000,
the company's chief executive officer said Monday.
   Delta plans to add more than 300 planes to its active fleet of
396 planes, Hollis L. Harris told a travel industry conference.
   Harris said most of Delta's planned expansion is in the European
and Pacific markets and is needed because of expected increases in
air travel.
   The Federal Aviation Administration predicts that by 2000, the
number of air passengers will increase to 761 million annually from
455 million in 1988.
   Harris said the Eastern Airlines strike has helped Atlanta-based
Delta but has had a mixed effect on the airline industry.
   He said he empathizes with Eastern workers but would like to see
the reorganization plan by Texas Air Corp., Eastern's parent, work
so the strikers could regain their jobs.
</TEXT>
