<DOCNO> AP890522-0359 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 2323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GasMeeting 1stLd-Writethru f0153 05-22 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gas Meeting, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0153,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Company Exec Says Oil Spill Was Catalyst For Higher Gas Prices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with oil company executive saying
spill was catalyst for gas price rises, CLARIFY that economist was talking
about effect of the loss of oil from the spill, sted spill itself; picks
up 6th graf, `Attorneys general ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil company executive said Monday the
Exxon Valdez oil spill was the catalyst for gasoline price
increases around the country that would have occurred anyway by
mid-summer.
   With worldwide oil production down and crude oil prices up since
November, gasoline prices in the United States were bound to go up,
said Tom Burns, manager of the economic department of Chevron USA.
   Since the first of the year, retail markets had been resisting
upward pressure on gasoline prices, Burns said.
   However, he said, the ``massive uncertainty'' surrounding the
continued flow of oil from Alaska after the Exxon Valdez ran
aground March 24 in Prince William Sound opened the way for price
increases.
   Burns was one of several oil executives who attended a meeting
of top justice officials from seven states and representatives of
Chevron and Mobil Oil called by Oregon Attorney General Dave
Frohnmayer.
   Earlier Monday, an economist said the loss of the oil from the
Exxon Valdez could not be blamed for rising gasoline prices because
West Cost refineries kept up production despite a brief drop in
crude oil shipments from Alaska.
   ``It did not have the impact in the production of gasoline,''
Keith Leffler of the University of Washington said.
   Leffler said his research indicated gasoline price increases
were linked to rising ``refinery margins,'' or increases in the
difference between the prices refineries pay for crude oil and the
prices they charge for finished products.
   Other oil companies were invited to the meeting. Shell Oil,
Atlantic-Richfield and Exxon, whose Exxon Valdez tanker caused the
spill, agreed to private meetings later in the week at Frohnmayer's
office in Salem.
   Attorneys general from Washington, Oregon, Idaho and North
Dakota attended the meeting, along with top deputy attorneys
general from California, Alaska and Indiana.
   The meeting preceded the summer driving season, which begins
this weekend.
   Leffler was hired by Oregon and other Western states to analyze
gasoline price increases after prices shot up between mid-March and
mid-April by an average of 20.1 cents in Portland, 16.9 cents in
Seattle and 18.6 cents in Boise, Idaho.
   The tanker spilled 10.9 million gallons of crude oil, and
restrictions imposed by the U.S. Coast Guard curtailed shipments of
Alaskan crude oil for nearly two weeks afterwards.
   However, Leffler said, despite the ``loss'' or late delivery of
546 million gallons of crude, gasoline production remained steady,
with only a slight dip in the week after the accident.
   The economist said crude oil prices and retail gasoline prices
both jumped right after the accident. Uncertainty over how the
spill would affect supplies of crude oil probably was behind the
increases, Leffler said.
   Crude oil prices then dropped as the international oil market
adjusted to the dip in Alaskan supplies, Leffler said. Dealer
margins, up right after the spill, also dropped, but the price of
gasoline kept going up, he said.
   What went up, and did not come back down, were the refinery
margins, Leffler said.
   In the midst of ``massive uncertainty'' over whether gasoline
supplies would fall, Leffler said, refineries were able to increase
their margins.
   ``You and I see that reflected in the price we pay at the
pump,'' he said.
   Leffler told the state officials that he was unable to say
whether the refinery margins, which still were going up six weeks
after the spill, were justified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
